<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0765 10-10 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0765,0749</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Gampell and Alexander; AMs separates moved as a0689 on
Adams, a0671 on Gottlieb and a0694 on Harper. Gottlieb moved on the
business wire and Croudip moved on the sports wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Samuel Adams</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRAFFORD, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Samuel A. Adams, a CIA analyst whose
accusations about intelligence estimates during the Vietnam War
formed the basis for a CBS documentary that prompted a celebrated
libel suit, died Monday of an apparent heart attack. He was 55.
   Adams, who joined the CIA in 1963, was an expert on the Viet
Cong, the guerrilla force North Vietnam organized in South Vietnam.
He contended that Army General William Westmoreland's military
intelligence officers had been ordered to underestimate the
strength of the guerrilla force to make it appear the
American-backed war was being won.
   The dispute over the Viet Cong strength was a major controversy
at the CIA, where Adams worked for 10 years. Adams contended the
CIA director, Richard Helms, also knew Westmoreland had rigged Viet
Cong battle statistics.
   The Adams controversy was the foundation for the CBS
documentary, ``The Uncounted Enemy: A Vietnam Deception,'' which
resulted in a libel suit against the network by Westmoreland. The
general settled the case out of court after hearing testimony by
his former chief of military intelligence that confirmed charges
made by Adams.
   His account of the Vietnam controversy is contained in a book,
``Who the Hell Are We Fighting Out There?'' which he was completing
at the time of his death and which is to be published by W.W.
Norton in New York.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Alex Gottlieb</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alex Gottlieb, a TV producer who staged such
programs as ``The Bob Hope Chrysler Theater,'' ``The Donna Reed
Show'' and ``The Smothers Brothers Show,'' died Sunday of a
cerebral hemorrhage. He was 81.
   Gottlieb, who produced more than 50 television shows during a
career that spanned four decades, also wrote several film scripts
and Broadway plays.
   His film credits include ``I'll Take Sweden,'' ``Susan Slept
Here,'' ``Macho'' and ``Hollywood Canteen.'' He also wrote the
stage version of ``Susan Slept Here,'' ``Separate Rooms,'' ``Two
For The Money'' and ``Your Place Or Mine?''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Iva McConnell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iva McConnell Harper, the mother of actress
Valerie Harper, died Friday of cancer. She was 71.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>David Croudip</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Croudip, 29, captain of the Atlanta
Falcons' special teams, died Monday. A medical examiner said a
preliminary examination indicates cocaine was in the system of the
NFL cornerback.
   Croudip attended San Diego State before joining the Los Angeles
Express of the United States Football League. He later played with
the USFL's Houston Gamblers and was picked up by the NFL's Los
Angeles Rams in 1984.
   After being cut by the Rams, he played two games for the San
Diego Chargers in 1985 before being cut and signed by the Falcons.
He was a reserve cornerback.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ralph Gampell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Gampell, a British-born
physician-turned-lawyer who became the top administrator of the
California court system under Chief Justice Rose Bird, died Oct. 3
of cancer. He was 71.
   Gampell practiced medicine for 17 years, five in England and 12
in the United States, where he emigrated in 1949. While working as
a doctor, he attended Stanford Law School, passed the bar and began
a 17-year law practice in San Jose.
   Elected president of the State Bar in 1976, Gampell was in
office when the bar formally evaluated Gov. Edmund Brown Jr.'s
controversial nomination of Bird as chief justice in 1977.
   After taking office, Bird asked Gampell to become administrative
director of the courts. The director manages the staff and lobbies
the Legislature for the Judicial Council, which makes policies for
state courts at all levels.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Elmer Alexander</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elmer ``Mousey'' Alexander, a drummer and
veteran of the bands of jazz greats Benny Goodman and Zoot Sims,
died Sunday at age 66.
   A purist who dismissed contemporary jazz-rock fusion, Alexander
promoted concerts by traditional jazz musicians at Central Florida
nightclubs. He performed regularly in the months before his death
and hoped to record with a trio he had recently formed with bassist
Ron Miller and pianist Joe Piscatelli.
   He also played with singer Billie Holiday, trumpeter Sy Oliver,
the Clark Terry Big Band and Doc Severinsen's Tonight Show band.
</TEXT>
