<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0003EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PaisleyConflict     10-10 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paisley Conflict,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Figure In Pentagon Procurement Scandal Contacted Boeing Despite
Pledge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key figure in the Pentagon procurement
scandal violated a conflict-of-interest pledge not to associate
with his previous employer Boeing Co. while working at the
Pentagon, it was reported.
   A Senate oversight subcommittee recently reviewed the records of
a 1983 criminal investigation of possible conflicts of interest by
Melvyn R. Paisley in his dealings with Boeing Co., questioning
Pentagon lawyers at a recent unpublicized hearing. The subcommittee
made available records of the hearings to the Los Angeles Times.
   The subcommittee said Paisley, the former assistant Navy
secretary, urged government officials days after meeting with the
president of Boeing's helicopter unit to speed the development of a
tilt-rotor helicopter on which Boeing was the eventual winning
bidder, Senate investigators told the Times on Friday.
   Paisley, once the Navy's most powerful procurement official,
also recommended several top Boeing executives for positions on
sensitive Pentagon advisory boards during times he had disqualified
himself from dealings with the firm, the subcommittee said.
   Among them was James E. Gaines, who later became a deputy
assistant Navy secretary.
   Paisley's attorney, E. Lawrence Barcella Jr., said it was
appropriate for Paisley to recommend Boeing officials for service
as Pentagon advisers.
   ``The fact he had previously been employed by Boeing certainly
should not prohibit one of the country's major defense contractors
from participating in naval advisory boards,'' Barcella said.
   Gaines and Paisley are under investigation in Operation Ill
Wind, the far-ranging probe of Pentagon procurement expected to
result in indictments within a month, federal agents said.
   Paisley joined the Pentagon in 1981 after a 27-year career at
Boeing.
   Investigators are trying to determine whether Paisley received
payments from military contractors while serving as assistant Navy
secretary and whether he improperly obtained confidential Pentagon
data after he left the Pentagon in 1987 to become a defense
consultant.
   Sen. Carl M. Levin, D-Mich., chairman of the oversight
subcommittee, told Pentagon lawyers he was deeply disturbed by the
disclosures of Paisley's dealings with Boeing, according to a
transcript of the Sept. 29 hearing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
