<DOCNO> AP881010-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MiniatureKingdom     10-10 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Miniature Kingdom,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Visitors `Experience' Buildings At Miniature Kingdom</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE MADER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She lives in a white castle-shaped
building with a room full of miniature European castles, cathedrals
and houses surrounded by tiny brass cars and hand-painted people.
   Trudy Thuijs' late husband, Arthur, constructed the 45 buildings
on a scale of { inch per foot.
   With a Strauss waltz playing in the background, visitors walk
around the black-painted room and its islands of tiny buildings
encircled by moving trains.
   The Miniature Kingdom has a replica of the Castle Neuschwanstein
in Fussen, Germany; the Kremlin and Red Square in Moscow; and a
hotel on the Riviera with a beach covered by umbrellas and chairs.
The Cathedral of the Assumption of the Holy Virgin recreates the
original 1479 building in Moscow down to the domes gilded with real
gold and silver.
   ``To me, these buildings are works of art. It's a view of
architecture and time's past,'' said Mrs. Thuijs, 48. ``You can't
experience it (the real building) the way you could here.''
   Miniature Kingdom is one of five tiny villages researched,
designed and built by her husband, a native of Holland who died in
1984. He sold the others located in The Hague, Holland; Lake
Lugano, Switzerland; Klagenfurt, Austria; and Dusseldorf, West
Germany.
   Thuijs started crafting miniatures in the 1950s after years of
designing hotels, restaurants and government buildings in Europe.
   He built the Miniature Kingdom buildings in Holland, and was
persuaded to move them to the Great Adventure theme park near
Jackson in 1974 by the park's builder, Warner Leroy, according to
Mrs. Thuijs.
   She met her husband while working at Great Adventure, where the
miniature buildings were kept outdoors.
   Eventually, the couple looked for an indoor home for the display
and a place to retire. They chose Washington, a rural northern New
Jersey community about 15 miles east of the Pennsylvania border.
   Mrs. Thuijs said the exhibit was valued at $550,000 when built
in the 1960s and now is worth more than $1 million. But she has no
plans to sell Miniature Kingdom.
   Each building, made of Swedish masonite to withstand the
weather, took three to six months to build. Thuijs spent 1{ years
working on the Castle Neuschwanstein, patterned after its 1869
German namesake constructed for King Ludwig II of Bavaria.
   The castle and the Georgian House _ a model of a 1710 London
mansion _ are among Mrs. Thuijs' favorites.
   ``I tend to the more ornate buildings,'' she said.
   She thinks her husband chose the buildings he re-created because
he had seen them during his travels in Belgium, Holland, Germany,
the Soviet Union, Poland, England and Switzerland.
   Only one miniature scene is out of place among those of Europe:
New York Harbor.
   ``It was the first step in what was going to be a very expanded
miniature village at Great Adventure,'' Mrs. Thuijs said. ``He was
to create another set of miniatures, but because of financial
problems (at the theme park) he didn't continue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
