<DOCNO> AP881010-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RaceTrackChaplain     10-10 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Race Track Chaplain,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chaplain Ministers At Horse Race Track</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLLINSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Barry Harris admits he
sometimes gets the itch to play the horses. And it's a difficult
urge to avoid working around 1,100 of them on the ``back side'' at
Fairmount Park Race Track.
   Harris began ministering to the ``nomadic'' peoples on the back
side _ the area behind the grandstand where horses train and
trainers sleep _ in May 1985.
   ``I had the feeling that some of my brother ministers treated me
with some suspicion, and were a bit cool toward me,'' the Southern
baptist said, recalling his start.
   ``Just for the simple fact that I'm here where betting, gambling
takes place. I just figured it wasn't my job to judge, but to
minister.''
   Thrice weekly, starting at 8 a.m., Harris broadcasts an
``economical'' prayer and devotional message over the
public-address system to the track's 1,500 workers.
   He then strolls around to the stables, meeting members of the
horse-racing industry, including jockeys, horse owners and trainers.
   The 44-year-old Harris, born in nearby East St. Louis, says
people seek his counsel for many reasons, including problems with
relationships, health or downright boredom.
   ``Whatever turns up, that's what I'll deal with,'' said the
silver-haired reverend, wearing brown leather boots, faded blue
jeans, a crisp white shirt, a gray-blue-and-brown tie and a
cream-colored jacket.
   ``That's where I find out about the wedding that's being
planned. I did one in the winner's circle,'' he recalled, laughing.
The groom was a jockey.
   Harris, who also works at the track two evenings weekly, holds a
Bible study Tuesdays in the Horsemen's Lounge. On Thursdays, before
racing starts, he has a devotional service for the jockeys.
   He says people who work the back side, which at Fairmount
shelters about 1,100 horses, need a chaplain because their
migratory life doesn't permit them to put down roots.
   ``They're a nomadic people,'' he said. ``They're not plugged
into the community where they are.''
   Harris said it wasn't that he dreamed of growing up to become a
track chaplain. He never gave it much thought, really, though his
father, a steel worker, traded horses part time.
   He graduated from a Belleville high school in 1961, got married
and started working on the railroad. Then around age 24, in search
of another career, Harris entered the ministry.
   While serving as pastor at Highland Southern Baptist Church,
Harris sought to supplement his church's income to finance a
building expansion in 1985. The track job came open and he took it,
replacing another Southern Baptist minister.
   The job has existed since 1979, supported by the Horsemen's
Benevolent and Protective Association.
   ``I love it here,'' Harris said. ``Yeah, you get the urge every
once in a while'' to bet. ``But it's not in my game.''
   He doesn't try to justify the legalized betting at the track,
which Southern Baptists don't look kindly upon. ``It's not there
for me to approve or disapprove,'' he said. ``It's there.
   ``I am not God. I cannot stop these things. I am here to
administer to persons.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
