<1ST_LINE>u i PM-TradeBridge Bjt   10-10 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade Bridge, Bjt,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Boom Filtering Down to Agricultural Hamlet</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBIA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This agricultural hamlet of 350 people
on the banks of the Rio Grande has languished for decades, but
residents say a planned bridge to Texas to handle Mexico's booming
trade will spark change.
   But nearby towns already with bridges spanning the border are
concerned they may lose business.
   One is hedging its bets: it's helping finance construction of
Colombia's bridge to make money off the tolls.
   ``We need industries to come for our youth,'' said farmer
Tiburcio Tapia Lopez, born in Colombia in 1910. ``This town needs
some life.''
   Tapia and Colombia's 93 other communal farmers barely eke out a
living on the sorghum and corn they sell at market. He and his wife
Yolanda have nine children, all but one of whom went to other
Mexican cities or to the United States to work.
   Eloy Cantu, Nuevo Leon state secretary for development and
planning, said the bridge linking Colombia with a private tract of
land near an unincorporated site called Dolores, Texas, could be
under construction as soon as February.
   Cantu said the bridge will offer the most streamlined customs
operation along the nearly 2,000-mile border and may include
``shared customs'' so cargo trucks are checked by American and
Mexican officials simultaneously.
   ``It'll be a showcase,'' Cantu said in an interview in the state
capital of Monterrey, northern Mexico's largest and most
industrialized city.
   Nuevo Leon is the only U.S.-Mexico border state without an
international bridge, Cantu said.
   Mexico, in a severe economic crisis since 1982, joined the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, or GATT, two years ago. The
move lowered import duties on hundreds of foreign products and for
the first time made exports of manufactured goods a No. 1 priority.
   Joining GATT was a sign the country is trying to reduce its
reliance on petroleum export revenues, which plummeted with the
price of oil from $14.7 billion in 1983 to $7.8 billion last year.
   Exports of manufactured goods, meanwhile, soared by 116 percent
during the 5-year period from 1983 to 1987.
   Total manufactured exports in 1987 hit $9.9 billion, according
to Banco de Mexico figures.
   In the first six months of this year, manufactured exports were
up by 23 percent over the same period last year, according to the
Industry and Commerce Department.
   Now there's talk of building or improving international bridges
all along the border to handle the unending streams of 18-wheel
cargo trucks that go back and forth from Mexico to the United
States.
   Tapia said Colombia had a short heyday in his youth when his
father operated a ferry that carried Mexican workers to the coal
mines at Dolores and brought supplies from the United Statess.
   ``That ended about 1925,'' he said. ``Since then there's been no
work here.''
   Nuevo Leon still has to make major road improvements to
Colombia, build customs houses and upgrade water and electricity
systems.
   But while Colombia is rejoicing, the twin cities of Nuevo Laredo
in Tamaulipas state and Laredo, Texas, just 24 miles downstream,
are concerned.
   Laredo, which will pay half the estimated $1 million cost of the
bridge and earn toll revenues from it, would fare the best,
although City Managuer Marvin Townsend said Laredo will fight any
attempts to build a road bypassing it on the Texas side.
   Both cities earn millions on the truck trade through bridge
tolls, customs brokers, trucking companies, motels, restaurants,
banks, insurance companies and government offices that monitor the
industry.
   Both Laredos agree another bridge is needed. But they had hoped
a third one would be built there first.
   ``Nuevo Laredo's main source of income is international trade,''
said Sergio Lujan, vice president of the Nuevo Laredo Association
of Customs Agents.
   ``My colleagues are very, very concerned about the competition.
They fear Nuevo Leon will try to sponsor its own border town and
make it grow,'' he said.
   Cantu said limited development is planned in Colombia and that
the state's main goal is to slow growth in the sprawling,
water-short Monterrey by encouraging growth in Anahuac, a city of
about 30,000 people 40 miles south of Colombia.
</TEXT>
