<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusinessOutlook     10-10 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Outlook,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Executives Looking for Economic Slowdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One year after the stock market crash,
America's business leaders are looking back on a year of
surprisingly strong growth and ahead to what in some ways would be
a welcome slowdown.
   Economists widely expected the economy to topple into a
recession this year or at best into a period of sluggishness.
Instead, business has been good and many of the executives gathered
last weekend for the semiannual meeting of the Business Council
sounded like Roger B. Smith, chairman of General Motors Corp.
   ``The U.S. auto industry is just finishing their 1988 model
year, which needless to say was a very, very good year for us,''
said Smith, who in 1989 and 1990 will serve as chairman of the
council, composed of 62 chief executives from the country's biggest
corporations.
   A panel of about 20 economists from member companies is
predicting growth this year, as measured by the gross national
product, of 4 percent. If realized, that would be the best since
1984.
   However, economic growth will slow to 2.5 percent next year and
to below 2 percent in 1990, the panel predicted. They've been
making a similar prediction for two years now.
   Citicorp Chairman John S. Reed, who delivers the council's
economic report, said that once again the group's consultants
``suggest that next year things will begin to slow down a little
bit.''
   Even another year of unexpected growth would only ``put off for
another year the expected slowdown,'' he said.
   But if the economists undershoot again, the implications could
be grim.
   The Federal Reserve Board has been pushing up interest rates in
an attempt to fight inflation by curbing growth.
   If the Fed doesn't see the ``soft landing'' it desires, it may
force rates still higher, precipitating an actual contraction of
the economy, a recession, instead of just sluggishness.
   So, when Reed was asked how he could describe a prediction of a
slowdown as optimistic, he replied, ``There is nothing called a
recession in this forecast.''
   The area of the economy expected to slow the most, according to
the economic panel, is consumer demand and the executives are
tailoring their plans to that expectation.
   Smith predicted a ``rationalization of capacity'' in the auto
industry over the next few years, meaning outdated plants will be
closed and, perhaps, jobs lost.
   Philip M. Hawley, chairman of Carter Hawley Hale Stores Inc., a
department store chain, said retailers are expecting only
``reasonably moderate growth'' in holiday sales.
   If growth in consumer spending was more vigorous, as it was in
1982-86, that would have ``long-range implications for the economy
that were not good,'' including higher imports at a time when the
United States is trying to shrink its trade deficit.
   In between rounds of golf and sets of tennis at the Homestead, a
posh resort in the mountains of western Virginia, the executives
met behind closed doors to hear from politicians and experts on two
subjects: education and the federal budget deficit. The news was
not good.
   Albert Shanker, president of the American Federation of
Teachers, said only 15 to 20 percent of the nation's children are
receiving an adequate education.
   Yet, according to Ernest L. Boyer, president of the Carnegie
Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching and a former U.S.
commissioner of education in the Carter administration, neither of
the presidential candidates has put forward a coherent education
program.
   There's been ``a strange silence,'' he said.
   Robert S. Strauss, co-chairman of a high-level government
commission working on a budget deficit reduction plan for the next
president, said he is of ``reasonably good cheer'' about the
prospects of proposing a ``constructive and worthwhile'' solution.
   But Strauss and his fellow co-chairman, former Reagan
administration Transportation Secretary Drew Lewis, said their
recommendation would fail without the support of the next president.
   Republican candidate George Bush has already said he will ignore
the recommendation if it includes a tax increase. Democrat Michael
Dukakis' chief revenue-raising proposal is more efficient tax
collection. Neither candidate has proposed substantial spending
cuts.
   ``Without support from the White House ... Congress isn't going
to fall on its sword to please our commission,'' Lewis said.
``There's got to be a joint effort here.''
</TEXT>
