<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dispiritof'88 Bjt   10-10 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dispirit of '88, Bjt,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Sounds of '88: `Trivial, Superficial and Inane'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The other day Darleen Reilly picked up the
phone and called a local radio station to play a game it calls
``Name That Sound.'' She correctly identified a ``rack being rolled
into the dishwasher,'' and came away $4,000 richer.
   Then the disc jockeys turned to politics.
   One of them described the irony of Lloyd Bentsen and Dan Quayle
_ ``these two millionaires,'' he said derisively _ sharing a stage
in Omaha to discuss all the good things they would do for the
common man.
   It was a cynical moment, but the presidential campaigns have
invited this sort of contempt. From the moment the conventions
ended in August, it's been a dispiriting race. It began trivial,
quickly turned negative, and now it's gotten worse.
   George Bush generally gets the blame for touching off the
trivia. Budget deficits are enormous, a drug epidemic has hit
practically every strata of society, superpower relations at a
turning point, farmers coming off another tough year, nine
Americans remain hostage in Lebanon ...
   With all this facing the next president, Bush has been
bludgeoning Dukakis over the Pledge of Allegiance and a
Massachusetts prison furlough program. He initiated a made-for-TV
battle of cop endorsements and summoned reporters to Boston Harbor
to ridicule Dukakis over its filth _ while refusing to answer
questions about administration environmental vetoes.
   It got so bad that Richard Nixon, of all people, described
campaign '88 as ``trivial, superficial and inane.'' Nixon said Bush
and Dukakis ``have found that the surest way they could make the
evening news was to be silly or irresponsible or both.''
   Barry Goldwater, summoned for an Arizona campaign appearance,
startled Quayle by telling his fellow Republican: ``I hope you'll
take this kindly. But I want you to go back and tell George Bush to
start talking about the issues.''
   Don't hold your breath. Trivializing is working for Bush: He's
come from behind to enjoy a comfy lead in the polls and he
continues to put Dukakis on the defensive on these ``gut issues''
(Dukakis finally answered on Saturday after a week of Bush abuse on
crime policy).
   Behind in the polls, the Dukakis people figured they better
answer in kind. They saw that voters seemed to respond to the
negative campaign and though it would be nice to get off the
defensive for a change.
   Dukakis had been delivering some issue-oriented speeches on
defense, health insurance, college education, but now the high road
would take a back seat to a new series of starkly negative campaign
ads.
   No sooner did the millionaires' debate end then Dukakis hit the
air with some anti-Quayle commercials.
   A spot called ``Oval Office'' features scenes of Harry Truman,
Lyndon Johnson and Gerald Ford taking their presidential oaths as a
narrator says one in five vice presidents has had to rise to the
presidency.
   ``For this job, after five months of reflection, George Bush
made his personal choice _ J. Danforth Quayle,'' the ad says.
``Hopefully, we will never know how great a lapse of judgment that
really was.''
   The Bush campaign, meanwhile, is airing tough ads criticizing
Dukakis' prison furlough program, tax hikes and other aspects of
his record as Massachusetts governor _ spending about $4 million
last week alone.
   The victim of one furloughed inmate flew to California last week
to cut some radio ads for Bush. What the ads won't say is that
President Reagan, as governor of California, supported furloughs
even after two convicts killed people while on furlough in the
early 1970s. And Reagan raised taxes when he had too, just as he
did as president.
   One of these days _ maybe tomorrow! _ the campaign may focus for
a minute on something like strategic doctrine or Central American
policy or a real war, not a phony war, on drugs. But unless there
is a sudden sea change in the tenor of campaign '88, millions of
registered voters are going to wake up on Nov. 8 scratching their
heads and asking, where do these guys stand?
   ``What are the issues so far,'' wonders a perplexed New York
Gov. Mario Cuomo. ``Pledge of Allegiance, furloughs, death penalty.
Are you kidding?''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Jonathan Wolman is AP's assistant bureau chief in
Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
