<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignContrasts     10-10 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Contrasts,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Differences Abound: Air Force Two Vs. `Sky Pig'; Airline Vs.
Military Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the presidential race were to go to the
candidate with the fastest plane, Republican George Bush would
leave Democrat Michael Dukakis in his jetstream.
   One only need to hear the nickname of the Dukakis plane _ ``Sky
Pig'' _ to get the general idea.
   The name comes partly from the bloated look of the aircraft, a
stubby 20-year-old Boeing 737, but mostly the description is based
on flying time: It takes the plane seven hours to cross the country
_ a 4{-hour flight on most commercial airlines.
   Method of travel is just one of many contrasts of day-to-day
life on the campaign trail for the two men who would be president.
   Because he's the vice president, Bush gets to draw from a fleet
of fast Air Force planes hangared at Andrews Air Force Base near
Washington.
   As any plane the president flies automatically becomes ``Air
Force One,'' whatever plane Bush is on becomes ``Air Force Two.''
Usually a converted Boeing 707 or a McDonnell-Douglas DC-9, Bush's
planes are fast, meticulously cared for and flown by Air Force
pilots.
   Bush's campaign reimburses taxpayers, in part, for the use of
the plane, which is blue and white with the words ``The United
States of America'' emblazoned across the sides.
   Dukakis' plane, chartered from Presidential Airlines, is the
same aircraft that Bush's former rival, Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, used.
Designed for short-range flying, ``Sky Pig'' cannot cross the
country without one or more refueling stops.
   That was fine for the kind of campaigning Dole did during the
GOP primaries _ after all, Dole used to joke that he'd fly over a
state and direct the pilot to land wherever he spotted a crowd _
but it poses some scheduling problems in the final weeks of a
national campaign.
   Aides to Dukakis, however, say the candidate is comfortable with
the plane, likes the ``Presidential'' designation on the side in
green letters, and has no plans to trade it in for a sleeker model.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   One reason Dukakis may like the plane is food.
   He has been known to eat with delight meals that aides and
reporters flying with him have pronounced indigestible. The airline
also stocks plenty of raisin bran and milk, the Massachusetts
governor's favorite breakfast.
   Bush, by comparison, smothers nearly everything he eats on the
plane _ ranging from pork rinds and taco salads to tuna fish
sandwiches _ with hot red pepper sauce. But then, the usual
offering on Air Force Two is bland military fare, served by
government employees.
   When possible, Bush treats plane meals as snacks, or skips them
altogether, saving most of his appetite for large meals in
restaurants.
   Bush usually hits a restaurant unannounced, then mingles with
the other patrons for some impromptu campaigning. Dukakis, by
contrast, seldom eats in restaurants while on the campaign trail.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Both candidates travel with an entourage of aides, Secret
Service agents and reporters.
   But Air Force Two has room for only a small ``pool'' of six to
nine representatives of the news media; the rest of the traveling
press corps is put on one, and sometimes two, press planes.
   Dukakis' plane has more seats for members of the news media _
about 30 _ but there is also a backup plane for camera crews and
reporters unable to get seats on ``Sky Pig.''
   For a reporter, the main advantage of riding on Dukakis' backup
plane, a Boeing 727, is that it always gets there first. The main
advantage of riding on Bush's press plane: The food is better.
   Bush frequently comes back and chats with the small group of
reporters on his plane, sometimes inviting them up to his cabin for
drinks and informal chitchat.
   By contrast, Dukakis seldom speaks to the reporters or Secret
Service agents who travel with him.
   However, Dukakis aides are generally more plentiful and more
talkative.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Security for both candidates is tight, but Bush's motorcades are
longer. In addition to two bullet-proof black limousines, both
flown in on cargo planes in advance, Bush's motorcades routinely
have five or more vans for staff and special guests.
   By the time Secret Service vehicles and press vans and buses are
added, Bush motorcades can easily stretch for blocks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
