<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CyanideEvacuation     10-10 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyanide Evacuation,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Says More To Come For Town Of Nitro</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NITRO, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rusting cylinder of poison has been
destroyed, and the 3,500 residents who were cleared out are home.
But officials say more evacuations can be expected if new hazards
are found at an abandoned chemical plant.
   Residents within 1,000 yards of the plant were told to leave
their homes Sunday while the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency
blew up a tank of what it thought was hydrogen cyanide.
   As little as 50 milligrams of the chemical, or less than
one-sixth the weight of the average aspirin tablet, can kill.
   The evacuations took two hours, 2{ hours less than expected.
   ``There is a possibility, almost a certainty, that there will be
future evacuations here,'' said EPA spokesman Harold Yates.
   More than 3,400 drums and barrels _ most unidentified, rusting
or both _ were left behind in this Kanawha River town of 9,000 when
Artel Chemical Co. couldn't pay its workers and a federal judge
ordered the site closed in June.
   With the hydrogen cyanide cylinder blown up, the most pressing
problems now are a 9,000-gallon tank of methyl mercaptan, which is
toxic and highly flammable, and a bunker full of sodium, which
reacts violently upon contact with water.
   There could be surprises, too, as the cleanup continues at the
Superfund site, Yates said.
   ``We have found a number of incompatible materials stored in
close proximity,'' Yates said. ``It's a threat to public health.''
   Sunday's explosion occurred at 1:55 p.m., and a fire was started
to burn off the tank's contents. None of the gas was detected
downwind, but a cyanide monitor held directly over the burning
cylinder read 1 part per million, said Jerry Heston, the EPA's
on-site coordinator.
   ``There was no reason to think it was anything other than
hydrogen cyanide,'' Heston said, but added that more tests will be
done to find out.
   The EPA took over the plant and closed it after the federal
government declared it a threat to public health. Yates said the
cleanup could take years, and Mayor Don Karnes said future
cooperation could be limited.
   ``I'll tell people they should leave if they (the EPA) tell me
to, but I'm not sure they're going to go,'' Karnes said. ``They
made all this fuss about this and then it turned out to be almost
nothing.''
   Elmer Fike, who for 33 years operated Fike Chemical Co. _ now
Artel Chemical Co. _ said venting the poison to the atmosphere over
a 24- to 36-hour period would have eliminated the need to disrupt
so many people.
   ``I've told them other ways to taking care of this,'' Fike said
before the explosion. ``They're blowing this way out of
proportion.''
   But Heson said the EPA believed a controlled explosion of the
tank and its contents was the best solution.
   ``I'm not going to open the valve and see what it is,'' he said.
   The evacuation was scheduled to last from 12:20 p.m. to 5 p.m.
but the detonation went so smoothly that the all clear signal was
given 2{ hours early. Nearly everyone who was asked to leave did,
heading to nearby shopping malls or to relatives' homes rather than
the official evacuation center, where only 26 people went.
   The federal government built the town of Nitro in World War I to
manufacture explosives and munitions. There are now more than two
dozen chemical plants in a 12-mile stretch along the river that's
known as ``Chemical Valley.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881010-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghan-NewTactics Bjt   10-10 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan-New Tactics, Bjt,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kabul Government Adopting New Tactics In Struggle Against
Guerrillas</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet-style government is
changing its tactics against Moslem guerrillas in the battle for
power as Moscow's army withdraws.
   The government, dominated by a Communist Party that has been
trying to portray itself as the real defender of the Moslem faith,
is campaigning for international pressure to halt American and
Pakistani support for the guerrillas.
   Both the Soviet Union and the Afghan government have been
maneuvering for a negotiated settlement, rather than a military
showdown, although Moscow continues to arm the Kabul government.
   The guerrillas have also achieved some changes, such as the
ability to move weapons faster from Pakistan to the hills outside
Kabul. But they still lack the coordination for a significant new
strategy,.
   However, some Western diplomats believe the fierce Afghan winter
poses less of an obstacle to the guerrillas' ability to mount
attacks on Kabul than in the past.
   The withdrawal of about 50,000 Soviet soldiers this summer gave
the guerrillas greater control of roads and highways, especially
those leading from their supply bases in Pakistan to Kabul. This
means they are no longer restricted to taking circuitous routes
through mountains where winter snows often block the passes.
   The remaining Soviet soldiers, estimated at 50,000 to 55,000,
are to withdraw by Feb. 15 under an accord signed in Geneva last
April.
   The rebel's ``supply situation has improved vastly,'' a Western
diplomat said, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``A few years
ago they depended on camels, donkeys and horses. Now they're
depending on Mercedes-Benz trucks.''
   But the real test will be whether the rebels can mount a serious
enough siege of Kabul to curtail the city's fuel and food supplies
this winter.
   Already, sugar has virtually disappeared from the markets in
Kabul in the last week after key highways leading to the capital
were closed by the guerrillas.
   Residents also report a shortage of flour for bread, an Afghan
staple, and say the prices of basic foodstuffs have risen by 20
percent or more in the last two months.
   The April 14 Geneva agreement that provided for the Soviet
withdrawal was signed by the United States, the Soviet Union,
Pakistan and Afghanistan.
   Both Afghanistan and the Soviet Union have increasingly targeted
Pakistan as a violator of the accord in an effort to pressure
Pakistan to force the guerrillas to negotiate. In addition, the
death of Pakistan's President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq in August
deprived the guerrillas of their most ardent suppporter.
   So far, the rebels don't appear willing to negotiate.
   Foreign diplomats estimate the Soviets now have 35,000 men
defending Kabul and an additional 20,000 or more deployed outside
the capital.
   Washington has predicted the Afghan government and its armed
forces will collapse after the Soviets complete their withdrawal.
   The morale of the 40,000-man Afghan army is considered low, but
the army is not the backbone of the government's military strength.
   Its real clout, as one well-regarded Western analyst pointed
out, rests with three other forces that have a total of at least
100,000 men who are highly motivated and equipped with heavy armor,
field guns and aircraft. These are the Sarandoy, a paramilitary
force of 25,000, the 15,000-man secret police force known by the
afghan acronym of KHAD and 60,000 to 70,000 tribal militiamen paid
by Kabul.
   The rebel's strength has been variously estimated at between
40,000 and 200,000, but there is no clear indication how many are
full-time fighters or even inside Afghanistan instead of across the
border in Pakistan.
   More important, the analyst said, is that the biggest band of
guerrillas in any location numbers no more than 100 men and local
commanders have little contact with each other.
   The rank and file of Afghanistan's regular army is generally
regarded as little more than cannon fodder. Foreign diplomats and
Afghans said vacancies caused by desertions and casualties are
filled by forced conscription of draftees as young as 14 and by
giving amnesty to political prisoners and then drafting them.
   As part of the government's attempt at changing its image, this
spring it started allowing the International Committee of the Red
Cross to visit political prisoners and has announced the release of
4,000 such prisoners so far this year.
   ``The belief is that half of them have gone straight into the
army. They're given one day of training and then ... they're put
into the front line,'' the Western analyst said.
   He and other diplomats said boys of 14 and 16 continue to be
rounded up for army duty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
