<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Elections     10-10 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Elections,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Enthralls Supporters With Vow To Crush Intefadeh</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DIMONA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir drew cheers
in this working class town by vowing to use more force to quell the
Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories if he is
re-elected next month.
   The 72-year-old leader also said Sunday he would never agree to
an independent Palestinian state, which PLO leaders may declare at
a meeting planned later this month in Tunisia. Shamir said he would
seek other ways of reaching peace with Arab neighbors.
   He told The Associated Press he would propose peace talks with
Arabs on the basis of an autonomy plan outlined in a 1979 peace
treaty with Egypt. Asked why he would pursue the idea despite its
rejection by Palestinians, Shamir replied: ``Whoever wants to
propose something the Arabs will accept, has to say good-bye to the
state of Israel.''
   ``I will initiate and attempt to persuade,'' Arab states to
negotiate by this plan, Shamir said. ``If they say, `no,' outright,
I won't be deterred.''
   Shamir, head of the right-wing Likud bloc, spoke after being
flown by army helicopter to Israel's Negev desert, where he
campaigned for five hours in three towns, including Dimona, 50
miles south of Jerusalem.
   Dimona, like many other immigrant towns in Israel, is a Likud
stronghold whose residents are mostly of Sephardi origin. Sephardi
Israelis make up a large percentage of the nation's disadvantaged
and have long enjoyed more political influence in Likud than in the
left-leaning Labor Party.
   Dozens of children waving plastic Israeli flags surrounded
Shamir as he arrived in Dimona. A local official invited him home
for a light dinner of fried sole, eggs and cheese.
   Later at an election rally in a shopping center, Shamir
enthralled some 3,000 supporters with calls for tough treatment of
Arab violence.
   Waving a fist in the air, Shamir unleashed attacks on Labor
Party leader and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, his main rival in
the Nov. 1 parliamentary elections. Shamir warned that Peres'
conciliatory approach to the Arabs ``is liable to bring us the
greatest tragedy.''
   ``If Likud wins, the Arabs will understand, there is no more
hope for an international conference or a Palestinian state,''
Shamir said. ``They'll see they have to hold dialogue with the
Likud and that we are ready for negotiations, without
preconditions.''
   Peres has backed an Arab-supported plan for a conference of
Western countries including the U.S. and Soviet Union who would
mediate a settlement of the Arab-Israeli conflict. Shamir opposes
the plan, claiming such a wide forum of nations would put
inordinate pressure on Israel to concede lands captured in the 1967
Middle East War.
   ``Whoever withdraws from Judea, Samaria (biblical names for the
West Bank) and Gaza, opens the door to a Palestinian state,''
Shamir warned.
   A Palestinian state, he said, ``would be a trap. Every country
would come to its aid _ America, the Soviet Union, Europe _ there
would be war forever.''
   Shamir also promised to crush the uprising that has claimed the
lives of more than 290 Palestinians and six Israelis since Dec. 8.
   ``We will use all the means at our disposal, so that the Arabs
will see there is not much point to their war,'' Shamir added
privately, in remarks to reporters.
   The premier also warned supporters against disrupting Labor
party rallies, after two Likud fans nearly broke up three Labor
rallies this week, heckling Peres and calling him a traitor. In one
town, Likud backers sprayed water from hoses at Labor ralliers on
Saturday.
   Labor reportedly planned to protest the violence to the Central
Elections Committee today.
   The election campaign has grown tense largely over charged
emotions generated by the unrest in the disputed territories and
because public opinion polls show both large parties at a virtual
deadlock.
   ``Don't vent your anger so freely,'' Shamir cautioned. ``We must
control ourselves, exercise self-restraint, keep our anger in our
hearts and express it only at the ballot box.''
</TEXT>
