<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Law     10-10 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Law,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Considers Removing Suspect's Right To Silence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd says Britain needs to
change the law that gives suspects a legal right to remain silent.
   At present, if they stay silent under police questioning this
cannot be held to weigh against them at their trial.
   ``No one can take out the thumbscrews and force reluctant people
to speak,'' Hurd said in an filmed interview for the British
Broadcasting Corp. program ``Panorama.''
   ``The question is to what extent can a court take into account
the fact that someone has been dumb, has not spoken or has spun a
yarn at the last minute, which didn't emerge at the police
station.''
   In the end, he said, ``we will need, I'm quite sure, in England
and Wales, to change the law on the right to silence.''
   The interview was filmed in advance for broadcast tonight but
made available to journalists before screening.
   Cabinet member Hurd's Home Office is the government department
responsible for police and law and order among other matters.
Scotland has its own legal system.
   A year ago, the head of Scotland Yard, Metropolitan Police
Commissioner Peter Imbert, said a suspect's legal right to remain
silent in police custody without this weighing against him or her
at the trial hampered the fight against crime and should be removed.
   Both the judge and prosecution should be able to draw a jury's
attention to a suspect's refusal to answer questions, Imbert told
an internatinal police conference in London.
   ``It's a puzzle to me how a privilege against self-incrimination
ever gained a respectable place in the English legal system. If we
are to deter people from criminal acts, then increasing the
prospects of conviction for them would be a most significant
step,'' Imbert said.
   Civil liberties organizations and some lawyers' groups have
protested that removing the right to silence would cause a
fundamental change in the law to the detriment of defendants.
   At present, the so-called burden of proof at a trial is on the
prosecution. It must show conclusively that an accused person is
guilty before he or she can be convicted. Critics say that if the
right to silence is removed, the burden of proof will be shifted to
the defense to show that an accused person is innocent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
