<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EBStrike     10-10 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EB Strike,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Agreement Could End Shipyard Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union leaders at Electric Boat will seek
members' approval of a tentative pact to end a 4-month-old strike
by more than 10,000 workers against the Navy's only maker of
Trident nuclear submarines.
   The company and the Metal Trades Council announced the tentative
settlement Saturday night following four full days of negotiations.
   An eight-hour session ended with union President Joseph W.
Messier and Electric Boat's chief negotiator, Thomas E. Kelly,
jointly announcing the agreement.
   ``We will unanimously endorse this agreement and recommend to
our membership that they ratify it,'' Messier said.
   ``The company is pleased that the long negotiations have come to
an end,'' Kelly said.
   Messier and Kelly refused to answer questions about the details
of the contract, which will be voted upon by union members Tuesday.
   The union initiated the latest round of negotiations following a
series of events that have weakened the union's position, including
a charge by the National Labor Relations Board that the strike was
illegal. The board said the union failed to give federal mediators
a mandatory 30-day notice before walking off the job.
   The company's last known four-year offer included a bonus worth
5 percent of a worker's annual pay in the first year; a 4 percent
bonus in the second year; a 3 percent general wage increase the
third year; and a $600 bonus in the fourth year. The proposal also
included a $1,000 contract ratification bonus.
   The Metal Trades Council, which represents 10 local trades
unions, struck July 1 when Electric Boat proposed a new contract
that included only bonuses and no raises over three years. Workers
rejected the proposal by a 5-3 ratio June 30.
   Electric Boat is the Navy's sole producer of the giant Trident
nuclear submarines and competes annually with the Newport News
(Va.) Shipbuilding & Drydock Co. for contracts to build the
smaller, SSN-688 fast attack subs.
</TEXT>
