<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Rightists     10-10 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Rightists,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extreme Rightists Toning Down Activities Due To Emperor's Illness</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Japan-Emperor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Extreme right-wing groups have been turning down
the volume of loudspeakers used to amplify streetcorner speeches
out of deference to the ailing emperor, Tokyo police said today.
   ``It's been very quiet lately,'' said an officer with the
Metropolitan Police Department. ``The rightists seem to be showing
self-restraint as the emperor is ill.''
   Emperor Hirohito, 87, the world's oldest reigning monarch, has
been bedridden since he vomited blood Sept. 19.
   Right-wing groups in Japan are notorious for driving through
major cities in convoys of military-style jeeps and trucks, blaring
recorded marching music and anti-communist slogans from public
address systems.
   Among the goals of many extreme rightists are revising Japan's
constitution to allow the re-militarization of the country and
reinstating the emperor's prewar status as a god-like soveriegn.
   ``Lately we have been quieter in our daily campaigning because
the emperor is ill,'' said a member of the extreme rightist Great
Japan Patriots Party. ``We've turned down the volume of our
speakers, but our leader continues to make his daily speeches.''
   She refused to divulge her name or the membership of the party,
estimated to be as high as 5,000, but said the group has been
praying daily for the recovery of the emperor.
   The Metropolitan Police officer, who requested anonymity, added
that a national meeting of the left-leaning Japan Teacher's Union
Sunday opened peacefully, with rightists quietly passing out
handbills. The meeting is scheduled to continue through Wednesday.
   ``The union's meetings are usually a target for rightist
groups,'' he said, ``but there has been little trouble.'' The
officer said 34 rightists demonstrated Sunday, and only 40 police
were mobilized. No rightists were reported protesting today.
   He said that at the union's general meeting in Tokyo last year
nearly 2,000 rightists in 400 cars and trucks turned out in
protest, and 1,800 riot police were dispatched to keep the peace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881010-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-AbortionVotes Bjt   10-10 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Votes, Bjt,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters In Three States Consider Abortion Ballot Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While anti-abortion activists assaulted
clinics during last week's ``siege of Atlanta,'' a lower-key though
no less intense battle raged in Michigan over a ballot measure
aimed at outlawing tax-financed abortions for the poor.
   The referendum in Michigan, one of three states with
abortion-related questions on November's ballot, is being closely
watched because so much money is being spent _ more than $3 million
budgeted by both sides.
   Abortion foes here have passed out Lifesavers candies in hopes
of mobilizing the like-minded without offending anyone else.
   The pro-choice side is considered the underdog, out-financed and
out-organized by the anti-abortion forces.
   ``Michigan is certainly the bellwether state _ there's no
question about it,'' said Dr. John Willke, president of National
Right to Life. ``But I'm not going to predict any of this. I don't
know who's going to win.''
   In Arkansas, where officials say no state funds are used to pay
for abortions, voters nonetheless are being asked to enshrine the
no-abortion spending policy in the state Constitution and to
declare ``the policy of the state of Arkansas is to protect the
life of every unborn child from conception until birth.''
   Jerry Cox, executive director of the Unborn Child Amendment
Committee, said a victory at the polls would put Arkansas in
position to outlaw all abortions if the U.S. Supreme Court ever
modifies Roe vs. Wade, the landmark 1973 decision legalizing
abortion.
   In Colorado, pro-choice forces are trying to repeal a
constitutional amendment similar to Arkansas'. Since 1984, Medicaid
abortion spending has been prohibited except in extreme situations.
   Campaign officials estimate total spending on the ballot
question could reach $1 million.
   ``The current prohibition against public funding is extreme,
it's unfair and it's expensive,'' said Ed Zorensky of Colorado
Taxpayers for Choice.
   According to the state Office of Budget and Planning, it would
cost four times as much in welfare costs to force unwilling women
to bear unwanted children and support them on welfare than to
provide public funding for abortion.
   Pro-choice activists there believe they lost the 1984 campaign
because the ballot wording confused voters.
   ``Colorado is a very strong pro-choice state. If we get the
message out I think we'll win,'' Zorensky said.
   The campaign is hottest in Michigan, where attention has
centered on the impact of the Committee to End Tax-Funded
Abortions' ``not with my money you don't'' advertisements.
   ``I worry about the tremendous amount of resources the other
side is putting into misleading media,'' said Debra Ness, who
tracks the state ballot campaigns for the National Abortion Rights
Action League. ``Unless we have the resources to counter those
messages it's not a fair test of the question of choice.''
   The message from the Committee to End Tax-Funded Abortions
deliberately is not about choice.
   Its commercials, put together by the agency handling George
Bush's presidential campaign advertising, feature well-dressed
people talking in a nice restaurant about how they're going to vote.
   The ads make a distinction between the issue of abortion and the
issue on the ballot.
   ``The way that it's framed is very, very clever,'' Ness said.
``Money buys sophistication. The anti's are trying to make their
stand in Michigan.''
   The state League of Women Voters, which won't choose sides
between political candidates, is working with the pro-choice
coalition and has lambasted the anti-abortion campaign, claiming it
is disguising its long-term goals behind the ads.
   The People's Campaign for Choice, a coalition of women's,
religious and labor groups that's fighting to defeat Michigan's
Proposal A, says $6 million a year in welfare abortion spending is
not the only thing at stake in the campaign.
   The group contends that if voters strip the poor of the right to
a state-paid abortion, it will give momentum to those seeking to
end all abortions.
   In Atlanta, more than 450 people were arrested last week in four
days of protests dubbed the ``siege of Atlanta'' by Operation
Rescue, the New York-based anti-abortion group that staged the
demonstrations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881010-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Chile Bjt   10-10 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile, Bjt,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Again Rules Out Opposition Demands For Him To Step Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet acknowledged
defeat in a referendum on extending his rule but again rejected
opposition demands for his resignation and vowed to stay in power
for another 18 months.
   A key opposition leader, meanwhile, was quoted Sunday as calling
for talks with the military government on the nation's political
future.
   In a surprise television appearance from his country home at
Bucalemu, Gen. Pinochet said Sunday, ``I acknowledge the
opposition's victory, but I am not going to change what the
constitution says. March 11, 1990, is going to be the day that the
government is handed over.
   ``The situation is very simple,'' he said. ``We fulfilled the
constitution that was set up ... so now that the opposition has
triumphed, why should we change?''
   The comments of the 72-year-old commander-in-chief of Chile's
armed forces came during a three-minute TV newscast. Pinochet was
dressed in a short-sleeve blue shirt. He appeared relaxed and spoke
clearly and firmly.
   Nearly 7 million Chileans went to the polls Wednesday to vote on
the armed forces' proposal that Pinochet remain president until
1997. Pinochet, who ousted elected Marxist President Salvador
Allende in a 1973 coup that left Allende dead, lost by about
800,000 votes or a margin of more than 11 percent.
   The vote was carried out under a 1980 constitution. That
document also calls for elections for president and congress to be
held in December 1989, with the winners taking office in March.
   Opposition leaders have pressed Pinochet's military government
to move up the date of elections and make other constitutional
changes.
   Their proposals include eliminating a constitutional ban on
Marxist groups, and allowing the entire Senate _ not just
two-thirds _ to be elected rather than appointed.
   Opposition leaders also want to streamline the process by which
future constitutional changes can be made.
   ``We will formally call on those holding power now to talk to
reach an agreement,'' opposition spokesman Patricio Aylwin said in
an interview published Sunday in the newspaper La Epoca. ``We will
take the initiative by making a proposal and call to the armed
forces.''
   Aylwin is spokesman for the 16-party coalition that urged
Chileans to vote ``no'' in the referendum.
   A 4-man military junta acts as the legislature of this South
America country, which has been ruled by freely elected, democratic
governments for most of its 178-year history as an independent
nation.
   The junta is empowered to change the constitution, but Pinochet
said in a speech broadcast nationwide the night after the
referendum that he had no intention of doing so.
   Ricardo Lagos, a prominent, moderate Socialist, acknowleged that
negotiations, if they take place, would take time. ``The people are
mature enough to understand that 15 years of dictatorship don't end
in 15 hours.''
   But other Pinochet opponents already have served notice they
don't intend to wait long or peacefully. On Saturday, a coalition
of leftist parties publicly called for Pinochet's immediate
resignation.
   The situation sets up potential clashes between the government
and its opponents. In the two days following the election, tens of
thousands of Chileans celebrated Pinochet's defeat with spontaneous
demonstrations in the streets of the capital and other major cities.
   On Friday, an estimated 350,000 Chileans gathered in a downtown
park in a rally organized by the opposition.
   Hundreds of youths have clashed with riot police since the
referendum, leading to two shooting deaths, as well as dozens of
injuries and arrests.
   About 20 reporters and photographers suffered minor injuries
last week when they were attacked by riot police as they covered
opposition celebrations.
   On Sunday, two national policemen guarding the U.S. Consulate
fired on two unidentified gunmen who shot at them from a parked
car, the state Orbe news agency said. No injuries were reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
