<HEAD>Police Seize Explosives From Student; 250 Evacuated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of Colorado engineering
student was arrested after campus police discovered two sticks of
dynamite and other explosives in his dormitory room, authorities
said.
   Mark Gregory Borchelt, 19, of Evergreen, was arrested Sunday for
investigation of felony possession of explosives charges, said
Pauline Coker, a university spokeswoman.
   About 260 students were evacuated from Andrews Hall on Sunday
after police received an anonymous tip alleging explosives were in
Borchelt's third-floor room, Coker said.
   With help from the Boulder Police Department and the Boulder
County Sheriff's Department, campus police confiscated two sticks
of dynamite, two bottle rockets, six jars of suspected explosive
powder, two bottles of flash powder, 10 6-inch lengths of dynamite
fuse and a commercial pull-fuse igniter, officials said. The
materials were in a metal ammunition box.
   Coker said one investigator described the material as
``extremely, extremely dangerous.''
