<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Explorer'sSon     10-10 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Explorer's Son,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Admiral Byrd's Son Was Mistaken For A Vagrant Before His Body Was
Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A warehouse custodian says a few days before he
found the body of polar explorer Richard E. Byrd's son, he ran him
off the property because he thought he was a drifter.
   Police said Richard E. Byrd Jr.'s body was found last week in
the debris-strewn warehouse. The body was clad in workman's clothes
and one shoe, although Byrd had left Boston by train wearing a tan
shirt and brown pants for a National Geographic Society ceremony in
Washington, D.C., honoring his father.
   Burt W. Gayleard, the on-site manager for Time Realty, which
owns the warehouse, said he spotted Byrd and an unidentified man
Sept. 27.
   ``The first time I came across him, he said, `Somebody take me
to Baltimore. I want to go to Baltimore','' Gayleard recalled. ``He
was trying to sleep when I found him. He didn't have any teeth and
he spoke like a vagrant, but he pronounced `Baltimore' properly,
not like someone who lived here.''
   Byrd, 68, left Boston on Sept. 13 to attend the ceremony
honoring his father.He never arrived and his whereabouts remained a
mystery for three weeks.
   ``I put him on a train and my wife was supposed to meet him,''
said his son, Leverett Byrd of Needham, Mass. ``What happened in
between, I don't know. It's very strange, this whole thing. We're
trying to come to grips with it.''
   Byrd said his father had suffered from some memory loss, but
hadn't wandered before.
   Police identified Byrd through a Boston Transit Authority
identification card pinned to his undershorts.
   Byrd's family has asked Arlington National Cemetery officials
outside Washington for permission to bury him there, Byrd's sister,
Katharine Breyer, said Sunday.
   Baltimore police spokesman Dennis Hill said Sunday that
investigators were waiting for results from toxicology tests that
might shed light on the cause of death.
   Although Byrd appeared to be suffering from malnutrition and
dehydration, a cause of death remained undetermined.
   Byrd was 6 years old when his father, Adm. Richard Evelyn Byrd,
reached the North Pole, and in the 1940s, joined the admiral on an
expedition to the South Pole.
   Leverett Byrd said his father, who lived off small trust funds
and stock market investments, had a hard time being the son of a
famous figure.
   ``His whole life was pretty difficult. You can imagine what it
was like to be the son of Admiral Byrd.''
</TEXT>
