<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Delinquents,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Gangs Plague Students In Shenzhen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployed youths are robbing and beating up
elementary and high school students in the south China city of
Shenzhen, an official newspaper said today.
   A spokesman for Hongling Middle School said there were more than
20 cases in the school this year in which small groups of
unemployed youths, typically high-school dropouts, bullied students
and stole their money, the Shenzhen Special Zone Daily said.
   Other schools had similar problems, the paper said.
   Bullies repeatedly waylaid and stole a total of $80 from one
Hongling student who did not inform his parents and school
authorities because he feared reprisals, the paper said. The youths
also forced another student to steal money from classmates.
   On Oct. 4, four 17- and 18-year-olds held up a high-school
junior on his way home from school and beat him badly with iron
chains when he did not give them money. The student is still not
able to return to school.
   There have also been reports of juvenile delinquents threatening
and robbing students in Shenzhen's Lizhi Park, the paper said.
   Shenzhen, located across the border from Hong Kong, is one of
four special economic zones with greater freedoms to deal directly
with foreign investors and is regarded as one of China's most open
cities.
</TEXT>
