<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-NationalDay     10-10 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-National Day,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Celebrates National Day With Military Parade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nationalist China celebrated its national
day today with a massive military parade that was considered a show
of support for Taiwan-born President Lee Teng-hui.
   The 70-minute parade in front of the Presidential Building,
where Lee and other officials watched, included a march by 13,000
goose-stepping cadets, soldiers and bare-chested frogmen and 600
armed vehicles as well as domestically-developed long-range
missiles and other weapons.
   Air Force jet fighters and helicopters flew in formation over
the large crowd in the parade area that included 30,000 overseas
Chinese, many of whom will be taken later at government expense to
visit major military bases, high-technology companies and scenic
spots around the island.
   Lee, 65, has been president since January when President Chiang
Ching-kuo died. He is the first native Taiwanese to hold the post
and there have been reports that the island's generals have gained
added power at his expense since strongman Chiang's death.
   Analysts said the emphasis on military might may also have been
intended to emphasize to China that there has been no softening of
Taiwan's anti-communist stance despite an easing of tensions
between the rival governments in the past year.
   ``Our armed forces have proved their strength in the parade,''
Lee told the gathering after the parade. ``We can give the
war-mongering Chinese Communist authorities a frontal attack.''
   Lee said the Nationalists are determined to recover the Chinese
mainland and reunite China under the three principles of
nationalism, democracy and social welfare advocated by Sun Yat-sen,
founded of the Chinese republic who died in 1925.
   Taiwan held 15 military parades after 1949 when the Nationalists
were defeated on the China mainland and retreated to Taiwan. But
since the mid-60s, the parades have concentrated more on
publicizing Taiwan's economic successes and civilian lifestyles
rather than its military strength.
   The Nationalists and Communists are technically still at war but
the late President Chiang adopted a more open policy toward China
in 1987 when he lifted martial law and relaxed a ban on travel to
the mainland to allow family reunions.
   National Day celebrations were also held in other cities and
they included mass rallies, folk dances, concerts, exhibitions and
fireworks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881010-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0548EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PavarottiCompetition     10-10 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pavarotti Competition,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pavarotti Names 40 Winners of Opera Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON BEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucianno Pavarotti named 40 singers who are
winners of the third Opera Company of Philadelphia-Lucianno
Pavarotti International Voice Competition.
   ``But I must tell you, they are all winners,'' said Pavarotti
late Sunday as he stood on stage at the Academy of Music at the
conclusion of the final auditions that featured 70 finalists.
   He had them all join him and take a bow along with the winners.
   The competition began 1{ years ago with 1,500 singers. That was
narrowed to 140 finalists from 18 countries who completed their
auditions during the last week here.
   They weren't competing for medals, money or first, second or
third place. The 40 winners now get the chance to perform with
Pavarotti.
   ``Just to get a chance to sing for him, to listen to what he has
to say is worth it,'' said Izabella Labuda, a Polish soprano who
was among the 70, but not among the winners.
   There were 19 winners in the first competition that began in
1980 with 500 singers and 54 in the second, from a field of 1,000.
The format for selecting winners has drawn criticism.
   Rumanian-born bass Julian Rodescu, now a U.S. citizen living
here, was in the audience three years ago and said he was like
those critics in asking ``How could they have 54 winners?''
   But as one of this year's winners, he said the whole thing makes
sense.
   ``No one else but he (Pavarotti) could do something like this,''
Rodescu said. ``There is no other competition where there is
someone of his caliber to hear you and to help you.
   ``This is where someone is trying to find, to single out and to
help talented singers by giving them recognition.''
   Pavarotti, who owes his own beginnings to a voice competition,
decided to start his own so he could return the favor to the
audiences who made him what he is today. Also, he said he wanted to
help find new talent.
   The proof of his competition, Pavarotti said, is that 85 percent
of previous winners are full-time singers and the competition
proved to be a big boost for them.
   Pavarotti will return to the Academy in March and April in his
normal role of opera superstar to lead casts for two operas
featuring competition winners.
   Each opera will have two sets of cast members from the winners.
Others not in those productions will be offered roles in other
operas during the next two seasons, according to Margaret Anne
Everitt, Opera Company general director and one of the three
judges. The third judge was Antonio Tonini, Pavarotti's own vocal
coach and a former conductor and coach at La Scala in Milan.
   This year's winners:
   Sopranos Lynn Fortin, Ste-Foy, Quebec; Paula Romano, Milan,
Italy; Alessandra Ruffini, Piacenza, Italy; Lubica Rybarska,
Bratislava, Czechoslovakia; mezzo-soprano Victoria Livengood,
Elizabeth, N.J.; tenor Maurizio Saltarin, Placenza D'Adige, Italy;
bass Janusz Borowicz, Krakow, Poland; soprano Steffanie Pearce,
Philadelphia; tenor Martin Thompson, Bethlehem, Pa.; Chilean
soprano Veronica Villarroel, now of New York.
   Bass Julian Rodescu, Philadelphia; tenor Ivano Costantino, Rome;
soprano Cynthia Lawrence, Chicago; soprano Cecelia Rae Chaisson,
Philadelphia; tenor James Caputo, Guilford, Conn.; bass Kevin
Glavin, Pittsburgh; soprano Deborah Voigt, New York; bass Piotr
Nowacki, Lodz, Poland; mezzo-soprano Jody Kidwell, Philadelphia;
Claudine Cote, Chicoutimi, Quebec.
   Baritone Mark Gargiulo, Philadelphia; Chinese tenor Jianyi
Zhang, now of New York; soprano Anna Caterina Antonacci, Bologna,
Italy; Israeli baritone Mordecai Kaston, now of New York; Swedish
mezzo soprano Katia Lytting, now of Bologna, Italy; tenor Joseph
Wolverton, River Edge, N.J.; soprano Ibolya Verebics, Budapest,
Hungary; soprano Andrea Gruber, New York.
   Baritone Hyun-Soo Choi, Seoul, South Korea; soprano Cristina
Pastorello, Verona, Italy; tenor Eduardo Ayas, Buenos Aires,
Argentina; soprano Annalisa Winberg, Burlingame, Calif.; mezzo
soprano Susan Shafer, Closter, N.J.; soprano Virginia Croskery,
Highland Park, Ill.; bass Giovanni Furlanetto, Treviso, Italy;
Japanese soprano Michie Nakamaru, of Milan, Italy; Italian tenor
Roberto Alagna, of Clichy sur Bois, France; soprano Guadalupe
Gonzalez, San Jose, Costa Rica; baritone Mark Delevan, San
Francisco; soprano Antonella Banaudi, Sanremo, Italy.

