<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines 2ndLd-Writethru a0468 10-10 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0468,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Enrile Denies Links To New Coup Plot</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Eds: LEDES with 10 graf to UPDATE with Soriano denying report.
PICKS up 10th graf, `Defense Secretary ...'
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile
denied today that he or any of his relatives had any links with an
alleged new plot to topple President Corazon Aquino.
   Enrile made the denial during a radio interview after Mrs.
Aquino's speechwriter wrote in the Philippine Daily Globe that
Enrile and his sister were linked to a new plot codenamed ``Oplan
Three Kings.''
   In the report, Teodoro Locsin, the Globe's publisher, quoted
National Security Adviser Emmanuel Soriano as saying that the plot
involves an unidentified senator and a sister.
   But Locsin claimed the senator was Enrile and his sister, Irma
Ponce Enrile-Potenciano, who owns a bus company.
   Soriano was quoted as saying the unidentified senator will fund
the rebellion which will be pulled off next January around the
Feast of the Epiphany on Jan. 6.
   The feast marks the visit of the Three Kings to the infant
Jesus, thus the codename.
   According to the Globe report, the plot called for buses to
ferry a main force of renegade soldiers, led by cashiered Lt. Col.
Gregorio Honasan.
   ``I am calling Soriano a liar,'' Enrile said. ``I challenge
Soriano to come out with details of the `Oplan Three Kings' so that
we can discuss it in any proper forum.''
   Soriano later denied having told Locsin of the alleged plot.
   ``I don't know who came out with that story ... I am making an
official denial,'' Soriano said in a radio interview.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos told reporters that he was aware
of the rumored plot but said his information was based on ``raw
intelligence.'' He said it was unlikely Honasan was capable of
mounting another coup.
   Mrs. Aquino's government has survived at least six coup attempts
since it was catapulted to power during a civilian-military revolt
in February 1986.
   Honasan, with a force of more than 2,000 soldiers, led the most
serious attempt against Mrs. Aquino's government. At least 53
people were killed and more than 300 others wounded during the
failed Aug. 28, 1987 coup.
   The renegade colonel was arrested in December but escaped from a
prison ship the following April.
   Honasan was Enrile's security chief when the senator was defense
minister under former President Ferdinand Marcos and Mrs. Aquino.
Enrile was fired on Nov. 23, 1986, after a failed coup by his
followers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
