<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-TrainAccident     10-10 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Train Accident,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Derails, Death Toll Rises to 33</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two cars of an express passenger
train derailed at a station in eastern Yugoslavia, killing at least
33 people and injuring several others, the state Tanjug news agency
reported today.
   The crash occurred at 7:20 p.m. Sunday in Lapovo, about 50 miles
south of Belgrade.
   The train was on a regular trip from the southern city of
Skoplje to Belgrade when its last two cars jumped off the rails at
full speed at the Lapovo station and rammed into an engine of a
parked freight train, Tanjug said.
   A Belgrade radio report described the impact as ``tremendous.''
   Initial findings suggest that technical failure, rather than
human error, was the cause of the accident as the engine driver
reportedly entered the station observing all signals and did not
exceed speed limits, the agency said.
</TEXT>
