<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0612EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Marcos     10-10 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Dismisses Marcos Petition To Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The anti-graft court today dismissed
a petition by ousted President Ferdinand Marcos to return home to
witness the testimony of a former official on alleged kickbacks
during his 20-year administration.
   In a nine-page resolution, the court said Marcos' presence would
not be necessary when former Public Works Minister Baltazar Aquino,
who is reportedly ailing, gives his deposition Nov. 7 to Nov. 11.
   Marcos asked the court to allow him to return for the deposition
and act as his own defense counsel. But the court said the granting
of Marcos' request to return was a ``political question'' which the
government of Mrs. Aquino must decide.
   Marcos fled the country during the February 1986
civilian-military rebellion that ended his 20-year rule and
catapulted Mrs. Aquino to the presidency. He has lived in exile in
Hawaii since.
   In its decision, the court said Marcos can be represented by a
lawyer in Manila.
   ``Marcos can answer the charges by disposition, which is by
issuing legal statements from his home in Honolulu,'' the decision
said.
   It added that Marcos' ``recourse'' is to ask Mrs. Aquino to
issue him travel documents to return to the Philippines.
   Mrs. Aquino has repeatedly refused to allow Marcos to return,
citing national security.
   Lawyers for Marcos in Manila had earlier stated that if the
lower court rejected the former president's petition, they would
appeal the case to the Supreme Court.
   Marcos has not been formally charged in any Philippine court.
Philippine law bans trials in absentia, and the Mrs. Aquino's
government has delayed criminal proceedings for fear Marcos would
insist on attending the trial.
   Marcos is facing 39 civil cases on charges he embezzled up to
$10 billion during his term.
   Much of the money is believed to have been stashed in secret
Swiss bank accounts. Swiss authorities have refused to lift banking
secrecy laws until the Philippine government files criminal charges
against Marcos.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
