<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     10-10 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold and Damp in Northeast; Thunderstorms Hit Gulf Coast, Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cold, damp weather persisted over the Northeast early today and
thunderstorms soaked parts of the Gulf Coast and the southern
Rockies.
   Record temperatures in the 100s baked southern California Sunday
and sent more than 300,000 people to the beaches. Los Angeles
posted a record high for the date of 102 degrees, breaking the old
mark set in 1976 by 4 degrees and forcing some players at the Miami
Dolphins-Los Angeles Raiders contest at the Los Angeles Memorial
Coliseum to leave the game briefly.
   Highs were forecast to drop back into double digits today.
   Temperatures were only in the upper 20s and 30s in northern New
England and northern New York state. Cloudy skies stretched across
much of the northern Atlantic Coast region, with rain limited
mainly to Pennsylvania and New York.
   Rain fell along the coast of Louisiana and in eastern Texas
Sunday evening. Lafayette, La., recorded marble-sized hail and wind
gusts up to 40 mph. Thunderstorms also hit southeastern Arizona and
southwest New Mexico.
   Dry weather prevailed elsewhere with mostly clear skies over the
central Mississippi Valley, the Plains and the area west of the
Rockies.
   Today's forecast called for scattered rain from the Great Lakes
and upper Ohio Valley to western and northern New England. A few
showers and thunderstorms were expected to develop from Arizona and
southern Utah into New Mexico and southern Texas.
   Mostly sunny skies were forecast for the rest of the nation,
with gusty winds in the upper Mississippi Valley and the northern
Great Lakes.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s or 70s across much of the
nation; in the 40s in northern New England; in the 50s from
southern New England across the Great Lakes and south to the
central Appalachians; in the 80s in Oregon and southwest Idaho,
southern Texas and southern Florida; in the upper 80s to mid-90s in
California; and up to 105 degrees in the desert Southwest.
   At 3 a.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 29 degrees at Massena,
N.Y., and Plattsburg, N.Y., to 84 at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 50 partly cloudy; Boston 46 fair; Buffalo 47
showery; Charleston, S.C. 49 fair; Cincinnati 43 fair; Cleveland 48
fair; Detroit 45 foggy; Miami 74 fair; New York 53 fair;
Philadelphia 48 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 47 fair; Portland, Maine
38 rain; Washington 48 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 54 fair; Chicago 53 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 53 fair; Denver 41 fair; Des Moines 52 partly
cloudy; Indianapolis 46 fair; Kansas City 49 fair; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 56 fair; Nashville 48 fair; New Orleans 62 partly cloudy; St.
Louis 49 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 58 fair; Anchorage 33 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 71 fair; Los Angeles 74 fair; Phoenix 84 fair; Salt Lake City
59 fair; San Diego 68 fair; San Francisco 54 fair; Seattle 53 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 37 partly cloudy; Toronto 34 fair.
</TEXT>
