<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FinancialFlight     10-10 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Financial Flight,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Return From Tokyo May Lead To Recovery Of Some Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive financier's return to the United States
could lead to the recovery of some of the $25 million he allegedly
embezzled from investors, an official said.
   The FBI arrested Henry Gherman, 52, as he got off a plane in
Tokyo on Saturday after he was expelled from Taiwan, said FBI agent
William Wells.
   He has been a federal fugitive since August on charges of
embezzlement and mail fraud. He may have been in Taiwan as long as
six weeks, Wells said.
   ``There is a stronger likelihood now that he has been arrested
that we will recover substantial funds,'' said James Feltman, the
court-appointed overseer for Gherman's two investment concerns.
   Authorities said Gherman stayed in luxury hotels costing up to
$300 a night and spent lavishly on room service and telephone calls
to the United States.
   At the time of his arrest, Gherman was carrying up to $30,000 in
U.S. money and ``a sizable amount of Taiwanese currency,'' Wells
said.
   Gherman is accused of masterminding a scheme that may have
swindled nearly 50 investors, U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen said in
a federal complaint filed Aug. 29 in U.S. District Court.
   Authorities said the investigation of Gherman's activities
continues and additional charges are expected.
   ``We think we'll be successful in locating some of those
funds,'' Wells said. ``We don't know how much. We just don't know
how much is left.''
   Feltman said actions against third parties can help mitigate
losses.
   ``There are a lot of financial institutions who aided him,
knowingly or unknowingly,'' said John Schulte, attorney for an
association of seven doctors for whom Gherman handled a $1.5
million pension fund. ``They could be subject to claims.
   ``The secret is to get this guy back. Without him, you have to
speculate and re-create. But with him, you have the person who is
the star witness.''
   Gherman had a ``longstanding pattern of embezzlement'' from
about 25 professional associations handling pension funds and other
assets for members, Lehtinen said. Gherman's scheme could have
affected nearly 50 investors, including smaller investors such as
clerks and nurses.
   Gherman made telephone calls to his wife and to Miami attorneys
after his disappearance, but authorities were unaware of his
whereabouts until U.S. citizens in Taiwan reported his possible
location there, agents said. Authorities then found him and
arranged his expulsion, said Wells.
   Wells said that if Gherman agrees, he could be brought to Miami
within a week, but if he fights extradition, the process could take
as long as 45 days.
   Gherman is charged with five counts of embezzlement and two
counts of mail fraud. He faces 35 years in prison and fines in
excess of $1.5 million if convicted on all counts, Lehtinen said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
