<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     10-10 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was lower today in Europe, where
trading was thinned by holidays in Japan and the United States.
Gold prices rose.
   Foreign currency dealers in Frankfurt, West Germany, said the
dollar was still under pressure from Friday's relase of U.S.
unemployment figures.
   ``It seems people are disappointed over the employment
figures,'' said one dealer with a major West German bank. But he
said few traders are prepared to sell the dollar heavily on the
basis of one indicator, especially in such a thin market.
   The U.S. unemployment rate fell 0.2 percentage points to 5.4
percent in September from 5.6 percent in August, while non-farm
payrolls rose 255,000 compared with 169,000 in August, the Commerce
Department figures showed.
   The market was open in the United States, despite the Columbus
Day holiday.
   Japan's financial markets were closed for Physical Fitness Day,
a national holiday. In London, the dollar was quoted at 132.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates in London at midmorning, compared with late
Friday:
   _1.8565 West German marks, down from 1.8608
   _1.5755 Swiss francs, down from 1.5795
   _6.3260 French francs, down from 6.3420
   _2.0915 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0988
   _1,383.75 Italian lire, down from 1,387.50
   _1.2077 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2116
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7075, almost one cent more
than late Friday's $1.6985.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $404.20 dollars a troy
ounce, up from $403.05 bid late Friday. At midmorning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$406.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $406.15, up from the $404.25 bid
late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.28 to close at a bid of
$409.34.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.34 a troy
ounce, slightly higher than Friday's $6.33.
</TEXT>
