<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     10-10 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mine Injures Police Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mine exploded at a black
policemen's barracks early today, slightly injuring four officers,
police said.
   The bomb exploded at 1:55 a.m. near the Tembisa township police
barracks outside Springs, east of Johannesburg. Minimal damage was
caused to the building, police said.
   There have been more than 150 bombings in South Africa since a
national emergency was declared June 12, 1986. More than 70 have
occurred this year. The government blames most of them on the
outlawed African National Congress, which does not comment on
individual acts, but has adopted a bombing and sabotage campaign to
overthrow the white government.
   In their daily unrest report for the preceding 24 hours, police
said they had found the body of a black man who had been stabbed to
death at Nxamalala in Natal province where seven men were killed
the previous day in factional violence between black political
groups.
   In other black townships in the province, stonethrowers damaged
five houses and a church at Fredville, while two houses were
damaged by gasoline bombs in Mpumalanga.
   Two black men were shot when unknown gunmen fired shots at them
in Kwamakita outside Durban, in Natal, police said.
   Durban and other cities in Natal province have been the sites of
some of the country's most sustained black-on-black faction
fighting in recent years.
   The two main rivals are Inkatha, a political organization headed
by Zulu leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi, and the United Democratic
Front, a nationwide anti-apartheid coalition that the government
banned in February.
</TEXT>
