<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0724EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon     10-10 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli-Backed Militiamen Kill Two Guerrillas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli-backed Christian militiamen killed two
guerrillas today in a gunbattle in southern Lebanon, the army
reported.
   It did not say, however, to what group the guerrillas belonged.
   Meanwhile, Lebanon's acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss said that
partitioning Lebanon into sectarian sub-states would trigger
longterm wars between Christians and Moslems.
   A guerrilla squad fired on the South Lebanon Army patrol
immediately after it found a large bomb along a road. In the
battle, two guerrillas were shot to death, and Christian militiamen
suffered no casualties, the army spokesman said.
   The gunfight occurred on the border of Israel's self-declared
security zone in south Lebanon, close to the village of Aaichiye,
nine miles north of the Israeli border, said an army spokesman on
condition of anonymity.
   In his comments today, Hoss was responding to a statement by
Samir Geagea, leader of the Lebanese Forces, the main Christian
militia, that a federal system was the only practical way to end
the deadlock over presidential elections and Lebanon's 13-year
civil war.
   ``I challenge the advocates of federalization or partition to
draw up the borders of their cantons. This cannot be done,'' the
Syrian-backed Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, told The Associated Press.
   ``It will also lead to endless wars in the streets, alleys,
hills, villages and towns,'' Hoss said.
   Former President Amin Gemayel appointed a Christian military
government led by Gen. Michel Aoun in September at the end of his
six-year presidential term. However, Hoss' government refused to
resign and challenges the legitimacy of the new government.
   Under an unwritten national covenant dating to Lebanon's
independence from France in 1943, Maronite Christians have held the
posts of president, army commander and central bank governor.
Sunnis held the premiership, and a Shiite Moslem has been
parliament speaker.
</TEXT>
