<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1002EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Demjanjuk     10-10 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Demjanjuk,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demjanjuk Lawyer Claims Witness Intimidated, Files Court Motion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for John Demjanjuk, the retired
American autoworker convicted as a Nazi death camp guard, accused
Israeli authorities today of telling a potential defense witness
not to testify during the trial.
   Defense attorney Yoram Sheftel said a motion to present evidence
from Richard Glazier, a Treblinka survivor living in Switzerland,
was submitted today to the Supreme Court.
   Glazier refused to testify for the defense, Sheftel said.
   The attorney said a taped conversation between Glazier and an
American attorney indicates that Israeli authorities pressured
Glazier to withhold information that could have vindicated
Demjanjuk.
   ``We are asking the court to inform Mr. Glazier that he is not
obliged to keep his mouth shut,'' Sheftel said. ``This is a clear
cut case of obstruction of justice.''
   Demjanjuk, 68, was sentenced to death in April after being
identified as ``Ivan the Terrible,'' a sadistic guard at the Nazis'
Treblinka death camp who operated gas chambers that killed 850,000
Jews during World War II. He denied he was the guard.
   He was convicted of crimes against humanity and crimes against
the Jewish people and is now in an Israeli prison awaiting the
outcome of an appeal of his conviction sentence.
   Sheftel, reading from a transcript of the taped conversation
involving Glazier, quoted him as saying: ``I promised the general
attorney who investigated me, the Israeli attorney, not to talk to
anybody as long as the trial is not closed.''
   Sheftel said that when asked if Demjanjuk was ``Ivan the
Terrible,'' Glazier replied, ``I can't tell you.... Maybe he wasn't
at Treblinka.''
   The conversation took place in 1986 when William Wolf, an
attorney from Phoenix, Ariz., who assisted the Demjanjuk defense,
questioned Glazier, Sheftel said. Defense attorneys submitted a
transcript of the conversation today and asked the court to allow
the evidence in Demjanjuk's appeal, Sheftel said. The appeal is
scheduled for Dec. 5.
   A spokesman for the prosecuting attorneys in the case said they
have not seen the motion filed by Sheftel and would not comment on
it. Glazier, who lives in Zurich, Switzerland, could not
immediately be reached for comment.
   Sheftel said he spoke to Glazier ``a few times'' since the 1986
conversation with Wolf, and each time Glazier told him he was asked
by authorities to keep quiet during Demjanjuk's trial.
   ``He promised not to talk but he doesn't say why,'' Sheftel
said. ``It's clear the defense was not able to bring all of the
evidence to the trial. This casts strong reservations on all of the
proceedings.''
   During Demjanjuk's trial, defense attorneys said there were
death camp survivors who failed to identify the defendant as ``Ivan
the Terrible,'' but the defense did not produce any of them as
witnesses.
   Edward Nishnic, Demjanjuk's son-in-law and head of a defense
fund, said Glazier has repeatedly refused to talk to the defense
about whether he had knowledge of war crimes by Demjanjuk.
   He said in a prepared statement that Glazier previously had been
listed by the U.S. Justice Department's office of special
investigations as being unable to identify Demjanjuk as ``Ivan the
Terrible.''
   Demjanjuk was extradited to Israel in February 1986 from the
Cleveland, Ohio, suburb of Seven Hills. Defense attorneys maintain
Demjanjuk is a victim of mistaken identity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
