<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0442 10-10 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Bush remarks on furlough system; pick up
5th graf pvs bgng ``On Sunday...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said today he
would study the federal prison furlough system to make sure ``it
never slips into the Massachusetts model.''
   Bush said he would ``review everything'' about the system if
elected.
   Bush's remarks came aboard Air Force Two as he flew to New
Jersey, one of several key tossup states the vice president will
focus on in the final weeks before the Nov. 8 election. His
Columbus Day speech today was to focus on crime and the rights of
victims.
   Reporters asked Bush about a remark by his chief of staff, Craig
Fuller, that Bush favors reviewing the federal furlough system.
Asked if he had any specific reservations about the program, he
said, ``I don't have any specific feelings at all. I just ... want
to be sure it never slips into the Massachusetts model.''
   Bush has been highly critical of the Massachusetts furlough
system, accusing rival Michael Dukakis of overseeing a system that
allowed murderers out on weekend passes.
   Bush had a light campaign schedule this week ahead of the
Thursday night debate with Dukakis.
   Aides to Bush, known in the past for deliberately seeking to
lower expectations for their candidate's performances, suggested
that the Republican nominee's preparations this time would be less
intense than the last _ perhaps even dispensing with a mock
practice debate.
   ``We view it (the second debate) as being important, but we
don't look for it making a big difference in the campaign,'' Fuller
said.
   On Sunday, Bush participated in a parade in an ethnic Chicago
suburb. The visit marked the fifth time the vice president has been
to Illinois, which has 24 electoral votes, since formally accepting
the Republican nomination in August.
   Aides said both Illinois and New Jersey, with its 16 electoral
votes, are deemed critical battlegrounds where the contest could go
either way.
   The vice president also will take advantage of the Los Angeles
site for this week's presidential debate to base operations in
California for several days beginning Tuesday. Bush will prepare
for the debate, interrupted by short campaign forays in the state
with the most electoral votes _ 47.
   Aides said Bush's California campaigning will be capped by a
daylong bus tour of rural communities in the state's Central Valley
next Saturday.
   The presidential debate is scheduled for Thursday, although the
date could change if rainouts force the National League baseball
series to be extended.
   Fuller said the vice president engaged in several hours of
debate preparation with aides on Sunday morning. Bush was spending
this afternoon alone with briefing books at his Washington
residence, ``without aides or advisers,'' Fuller said.
   The aide said former Deputy Treasury Secretary Richard Darman,
Bush's sparring partner in practice for the first debate, would be
in Los Angeles on a standby basis. But there is a good chance
``there won't be a mock debate,'' Fuller said.
   ``He (Bush) is comfortable with debate preparations so far,''
the chief of staff said.
   On Sunday, Bush and his wife, Barbara, rode in an old-fashioned
fire truck and waved as thousands of people lined a two-mile parade
route between Cicero and Berwin, Ill., in the annual Houby Day
parade, a Czechoslovakian celebration of bountiful mushroom crops.
Houby is a Czech word for mushroom.
   ``This is the day we celebrate family, we celebrate faith and we
celebrate freedom,'' Bush said in brief remarks at the beginning of
the parade. ``And none of us will ever forget there is not freedom
in Eastern Europe and I have pledged as president to never forget
that.''
   To scattered protesters chanting the anti-Bush chant ``Where was
George?'' Bush at one point gestured toward himself and said, ``I'm
here.'' He then called out: ``Where is Mike?''
</TEXT>
