<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0498,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Palestinians Decide To Set Up Independent State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to ADD that council must approve any
agreement. Pickup 3rd graf pvs, ``Quoting an...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported today that Palestinian
guerrilla groups have agreed to set up an independent state on land
occupied by Israel.
   An emergency meeting later this month of the Palestine National
Council, or parliament-in-exile, is expected to include a
declaration of independence for the occupied territories and the
formation of a provisional government.
   The council must formalize any agreement by the guerrilla groups
to set up an independent state or a provisional government.
   Quoting an aide to Palestine Liberation chief Yasser Arafat, the
Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Quabas said in today's editions that leaders
of several rebel groups ``unanimously adopted a decision to set up
an independent Palestinian state and declare sovereignty on
Palestinian land.''
   ``We declare this to the entire world. It is a milestone in
Palestinian history,'' the newspaper quoted Arafat aide Salah
Khalaf as saying.
   The newspaper said it reached Khalaf by telephone Sunday night
at the end of three days of intensive talks among several
Palestinian factions at Palestine Liberation Organization
headquarters in Tunis, Tunisia.
   The PLO has been debating for months its agenda for the future
of the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip in light of the
10-month uprising by the 1.5 million Palestinian inhabitants. It
also wants to fill the vacuum left when King Hussein curtailed
Jordan's administrative links with the occupied territories in July.
   On Sunday, the state-run newspaper Al-Ittihad of Abu Dhabi
quoted PLO spokesman Jameel Hilal as saying that Oct. 25 has been
fixed as date for the council session and that the meetings will be
held as scheduled in Algiers.
   But Khalaf indicated the Algiers site might be changed, possibly
because of the riots in the North African country.
   Khalaf, also known as Abu Iyad, denied reports that the Soviet
Union asked the PLO to postpone declaration of a Palestinian state.
   ``The Soviets have told us they support any PLO decision,'' he
said.
   Khalaf said that a PLO delegation led by Farouk Kaddoumi, head
of the PLO Political Department, had left Tunis for Moscow to sound
out Soviet leaders on future PLO steps.
   He emphasized that the council meeting will be held before the
Israeli national elections on Nov. 1. ``This is our final
decision,'' he said of the latest PLO discussions.
</TEXT>
