<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionWars     10-10 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Wars,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Protesters Suspend `Siege of Atlanta' Demonstrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion opponents have ended their
demonstrations for the time being, leaving 282 people still in jail
today after a week of protests.
   About 137 of those still jailed have applied for bond but have
not been processed, Tom Pocock, deputy director of the Atlanta
Corrections Bureau, said this morning.
   He said the 137 had given their names to authorities and should
be released by Thursday. Police arrested 463 people during the
recent protests, and had released 181 by this morning, Pocock said.
   He said 145 others in custody had not applied for bond and had
not given their real names.
   Many of those arrested identify themselves only as ``Baby Jane
Doe'' or ``Baby John Doe'' and cannot be freed on bond, the city
says. The protesters say the ``Doe'' names symbolize their
solidarity with aborted fetuses.
   Operation Rescue, the New York-based organization that organized
the protests, has accused the city of purposely delaying the
releases to keep the demonstrators in jail until the organizers
leave.
   The city accuses Operation Rescue of boasting that it would clog
the city's judicial process with hundreds of arrests, and says the
demonstrators succeeded.
   The aim of the week of demonstrations was to block clinic
entrances to prevent women from entering or persuade them not to
have abortions. Clinic operators said most of the appointments were
kept, and some brought patients in before dawn to avoid the pickets.
   Processing of the prisoners has been delayed because city
officials have refused to separate the paperwork of Operation
Rescue prisoners from that of other cases. The prisoners have
complained of inadequate bedding and towels.
   Pocock said the city had received a list from Operation Rescue
of those who should be released first based on family, job or
health concerns, and about 40 of those on the list had been
released.
   Since Operation Rescue came to Atlanta in July for the
Democratic National Convention, police have arrested 1,235
demonstrators. Even before last week's resumption of
demonstrations, city officials said they had spent more than
$500,000 on security, arrests, jail and court costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
