<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HazardousHayride 1stLd-Writethru a0514 10-10 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hazardous Hayride, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0514,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Hospitalized After Trip Down `Suicide Hill'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS one graf after graf 6, `It was...', with more on
Pourchot's job; picks up 7th graf, `The most...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tractor driver was arrested for public
intoxication after 11 teen-agers were injured when a hayride wagon
overturned.
   A girl who suffered internal injuries in the Saturday night
accident was listed in critical condition, while a boy was
hospitalized with a neck injury.
   The driver, John R. Pourchot, 34, was arrested for public
intoxication and released on his own recognizance.
   One of the two wagons being pulled by the tractor overturned
about 10:45 p.m. Saturday as it was going down a steep road in
Eagle Creek Park, authorities said. Many of the 40 passengers were
affiliated with the Fellowship of Christian Athletes group at
Speedway High School.
   Mark Lewis, 15, who was listed in satisfactory condition, said
Pourchot, a parks department employee, had been ``acting a little
crazy and he was going too fast.''
   ``It was down the hill and he said, `You guys ready for Suicide
Hill?' He was going about 30 miles per hour when this happened,''
Lewis said.
   Joseph Wynns, deputy director of the parks department, said
Pourchot was a light-equipment operator whose normal duties
included driving for such events.
   The most seriously injured was Lisa Reed, 14, who was pinned
beneath the wagon. She was listed in critical condition Sunday
night at St. Vincent Hospital.
   Nine other people were treated at the hospital and released.
</TEXT>
