<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis     10-10 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Unveils Housing Program; Keeps Heat On Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEVITTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today visited this
post-World War II model community to unveil a housing program that
would allow first-time buyers to use IRA and pension savings for a
down payment on a home.
   The Democratic presidential nominee told a Levittown gathering
that the Reagan-Bush administration had broken the federal
government's longstanding promise to help families buy their first
home.
   ``We rolled up our sleeves _ Democrats and Republicans alike _
and made a great national promise, a promise to provide affordable
housing for all Americans,'' Dukakis said of the initiatives which
helped build Levittown.
   ``The administration that Mr. Bush has been a part of broke that
promise in the early 1980s,'' Dukakis said. He delivered the speech
at a high school after visiting with Lou and Betty Tolano, owners
of one of the original Levittown homes, and several of their
children.
   Among them was to be Steve Tolano and his wife, Lisa, who are
expecting a baby and are living with the elder Tolanos because they
cannot afford a home. But Lisa Tolano went into labor prior to the
meeting and was taken to an area hospital.
   Dukakis was headed next into New York City, to march in the
Columbus Day parade.
   Dukakis chided the vice president for declaring that ``housing
is up'' during their recent debate and also kept the heat on
Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, the Republican vice presidential nominee.
   ``He's right,'' Dukakis said of Bush's debate statement.
``Housing is `up,' so much it's almost out of sight in much of this
country. Since this administration took office, the price of houses
has raced ahead of people's wages and has made it impossible for
many people to buy the homes they grew up in.
   ``George Bush has no housing program,'' he continued. ``He has
no solutions. He has no new ideas.''
   Dukakis blamed Reagan administration cuts in housing programs
for the escalation of homelessness in the past eight years and said
much of the problem was rooted in the lack of affordable housing
for young families.
   The Dukakis plan, called Home Start, would allow first-time
homebuyers to use their Individual Retirement Account or other
tax-deferred pension savings for a down payment on a home. Dukakis
said the plan was a ``natural extension'' of the goal behind such
accounts.
   ``Under current law, young families can speculate on stocks or
gold, or soybean futures with these funds,'' Dukakis said. ``Home
Start will let them make the best investment they can _ in a home
for their families.''
   Dukakis, in the speech, said the program also would include
provisions to lower down payments and closing costs and to raise
borrowing limits on federally guaranteed mortgages. He did not cite
a cost estimate and campaign aides were not immediately available
to discuss the plan.
   Dukakis said the program would complement his proposal for a
National Partnership for Affordable Housing, which is modeled after
a Massachusetts program that uses some state money and agreements
with private developers to build moderately priced housing for
first-time buyers.
   ``George Bush and his friends are satisfied; they say all is
well,'' Dukakis said. ``Dan Quayle is the only cloud on their
horizon. They're right to worry about Mr. Quayle. And so are the
American people.''
   Dukakis, who was accompanied on his New York stops by Gov. Mario
Cuomo and John F. Kennedy Jr., was returning to Boston after the
parade and was spending the afternoon preparing for his second and
final debate with Bush Thursday in Los Angeles. The Massachusetts
governor was flying to California on Tuesday and was to remain
there through the debate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
