<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RoarkLicense     10-10 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Roark License,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bar Counsel Recommends Three-Year Suspension for Former Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state bar association's
disciplinary counsel today recommended that former mayor Mike
Roark's be suspended from practicing law for nearly three years.
   In briefs filed with a subcommittee of the bar's Committee on
Legal Ethics, however, Roark's attorney argued that his client
should be suspended for no longer than a year.
   Subcommittee chairman Arthur Recht said he did not know when a
decision would be made.
   Roark, 43, a former state and federal prosecutor, pleaded guilty
Nov. 17 to six misdemeanor federal counts of cocaine possession. He
was released July 20 after serving 5{ months in prison, and was
placed on three years' probation.
   Roark, who agreed to resign as mayor as part of his plea,
testified before the bar's three-member tribunal that he did
nothing to turn in or prosecute the two men who supplied him with
cocaine.
   The bar's disciplinary counsel, Jack Marden, recommended that
Roark's license be suspended until he has finished his probation.
</TEXT>
