<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceCadet     10-10 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Cadet,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Probing 1985 Death of Police Cadet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's chief medical examiner has
reopened an investigation into the death of a state police academy
cadet in the wake of the hospitalization of 16 cadets at another
state academy.
   James Whitehouse, 22, of Braintree died in 1985 after training
at the police academy in Framingham. Then-Medical Examiner Luke
Tedeschi ruled that Whitehouse died from a genetic tendency to
develop a disorder known as malignant hyperthermia.
   However, Tedeschi has since called for the case to be reopened,
saying he made his diagnosis on the basis of faulty information,
including police claims that Whitehouse had been exercising only
moderately.
   Brian Blackbourne, the current state medical examiner, has
agreed to the request and started a new investigation into
Whitehouse's death.
   Last month, 16 cadets out of a class of 50 were hospitalized for
dehydration, kidney failure and other problems shortly after
beginning training at another state police academy, the one at
Agawam in western Massachusetts. One of the cadets later had to
have a liver transplant and remains in critical condition.
   Academy officials have said the training was stressful to
prepare the cadets for the stresses of police work, but not abusive.
   Those who inherit the tendency toward malignant hyperthermia, as
Whitehouse apparently did, may fall prey during surgery to a
potentially deadly combination of rapidly rising body temperature,
shock and other problems.
   But Tedeschi said there are no recorded cases of a person with
the tendency dying after exercising. In fact, he said, several
professional football players have the disorder.
   Police instructors have maintained that Whitehouse died of the
genetic disorder and that the cadet was not subjected to enough
strenuous exercise to cause heat stroke in a normal person. They
also have said that he received prompt medical attention.
   However attorney John Marani, who is representing the Whitehouse
family, said the cadet collapsed from heat stroke and was not given
medical assistance for 45 minutes.
   ``I feel the 45-minute delay directly resulted in his death,''
the attorney said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
