<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Greece-Palestinian     10-10 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Palestinian,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Council Decides To Extradite Terrorist Suspect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judicial council today decided to
extradite to the United States a Palestinian accused of planting a
bomb that killed one person and injured 15 aboard a Pan Am jetliner
over Hawaii in 1982.
   However, defense lawyers appealed to the Areos Pagos, Greece's
supreme court, to revoke the decision to extradite 39-year-old
Mohammed Rashid. The country's highest judicial body will hear the
case within a month.
   ``There is a majority decision by the council for extradition.
Its decision is based on a portion of the U.S. request,'' appeals
court judge Stavros Gardikiotis said. Under Greek law, the appeals
council examines cases that involve crimes committed outside Greece.
   Gardikiotis said there was enough evidence presented by the
United States to back up its charges that Rashid planted a bomb
aboard the jetliner. A Japanese teen-ager was killed and 15 people
injured in the explosion.
   The council rejected as ``insufficient'' other U.S. claims
linking Rashid to the attempted 1982 bombing of another Pan Am
jetliner in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. No details of the alleged
bombing attempt were released in court.
   The council had twice postponed hearing the extradition request
for Rashid, a member of the Palestine Liberation Organization, and
delayed issuing its decision for one week.
   ``This decision is a blow to the PLO,'' Rashid told The
Associated Press. ``I will repeat once again that neither I nor the
PLO engage in terrorism. I trust the Greek justice system and will
be vindicated by the Areos Pagos.''
   Rashid also may be linked to an attack aboard the Greek cruise
ship on July 11 that killed nine people and injured 98. Police
theorize the attack may have been a botched attempt to take the
ship hostage and force Rashid's release.
   The Palestinian was arrested at Athens airport May 29 after a
tip from the U.S. Embassy. He was sentenced to seven months
imprisonment on July 14 for entering Greece on a forged Syrian
passport.
   In a separate hearing today, an appeal court upheld Rashid's
passport conviction but reduced the sentence to five months. He was
allowed to pay a $400 fine instead of serving the sentence.
   ``This doesn't mean he can go free. He continues to be held
until the extradition request is heard by the Areos Pagos,'' said
Rashid's lawyer, Spyros Fitrakis. He said the defense will argue
that the Greek constitution ``forbids the extradition of aliens
prosecuted for their action as freedom fighters.''
   ``As a member of the PLO my client is a freedom fighter,''
Fitrakis said.
   The United States considers the PLO a terrorist organization.
   U.S. officials have claimed Rashid also was involved in the 1986
bombing of a TWA jetliner flying over southern Greece that killed
four Americans. The TWA blast is not mentioned in the extradition
request.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881010-0083 </DOCNO>
