<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BushFlap 1stLd-Writethru a0534 10-10 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush Flap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0534,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Knights of Columbus Local Leader Says Bush Not Welcome To Speak To
Group</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4th graf to show state leader of Knights embraced
visit</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's presidential campaign hastily
changed today's campaign event after a local Knights of Columbus
official said the vice president was not welcome to make a
political speech to the group.
   Bush toured an Italian bakery and neighborhood before speaking
to a gathering sponsored by an Italian-American group. Press
secretary Sheila Tate said the Knights of Columbus, a Roman
Catholic men's group, decided not to sponsor the speech because of
its tax status as a non-profit organization.
   ``The Knights of Columbus cannot and will not take part'' in a
program to be held for Bush, Grand Knight Ben Valeri told The Times
of Trenton. ``We're not a dictatorship. If members of the Knights
want to greet Bush or any other political (figure) or want to go to
the Bush speech, they can do so on their own. But not as members of
the Knights of Columbus.''
   However, the head of the state Knights of Columbus, Bernie
McGlone, stood up at the Bush gathering and declared: ``I want to
make it perfectly clear that the state council is sponsoring the
event ... and we're proud of it.''
   Valeri's wife had said earlier that her husband objected to the
visit because the Knights are supposed to be non-political.
   William Palatucci, executive director of the Bush campaign in
New Jersey, insisted that Valeri agreed during phone conversations
last week to take part in a Bush visit.
   ``I was as surprised as anyone to see his comments in the
paper,'' Palatucci said. ``When I spoke to him Thursday and Friday,
he said it would be an honor to have the vice president.''
   Local Bush organizer John Hansburg said Valeri's remarks
resulted from pressure by Democratic committeemen.
   ``He's closely connected to the Democratic organization,''
Hansburg said. ``They got to him.''
   Hansburg said he didn't know which committeemen may have
pressured Valeri and said he had no evidence to support his claims.
   Palatucci said Roman Hall, where the vice president was
scheduled to speak Monday, is frequently rented but not owned by
the Knights of Columbus.
</TEXT>
