<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolBusCollision 1stLd-Writethruka0540twackyofplayoffs.
  10-10 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Bus Collision, 1st Ld - Writethruk a0540,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20 Students, Driver Hurt When Truck Hits School Bus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with officials now saying 21 injured
included the bus driver; account of witnesses, superintendent,
other detail. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EVERETT, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tractor-trailer truck slammed into the
back of a school bus near here today, knocking both vehicles down
an embankment and injuring the bus driver and 20 students,
officials said.
   The students, ages 5 through 17, attended the Everett School
District in this community of about 1,800 people in the
south-central part of the state. Four of the pupils were
hospitalized, two in critical condition.
   School Superintendent Edward A. Vollbrecht said the truck hit
the bus from behind as the bus was accelerating from a stop. The
bus was en route to Everett Area Elementary School and Everett Area
High School, he said.
   Witnesses said the two vehicles tumbled down a 25-foot
embankment.
   ``The school bus was down over the bank on its side and the
tractor-trailer was down over the bank on its side,'' said Floyd
Roberts, a volunteer firefighter.
   Most of the children were taken to Memorial Hospital of Bedford,
where 16 were treated and released within three hours, said nursing
supervisor Beth Arnold. Bus driver Randy Mearkle, 33, of Everett,
was also treated and released, she said.
   Two children were admitted to the Bedford hospital, while two
others, ages 14 and 15, were in critical condition with head
injuries at Conemaugh Valley Memorial Hospital in Johnstown.
   ``Most of them were just shook up,'' Ms. Arnold. ``They had a
few cuts, bumps and bruises, but most of them were fine. They were
pretty good. They were well-behaved.''
