<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0527,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslems Attack Kabul, Jalalabad With Rockets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with 20 reported dead in
Jalalabad, rebels capture garrison. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``About
50,000...'' TRIMS to tighten.
^With PM-Afghan-New Tactics, Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas fired rockets into
Kabul, killing five or six people, a government official said
today. Official radio reported 20 people were killed today in a
rocket attack in Jalalabad.
   In Islamabad, Pakistan, a guerrilla spokesman today claimed the
rebel forces seized a small garrison in eastern Afghanistan,
capturing a fleet of military vehicles, a helicopter and a tank.
   In Kabul, the government official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said he did not know how many people were injured in the
Sunday night attack on the capital and could not provide further
details.
   State-run Radio Kabul said guerrillas bombed Jalalabad, killing
20 people and injuring 32. It said 20 rockets hit the town,
destroying at least two houses. The city is 70 miles east of Kabul.
   Azim Nasser-Zia, the spokesman for the National Islamic Front of
Afghanistan, said in Islamabad that the front's guerrillas last
week captured the garrison in the district of Gairu, 140 miles
southeast of Kabul.
   He said nine guerrillas were killed taking the garrison. He did
not list casualties suffered by the government or say whether
fighting continued.
   He said the guerrillas captured a helicopter, 100 small arms, 30
military vehicles and 10 tractors. The claims could not be
independently confirmed.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas have continued their attacks on
Soviet and Afghan troops despite the withdrawal of some Red Army
troops under terms of an accord signed in Geneva. Under terms of
the April 14 agreement, the Soviet Union is to complete its
withdrawal by Feb. 15, 1989.
   About 50,000 Soviets soldiers already have left. Between 50,000
and 60,000 remain, according to Soviet officials and Western
diplomats.
   Afghanistan and the Soviet Union have stepped up their effort
for a negotiated settlement to end the war that has been going on
since a pro-Moscow government was installed in 1978. In December
1979, Moscow dispatched troops to its southern neighbor to prop up
the government, which is dominated by a Soviet-style People's
Democratc Party of Afghanistan.
   Most of these efforts have taken the form of diplomatic pressure
on Pakistan to stop sheltering, supplying and arming the guerrillas.
   The party's Central Committee convened today and was expected to
consider further peace efforts.
   A Foreign Ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the meeting of the 500-member body was likely to continue
Tuesday.
   The party has about 200,000 members.
   During the spring, President Najib _ who is also the party's
leader _ named a new prime minister and four vice presidents in a
show of broadening the base of his government. The prime minister,
Mohammad Hassan Sharq, and two of the vice presidents are not party
members, but Sharq has long been known for his close association
with the party and with Moscow.
</TEXT>
