<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Angola 1stLd-Writethru a0638 10-10 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Make Headway On Cuban Withdrawal From Angola</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with officials saying prospects for agreement
brighter.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospects for a 4-nation agreement to pull
Cuban troops out of an African war were brighter today after
negotiators ``substantially narrowed the gap'' on their
differences, U.S. officials said.
   Although no final deal was struck, Cuban officials indicated
they were willing to step up the pace of the withdrawal of 50,000
troops from Angola as well as the 16,000 to 18,000 stationed near
the border with Namibia, the officials said.
   In exchange, South Africa would pull its troops from Namibia and
prepare the territory for independence and an election under United
Nations supervision of an assembly to draw up a constitution.
   But the officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
negotiators would have to meet again and that ``further significant
decisions will be required'' before a final agreement is concluded.
   The talks were held over the weekend in New York and involved
officials from Angola, Cuba, South Africa and the United States.
   There already was a tentative understanding that the Cuban
troops would withdraw over 24 to 30 months. Some trainers were to
remain behind to assist the Soviet-backed government in its war
with guerrillas supported by the United States and South Africa.
   However, the questions were whether the withdrawal would be
``front-end loaded,'' meaning a sizable pullout in the early stages
to make the retreat irreversible, and how quickly the troops near
the Namibian border would leave.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said further
talks would be held soon but that it may not be possible to reach
the Nov. 1 deadline set by the United Nations for transition to
independence for Namibia.
   Still, negotiators ``substantially narrowed the gap,'' one of
the officials told The Associated Press.
   In Johannesburg, Roland Darroll, a Foreign Affairs spokesman,
said South Africa, Cuba and Angola had agreed that Cuban troops
should be withdrawn from Angola within 24 to 30 months.
   ``That was the agreement in Brazzaville. It was subject to
consultation with the governments,'' he said.
   He said he had no further information.
   Negotiators had not expected a breakthough at the New York
meetings. They were hastily arranged because senior diplomats from
all the nations involved were in New York attending the 43rd U.N.
General Assembly.
   South Africa has linked its willingness to cooperate with a
one-year independence plan for neighboring South-West Africa, which
it rules, to the withdrawal of the Cuban troops. Pretoria, which
pulled its soldiers out of South-West Africa earlier this year,
says Cuba's forces threaten the territory's independence.
   Diplomats involved in the talks had said they were working
toward reaching agreement on a Cuban withdrawal timetable at a
formal meeting to be held sometime later this month in the West
African nation of Congo.
   That meeting will be crucial because the negotiators are running
out of time to achieve a compromise before Nov. 1. South Africa has
suggested that date for putting into effect the U.N.'s independence
plan for South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
