<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Icebreaker     10-10 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Icebreaker,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Icebreaker Stuck In Arctic With Nowhere To Go, Maybe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard icebreaker Polar Star is at
Prudhoe Bay in northern Alaska, preparing to travel east through
the Northwest Passage after finding its usual route to the west
blocked by ice, the Coast Guard said today.
   However, whether the Polar Star will be allowed to make the
trip, through waters claimed by Canada, has been left up to the
U.S. State Department, Lt. Pete Marsh said.
   The icebreaker Polar Sea traveled through the Northwest Passage
in 1985, drawing Canada's ire. The United States government
maintained then that the Northwest Passage was an international
waterway.
   Rita Ragsdale, of the State Department's watch office, said
today that no press officer was on duty to comment because of the
Columbus Day holiday.
   A decision on whether to dispatch the Polar Star presumably
could have a further political impact in that the U.S.-Canada trade
agreement has stalled in the Canadian parliament. Congress has
already approved it.
   If the vessel doesn't head east, said Marsh, it would have to
winter over in the Arctic with a skeleton crew, as it did in 1981.
   He said that while the Polar Star was preparing for departure,
no decision had been made to head east.
   ``It's definite only that they cannot head west,'' he said.
``They tried a couple of days ago and couldn't break through.''
   The Polar Star had been on a normal Arctic research trip,
supporting scientists and their work, when it was delayed because
of assistance rendered to two Canadian icebreakers and because of
its own mechanical problems, Marsh said.
   ``It took a couple of days, and it was a couple of days too
many,'' Marsh said.
   If the Polar Star is to escape to the east, a decision will have
to be made soon, he said, before that route also freezes in.
   The Polar Star wintered over in 1981 in the Arctic, and it could
again, said Marsh. Most of its 140-member crew would be shipped
south to wait.
   But if the Polar Star is out of service over the winter, he
said, it could not be used as backup to its sister ship, the Polar
Sea. The Polar Sea leaves Seattle in a few weeks for the Antarctic.
</TEXT>
