<HEAD>Report New Generation of Locusts Forming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new generation of desert locust swarms has been
forming throughout the Sahelian countries of Africa and in the
Sudan despite intensified control measures, a United Nations agency
said Monday.
   New swarms are ``forming relentlessly'' because continuing rain
has created favorable breeding conditions, said Edouard Saouma,
director-general of the Food and Agriculture Organization.
   Up to now, serious damage to crops has been prevented, he added.
   The locust invasion in North Africa, described as the region's
worst in three decades, began earlier this year.
   The FAO also reported that swarms of locusts have reached Gambia
and in Cape Verde. Large-scale breeding of the pests was reported
in northern Ethiopia.
