<TEXT>
   Actress-turned-novelist Joan Collins revealed
Monday her ambition to appear on the London stage.
   ``I have every intention of going back into the theater in
England and there are a number of theatrical producers who know of
my interest and keep talking to me about various plays,'' Miss
Collins said.
   The 55-year-old star of ``Dynasty'' trained for the stage 40
years ago at London's prestigious Royal Academy of Dramatic Art,
but most of her work has been before cameras.
   ``There are so many Noel Coward plays and a lot of others that
would be right for someone of my age,'' said Miss Collins who is in
London to promote her first novel, ``Prime Time,'' the story of
back-stabbing executives in the world of television.
   Miss Collins told a news conference she has already started work
on a second novel.
   ``I am superstitious of talking about it before I've finished
it, but I can tell you it's not about television,'' she said.
   ``I wrote the first 50,000 words on holiday this summer. It
should be out the year after next.''
