<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LorraineResident     10-10 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lorraine Resident,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lorraine Protester Continues Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven months of bad weather, mosquitoes
and fear of living alone on the streets haven't halted Jacqueline
Smith's stubborn sidewalk protest outside the small motel where
Martin Luther King Jr. died.
   ``I'll be here for as long as it takes,'' she said, standing
beside a makeshift plastic tent that serves as her living quarters
outside The Lorraine Motel, where King was assassinated 20 yuears
ago.
   Miss Smith, 37, was evicted from the motel by sheriff's deputies
on March 2.
   A resident of The Lorraine since 1972, she refused to leave when
the crumbling motel was closed last January to eventually become
the centerpiece of a civil rights museum.
   ``I've been maintaining. I don't have any complaints,'' Miss
Smith said last week. ``I knew this wouldn't be easy.''
   She sleeps on a reclining lawn chair covered by sheets and
plastic and preaches to all who will listen that the museum is part
of a conspiracy to gentrify her downtown neighborhood.
   ``What they're trying to do is force the black people out and
they're using The Lorraine as a focus,'' she said.
   The area of The Lorraine, made up largely of warehouses and
rundown rental housing, was designated a historic district in 1982
and developers have launched several renovation projects there for
apartments, condominiums and offices.
   ``They're using The Lorraine Motel to get this land. They're not
fooling anybody,'' Miss Smith said.
   The Lorraine belongs to ``the people,'' she said, and should be
used as housing for the homeless or for some other public purpose.
   While hesitant to talk about her life on the street, she said
her food is supplied by friends and supporters who also donate
money from time to time. She has toilet privileges at a nearby
apartment, and she said a security guard has kept her company at
night for part of her vigil.
   ``The majority of the time I'm here alone, but I have great
moral and spiritual support,'' she said.
   A folding table beside her tent held several large pictures of
King, a jar for donations and a notebook for visitors to sign.
Three scraggly potted plants offered the only softening to the
concrete scene.
   ``Every now and then there are people who come by and scream
things out of their cars, but they pass so fast I can't even
understand what they're saying,'' Miss Smith said.
   Once, she said, a street person hit her with his fist for some
unknown reason.
   A rainy cold wave struck shortly after her vigil began and
temperatures during the summer topped 100 degrees. Insect repellant
used to combat mosquitoes caused a rash on her arms and hands.
   D'Army Bailey, a principal supporter of the museum, said he has
failed to convince Miss Smith that the project will be a monument
to King.
   ``There doesn't seem to be any rational, logical tone to her
perception of things,'' Bailey said.
   Part of the motel will be razed but the wing where King was
killed will be restored and will be at the heart of the museum.
Construction will begin in about three months, Bailey said, and the
museum should be finished in 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
