<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Rebels,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudanese Rebels Claim To Kill 62 Soldiers, Capture Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels in southern Sudan today claimed
they killed 62 government soldiers and captured a small town during
a three-day battle.
   The clandestine radio of the Sudan People's Liberation Army said
in a report monitored in Nairobi that 300 soldiers fled to nearby
Uganda when its guerillas captured Ikotos town in eastern
Equatorial Province on Friday.
   ``SPLA fighters have taken positions on the Sudanese side, but
because of the respect we have for international borders we cannot
cross into Uganda,'' the radio said. ``We urge the fugitives to
surrender. If they surrender without their arms, no harm will be
done to them.''
   The radio made no mention of rebel casualties, and it was not
possible to independently verify its report.
   The Sudan People's Liberation Army took up arms in 1983 against
the Moslem-dominated government in Khartoum, demanding more
autonomy for the mainly Christian and animist south. The rebel
movement claims control of 90 percent of the southern countryside
and small towns.
   Thousands of civilians fleeing the war and the food shortages it
has caused have headed to larger towns such as Juba or to northern
Sudan, but relief officials say many have starved to death on the
way.
