<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Czechoslovakia 2ndLd-Writethru a0596 10-10 0714</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0596,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Premier, Slovak Premier Resign In Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1 graf for 10th pvs, ``In his...'' to ADD that Jakes did
not name other officials whose titles changed. Pickup 11th graf
pvs, ``Jakes was...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovak Premier Lubomir
Strougal, who headed the federal government for more than 18 years,
and Slovak Premier Peter Colotka resigned today, the state news
agency CTK reported.
   The announcement was made by Communist Party chief Milos Jakes
in a speech at a plenary session of the party's Central Committee.
   He said the resignations were accepted.
   Strougal, believed to be the longest-serving premier in Europe,
replaced Oldrich Cernik in January 1970.
   Colotka has served as Slovak premier since May 1969 and as
Czechoslovak deputy premier since September 1969.
   Czechoslovakia consists of two republics of equal rights, the
Czech Socialist Republic and the Slovak Socialist Republic.
   Each is governed by a National Council, which delegates to an
overall Federal Assembly responsibility for constitutional and
foreign affairs, defense and important economic decisions.
   The primary source of power in Czechoslovakia is the Communist
Party.
   The shake-up in Czechoslovakia follows similar government
reorganizations in the Soviet Union, Hungary and Poland.
   In his speech, Jakes also said changes were made in the
top-ruling Politburo, the party secretariat, the Central Committee
itself and federal, Czech and Slovak governments. However, he did
not name the effected officials.
   Jakes was quoted as saying the proposed changes, ``proceed from
the need for a new deployment of leading cadres in the intereest of
mastering the demanding tasks of economic and social
restructuring.''
   There have long been rumors about top-level changes in
Czechoslovakia and Jakes and other officials indicated for some
time that younger people would be promoted to senior positions.
   In remarks winding up a two-day session of the Central Committee
on April 9, Jakes said the leadership wanted ``to elevate younger
comrades, and thus create conditions for further successful
fulfillment of party tasks.''
   He then also said it was ``an important requirement to ensure
that qualified young people are more frequently proposed'' for key
economic and other jobs.
   At today's meeting, opening a two-day plenary session on
ideology, Jakes also proposed that the next party congress be moved
forward by one year and take place in 1990.
   Jakes also made clear that unlike in neighboring Hungary
independent human rights, ecological and other groups would not be
allowed to operate.
   He warned that formation and operation of ``anti-Socialist
political structures'' will not be tolerated and will be prosecuted.
   The meeting was called a week after the Communist party's ruling
presidium, or Politburo, met Wednesday to discuss personnel changes
amid speculation that Politburo member Vasil Bilak, who has long
held the key ideology portfolio, may also retire.
   A fellow ideologist, Jan Fojtik, was promoted to the ruling
Politburo in April and has appeared increasingly to oversee the
important function.
   Fojtik's promotion was one of the few changes made in
Czechoslovakia's top leadership since Milos Jakes replaced
President Gustav Husak as Communist party leader in December.
   The CTK news agency earlier reported the meeting would discuss
an ``evaluation'' of conclusions from two recent party sessions and
the ``tasks of ideological work of the party in the conditions of
restructuring.''
   In a highly surprising article carried by the party daily Rude
Pravo last week, a senior party official called for ``resolute
condemnation of egocentrism, the wish to stand at the head of the
party ... as long as possible and thus to prevent the younger
generation from enganging in decision-making.''
   Rudolf Hegenbart, who heads a Central Committee department
responsible for state administration, demanded accountability of
all leading cadres and ``more personal courage in admitting that `I
am no longer able to carry on the entrusted office.'''
   Most Czechoslovak leaders are well into their sixties, and some,
such as President Husak and Federal Assembly (Parliament) president
Alois Indra were known to be ailing or gravely ill.
   ``The working people want to elect representatives whom they
trust and not those who twist and turn like a weather wane when the
so-called new wind starts to blow (or) those who bear
responsibility for having brought the economy and other social
sectors into critical situations and yet call today for new
principles of management,'' Hegenbart told Rude Pravo.
</TEXT>
