<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NAACPMeeting     10-10 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NAACP Meeting,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NAACP National Board Ties Evers Remembrance to Voter Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NAACP National Board is planning a
nationwide get-out-the-vote campaign keyed to the 25th anniversary
of the murder of Mississippi civil rights leader Medgar Evers.
   Posters featuring Evers, which are being distributed across the
country to chapters of the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People, will be officially unveiled during the the
board's meeting here Thursday through Saturday, said Earl
Shinhoster, NAACP regional director from Atlanta.
   ``Black voters can make a significant difference if they turn
out in record numbers for the Nov. 8 election. Those records are
going to have to be higher than 1984's,'' Shinhoster said in an
interview Monday. ``We really believe we need to have 70 to 80
percent black voter turnout to make a difference in the election.''
   He said an estimated 45 percent to 60 percent of blacks
nationwide voted in the 1984 presidential election.
   The NAACP hopes blacks can be the decisive bloc in the
presidential race between Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts and
Vice President George Bush.
   Though the NAACP doesn't formally endorse candidates, Shinhoster
said in a recent news release, ``This year's presidential election
provides a clear and unmistakable choice between the politics of
Reaganomics and Reaganism and the politics of hope and
opportunity.''
   The posters featuring photographs of Evers, Mississippi's first
NAACP field secretary who was slain on June 12, 1963, state: ``On
Tuesday, Nov. 8, 1988, help us fulfill Medgar Evers' goals.''
   Those goals are listed as equal opportunity, fair housing
practice, justice and human rights, adequate health care, job
opportunities and better schools.
   No one was ever convicted of the ambush slaying of the
37-year-old Evers outside his Jackson home. Byron De La Beckwith
was charged with the shooting but two trials ended with deadlocked
juries.
</TEXT>
