<HEAD>Bush Opens Up Lead Among Hoosier Voters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush and running mate Dan
Quayle, a home-grown senator, hold a double-digit lead over
Democrat Michael Dukakis among Indiana voters, according to a new
presidential poll released Monday.
   The survey of more than 1,000 registered voters showed Bush with
47.6 percent support, compared with 31 percent for Dukakis and 21
percent still undecided.
   The Hoosier state controls 12 electoral votes in the November
presidential election.
   The 1988 Election Poll was conducted Oct. 6-9 by the Public
Opinion Laboratory at Indiana University-Purdue University at
Indianapolis and has a 3 percent margin of error.
