<DOCNO> AP881010-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1631EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FinancialFugitive     10-10 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Financial Fugitive,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two of Fugitive's Foreign Bank Accounts Reported Frozen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have frozen two foreign bank accounts
belonging to a fugitive financial planner who was captured in
Japan, spurring hopes that clients may be able to recover some of
the $20 million reported missing.
   Court-appointed receiver James Feltman said Monday he filed
lawsuits freezing Henry Gherman's bank accounts in two countries.
The Miami accountant said investigators were preparing to freeze a
third foreign account.
   Feltman said the freezing of the accounts increases the
likelihood that a substantial amount of the missing money will be
recovered, and Allen said Gherman's arrest over the weekend ``will
only help the case.''
   Both Feltman and his attorney, Richard Allen, refused to
identify the countries where Gherman's accounts were found, but
they said the countries are known for strict banking secrecy laws.
   Details of Gherman's financial arrangements could alert the
money manager's associates, Fletman and Allen said, and allow them
to empty the accounts before pending court actions are resolved.
   The FBI announced Saturday Gherman had been arrested in Tokyo.
   Gherman was sought on federal charges filed Aug. 29 of mail
fraud and embezzlement. He fled Miami two weeks earlier, leaving
notes of apology to his bilked investment clients.
   Up to 50 Miami-area investors, including several doctors and
nurses, may have lost as much as $20 million through Gherman over
the past decade.
   Feltman said the accounts frozen could hold anywhere from
hundreds of thousands of dollars to millions of dollars.
   ``But nothing has been verified,'' he said. ``We don't know
exactly how much because of the banking secrecy laws in those
countries, and that's making this stage of our investigation a very
thorny and delicate process.''
   Gherman is being held at Tokyo's Kosugi Prison in a detention
center for foreign prisoners. He is expected to face a preliminary
extradition hearing later this week, according to FBI spokesman
Paul Miller.
   Feltman said Japanese authorities have been asked if Gherman is
willing to cooperate in the investigation but have not responded
yet.
   Miller said Gherman first arrived in Taipei, Taiwan, on a
legitimate visa in his own name 11 days after fleeing Florida. He
subsequently registered at two Taipei hotels under his own name and
made numerous intercontinental telephone calls to the United States
using his own name. After U.S. authorities located him they
arranged for his expulsion to Japan.
   Feltman said the foreign bank accounts were traced through
records Gherman left at his North Miami Beach offices and through a
series of financial transactions the financial planner made before
his disappearance in August.
</TEXT>
