<DOCNO> AP881010-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1631EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeerCan-Mouse     10-10 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beer Can-Mouse,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvey Arraigned On Tampering, Extortion Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claimed he found a mouse in
a can of Coors beer pleaded innocent Monday to charges of extortion
and tampering.
   James N. Harvey, 30, was charged Sept. 27 with a state law that
prohibits tampering with consumer products and with extortion for
asking representatives of the Adolph Coors Co. for $35,000 in
exchange for the can of beer and the mouse.
   He remained free on bond and a pretrial hearing was scheduled
for Friday. If convicted of both counts, Harvey could face up to 30
years in prison.
   Harvey, a construction worker, claimed he purchased a can of
Coors on July 27 and discovered a mouse after taking a few swallows.
   On July 29, Harvey called the Coors' consumer hot line and
reported finding the rodent. Coors initially offered to pay $1,500
for the mouse and the can, but he refused and later asked for
$35,000.
   A judge later ordered Harvey to turn over both the mouse and the
can for testing.
   A University of Florida pathologist determined that, based on
the amount of decomposition, the rodent could not have been in the
can when it was packaged on May 13. That conclusion, however, was
disputed by a pathologist hired by Gary Pajcic, an attorney
representing Harvey at the time.
   Harvey is charged with violating the state statute of consumer
product tampering, enacted in 1987 following cases involving
pain-reliever capsules, including Tylenol, said Assistant State
Attorney E. McRae Mathis.
   The statute carries a maximum sentence of 15 years and a $5,000
fine. The extortion count also carries a 15-year prison term.
   Coors has sued Harvey claiming that he defamed the company's
product and attempted to defraud the company.
   Coors, based in Golden, Colo., claims it has spent $500,000
defending its reputation as a result of the adverse publicity, and
the local Coors distributor, Neal Tyler and Sons Inc., said it has
lost $100,000 in sales.
</TEXT>
