<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Sarandon     10-10 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Sarandon,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Bull Durham' Star Offers Tips For Watching World Series</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 6 p.m. EDT, Time set by source.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball fans trying to pick a team in this
year's World Series should check out the players' waists, according
to actress Susan Sarandon, who portrayed a baseball groupie in the
hit movie ``Bull Durham.''
   ``Never root for a team whose uniforms have elastic stretch
waistbands,'' Ms. Sarandon writes in the Oct. 15 issue of TV Guide
magazine. ``They are unsightly and without grace. ... It is the
reason the Cubs never make it.''
   Game 1 of the 1988 World Series is scheduled to begin at 8 p.m.
EDT Saturday and will be televised on NBC. The Oakland Athletics
will play the winner of the National League Championship Series
between the Los Angeles Dodgers and the New York Mets.
   Speaking as Annie Savoy _ the movie's believer in biorhythms,
mysticism and the ``Church of Baseball'' _ Miss Sarandon urges
viewer to root only for teams with belt loops, an undomed stadium
and no artificial turf.
   ``Keep an eye on the Oakland A's,'' she says. ``They play on
grass, under the sky and have terrific belt loops. Plus they've got
a circus elephant on their sleeves.''
   Miss Sarandon also says all series should go for seven games.
   ``It's a holy, magic number, a prime number, and a seventh game
assures the longest possible baseball season,'' she says. ``And the
shortest possible winter unless you go to Puerto Rico for winter
ball, where you can discover the next Jose Canseco while eating
fish soup in the bleachers at Santurce.''
   Among her other tips for viewers, Miss Sarandon says:
   _Disconnect phones.
   _Don't use remote control. ``To be shopping around, switching
channels, shows a lack of respect.''
   _Place the TV screen facing north, feet pointing south and
``refreshments at equidistant points to the east and west.''
   _Avoid health food. ``Nachos, dip, beer and hot dogs are
spiritually correct,'' she says. ``Your biosystem will adjust and
forgive you.''
   _Don't watch in curlers.
   _Wear loose clothes to avoid fainting when emotions peak.
   _Stick with one team, even if its situation seems desperate.
``Miracles can happen,'' she says. ``They have in the past and they
will again. You've just gotta believe in the Church of Baseball.''
</TEXT>
