<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hostages     10-10 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waite Still Missing After Reported Release Deadline Passes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church of England envoy Terry Waite
remained missing Monday after the deadline for his release reported
by a Beirut newspaper passed with no sign of the British hostage
negotiator.
   The conservative Al-Anwar daily, which is based in Christian
east Beirut, on Friday quoted an unidentified source as predicting
that Waite would be freed in 72 hours.
   Waite, 48, disappeared Jan. 20, 1987, after leaving his hotel in
Moslem west Beirut for a rendezvous with the captors of two
American hostages.
   Lebanon's media has reported at least 25 times this year that
Waite or others among the 14 foreigners missing in Lebanon were
about to be released. None was.
   This year's release of five hostages _ three Frenchmen, a West
German and an Indian _ all were signaled in advance by communiques
from the captors.
   None was independently predicted by Lebanese radio stations or
newspapers.
   The weekly Ash-Shiraa magazine, which gained international fame
after breaking the story of the secret U.S. arms sales to Iran in
November 1986, has published at least 10 erroneous predictions that
a hostage release was imminent this year.
   It reported Friday that the release last week of Indian
professor Mithileshawr Singh, a legal resident alien of the United
States, by Shiite Moslem kidnappers after 20 months in captivity,
marked ``the beginning of the release of more American hostages.''
   It said Waite would be freed ``very soon'' and American hostages
would be released before the U.S. presidential election Nov.8.
   Waite was in Lebanon to help gain the freedom of Americans Terry
Anderson and Thomas Sutherland when he disappeared. Although no
group has claimed to hold him, Lebanese officials believe he is
held by Shiite extremists.
   Anderson and Sutherland are held by Islamic Jihad, a pro-Iranian
Shiite faction.
   Apart from Waite, Anderson and Sutherland, seven other
Americans, three Britons, an Irishman and an Italian are missing in
Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881010-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     10-10 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Enrile Denies Involvement in Alleged Plot Against Aquino</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile on
Monday denied a published report that he and his sister were
involved in an alleged plot to topple President Corazon Aquino.
   The Philippine Daily Globe quoted National Security Adviser
Emanuel Soriano as saying a senator and his sister _ whom the
newspaper identified as Enrile and Irma Ponce Enrile Potenciano _
were linked to the plan.
   The newspaper quoted Soriano as saying Enrile would fund the
alleged plot to be staged Jan. 6.
   Enrile denied the allegations in a radio interview on Monday.
   ``I am calling Soriano a liar,'' Enrile said. ``I challenge
Soriano to come out with details of the (plan) so that we can
discuss it in any proper forum.''
   Soriano also denied the Globe report in a separate radio
interview, saying ``I don't know who came out with that story ... I
am making an official denial.''
   According to the Globe, buses owned by Mrs. Potenciano were to
transport renegade soldiers led by Lt. Col. Gregorio Honasan, who
organized an attempted coup against Mrs. Aquino on Aug. 28, 1987,
in which at least 53 people were killed and more than 300 others
wounded.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos told reporters he was aware of the
rumored plot but said his information was based on ``raw
intelligence'' and that Honasan was unlikely to be capable of
mounting another coup.
   Honasan was arrested in December and escaped from prison in
April. He was Enrile's security chief when the senator was defense
minister under former President Ferdinand Marcos. Enrile was fired
in November 1986 after a failed coup by his followers.
   Also Monday, a Manila court dismissed a petition by Marcos to
return home, where he was to testify in a trial on alleged bribes
his administration received during 20 years in power.
   Marcos and his family fled to Hawaii after the 1986 revolt that
swept Mrs. Aquino to the presidency.
   The court dismissed Marcos' petition to return home, where he
faces 39 civil cases on charges he embezzled up to $10 billion
during his rule. He has not been charged with criminal violations
and Philippine law bans trials in absentia.
   ``Marcos can answer the charges by disposition, which is by
issuing legal statements from his home in Honolulu,'' the court
resolution said.
   Marcos had asked the court to let him return and act as his own
counsel during the deposition, but the court said Marcos' return
was a political issue requiring a decision by the Aquino government.
   Mrs. Aquino has repeatedly refused to allow her predecessor to
return on grounds of national security.
   In another development, Philippine and U.S. officials have
finished talks on U.S. bases and an agreement on their status
through 1991 would emerge within a week, according to a highly
reliable source.
   The source said Philippine and U.S. officials have finished
talks to determine compensation, security and other issues
regarding four U.S. bases.
   ``It's over. An agreement is possible within a few days, maybe
within a week's time,'' said the source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``There was compromise on both sides,'' he added without
elaborating.
   The Philippine panel was reportedly asking $1.2 billion a year
for the use of the bases, but U.S. officials are offering only half
that amount.
   Panels from both countries began reviewing the status of Clark
Air Base, Subic Bay Naval Base and four smaller installations in
April, but the talks stalled over compensation and other issues.
   Foreign Secretary Raul Manglapus has been meeting with U.S.
officials in New York and Washington since September to discuss the
bases. He is expected to return to Manila this week.
   The United States maintains the bases under a 1947 agreement
that expires in 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
