<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     10-10 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arabs Say Rioters Casting Votes With Their Stones</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians contend Arab
rioters are casting votes when they hurl stones in the occupied
territories because the Arab rebellion has critically influenced
Israel's upcoming general election.
   ``We are very aware of the impact of throwing stones,'' said
Burhan Attalah, 24, a teacher from Bethlehem who was jailed for six
months without trial for anti-Israeli activism. ``The Palestinian
problem is reaching the bedroom of every Israeli.''
   In campaigning Monday in the coastal city of Ashkelon, Labor
Party leader Shimon Peres met with loud applause when he said the
only result of Israel giving up occupied territory would be ridding
itself of 1.5 million Arabs.
   But Attalah, like many Palestinians, believes the 10-month
uprising has strengthened the electoral prospects of right-wing
rival Yitzhak Shamir _ and stymied hopes of a negotiated
Arab-Israeli peace settlement soon.
   The uprising, which has left more than 290 Palestinians and six
Israelis dead, has become a major issue in the Nov. 1 parliamentary
election. Films of stone-throwing Palestinian protesters even have
been used in campaign ads.
   Some Palestinians said they favored Peres' left-leaning Labor
Party because he supports exchanging some land in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip for peace.
   However, even Labor supporters conceded that though Peres, the
foreign minister, might bring peace talks more quickly, only Prime
Minister Shamir's hard-line Likud bloc can deliver a long-term
solution to the conflict.
   ``The peace process might start earlier with the Labor Party,''
said Jack Khazmo, owner of the pro-Palestine Liberation
Organization weekly Al Bayader Assiyasi. ``But with the Likud it
could ultimately be stronger.''
   The reason, Khazmo said, is that without Likud there cannot be
the nationwide consensus required to initiate a peace process or
make the territorial concessions demanded by Palestinians.
   Shamir has opposed a U.S.-backed international conference on
Middle East peace supported by Peres, his governing partner. Shamir
also has refused to concede any of the land Israel seized during
the 1967 Middle East war and supports expanded Jewish settlements
on the land.
   ``If Shamir wins, this means Israel isn't convinced there is a
Palestinian problem. But after another year or two, when Israelis
see they cannot crush the Palestinian uprising by force and the
only answer is to negotiate _ at that moment the peace process
could be stronger than with a Labor victory,'' Khazmo said.
   ``If the Likud wins, it will introduce even stronger tactics to
try to crush the uprising,'' said Ziad Abbas, a 24-year-old
free-lance journalist from Bethlehem who served six months in
prison for allegedly inciting protests. ``And that will cause the
rebellion to explode even further.''
   With Labor and Likud running neck-and-neck in polls, Khazmo said
``the worst possible scenario'' would be a draw leading to another
uneasy coalition between the two parties, which he called ``another
government with its hands tied in terms of a peace process.''
   Later Monday, assailants threw a stone at Peres' car as it
passed through Kiryat Gat, a town developed by the government and
mainly populated by North African immigrants who lean toward Likud.
   The stone caused minor damage to the roof, Israel radio said.
Peres was not hurt, and the assailants fled, the radio said.
</TEXT>
