<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     10-10 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memory of Dead Leaders Dominate Pakistan's Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The campaign for Pakistan's first
free elections in a decade began over the weekend with the
formation of alliances inspired by the memory of dead leaders.
   The political battle lines were drawn between the eight-party
Islamic Democratic Alliance and the Pakistan People's Alliance _
two groups whose members supported the late President Mohammed Zia
ul-Haq _ and the opposition Pakistan People's Alliance _ a moderate
three-party coalition led by Benazir Bhutto.
   Zia, who led Pakistan for 11 years, died in an Aug. 17 plane
crash. He seized power in a 1977 coup by ousting Ms. Bhutto's
father _ socialist Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto _ and
ordering him hanged two years later.
   Ms. Bhutto will lead her party into Nov. 16 elections that are
widely considered to be the first free elections in Pakistan since
Bhutto's death.
   On Sunday, Ms. Bhutto invited Pakistani reporters into her
Karachi home to announce that her party, if elected, would form a
coalition government with the eight parties that form the Movement
for the Restoration of Democracy, a left-leaning coalition.
   Mohammed Khan Junejo, who served as Zia's prime minister for
three years, failed to heal a split among Zia loyalists. Zia in May
fired Junejo and other members of the Pakistan Muslim League who
formed the Cabinet, but kept on several other loyalists in an
interim government.
   That governing group, headed by chief Minister Nawaz Sharif,
formed its own faction in September.
   The Islamic Democratic Alliance, headed by the Nawaz faction,
and the Pakistan People's Alliance, headed by the more moderate
Junejo forces, both support Zia's program of making Islam the law
of Pakistan and his staunch military backing of anti-communist
Moslem rebels in Afghanistan.
   Both groups draw support from Zia's traditional power base of
business, wealthy landowners and the military. But the division
among the Zia loyalists is fueled by Junejo's bitterness after Zia
accused his government of corruption and incompetence.
   Ms. Bhutto espouses her father's populism and has inherited his
broad support among the masses, but she has pulled her party away
from his socialist economic policies, including nationalization of
industries.
   She also has pledged to continue Zia's Afghan policy and has
called for continued close ties with the United States.
   But Ms. Bhutto has said that Islam should remain a religion and
not enter politics, saying Islamisation would affect women's rights
and the country's system of justice.
   Ms. Bhutto's allies are expected to do well in the elections,
possibly winning a simple majority in a new national assembly.
   Later this week, the federal election commission is to allocate
symbols to each party to aid the illiterate, who comprise nearly
three-fourths of the country's 48 million voters. The approved list
of 82 symbols include pictures of a car, a slingshot and a
butterfly.
</TEXT>
