<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Rights     10-10 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Rights,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Disputes Western Counts of Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About a dozen people still are imprisoned under
two of the main laws that have been used against political
dissidents, a Soviet official said Monday.
   Alexei Glukhov, deputy chief of the Soviet Foreign Ministry's
department for humanitarian and cultural relations, also told the
Tass news agency that Western estimates of more than 200 Soviets
jailed for religious or political beliefs under those laws or
others are untrue.
   The London-based human rights group Amnesty International
estimated that about 200 Soviets were prisoners of conscience as of
the beginning of September.
   Without mentioning Amnesty International, Glukhov said such
estimates are four to five times too high, and include many people
who are ``black marketeers and thieves, murderers and spies, people
who committed military crimes, traitors, and mental patients under
compulsory medical treatment,'' Glukhov said.
   The Soviet Union released many political prisoners beginning in
1987, and prominent figures such as independent journalist Sergei
Grigoryants and religious activist Alexander Ogorodnikov have
stayed out of jail for the most part since then despite periodic
scrapes with the law.
   Those arrested for taking part in demonstrations now are more
likely to be sentenced to 10- or 15-day jail terms, or fined.
   Glukhov said about a dozen people convicted under articles of
the Soviet criminal code against anti-Soviet agitation and
propaganda or defaming the system remain in jail.
   Soviet officials have said they are studying those two laws as
part of a review of the criminal code to make them more precise and
prevent future abuses.
   Others who were tried under those laws have been found to be
mentally ill and have been sent for compulsory treatment, Glukhov
said.
   The Soviet Union quit the World Psychiatric Association in 1983
in the face of almost certain expulsion because of revelations of
the use of psychiatry against mentally healthy political dissidents.
   In January, the Soviet Union announced new laws that it said
would prohibit such abuse of psychiatry.
   Glukhov said the number of Soviets held under laws on political
and religious activity ``keeps diminishing every day as cases are
reviewed, people are released from penal institutions even before
completing their terms or checked out of psychiatric hospitals
after a re-examination.''
   ``The continuing propaganda campaign in the West does not take
into account the stable trend for creating a law-governed state and
humanizing every aspect of life in the U.S.S.R.,'' Glukhov said.
   He charged that the Western reports were aimed at sabotaging a
Vienna conference on security and cooperation in Europe, and Soviet
proposals to hold a human rights conference in Moscow. The head of
the U.S. delegation to the conference, Ambassador Warren
Zimmermann, confirmed last week that Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze told Secretary of State George P. Shultz last month
about 40 political prisoners will be released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
