<DOCNO> AP881010-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Falklands     10-10 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Falklands,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Falklands Immigration Issue Stirs Heated Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The people of the Falkland Islands are demanding
that immigration to the south Atlantic archipelago be restricted to
10 families a year, according to the Falkland Islands Association.
   The London-based association, which fosters links with the 2,000
inhabitants of the British colony, says citizens attending a recent
public meeting in the capital of Stanley said immigration should be
restricted to 40 people a year.
   The association's newsletter reported in its latest issue that
the islanders' supporters in Britain were ``startled'' because many
in Britain would like the population to rise to 10,000 and expand
the economy, which relies solely on fishing and sheep farming.
   The newsletter canvassed opinion among residents of the island,
300 miles east of Argentina, and reported a variety of responses.
   Kitty Bertrand of Stanley worried that Britain would dump
undesirables on the islands.
   ``We do not want masses of people rushed in who cannot do a
hands' turn for themselves. We want do-it-yourself types. Good
sensible British people suitable for our way of life,'' she wrote.
   Sydney Miller said: ``We need people, especially tradesmen, but
we have nowhere to put them.''
   Legislative councilor Robin Lee of Port Howard also cited a
housing shortage, and added: ``If you increase (immigration) too
quickly, the local population becomes the minority and will have
little say in the way the country is being run.''
   Lee said the islanders feel that a population of 5,000 in 10 to
15 years ``is about right.''
   Tim Miller of Manybranch Farm wrote to suggest 100 immigrants a
year for the next three years. ``I feel most of us want change ...
but we want it to be at a pace we can influence, to minimize the
bad things and maximize the benefits of the 20th century.''
   Norma Edwards, a former Stanley councilor, wrote: ``We've plenty
of space for lots more people, but we can't expect them to sit on a
wind-blown peat bog without being able to offer them a satisfying
and rewarding future.''
   Mike Summers, an association member, told The Associated Press
that hundreds of Britons have applied to immigrate to the islands
but are being turned away for lack of housing.
   Summers said the issue was controversial because the islanders
``tend to be protective about their way of life. They're most
afraid that their quiet well-behaved sort of place will be affected
if it's flooded with immigrants.''
   The islands are claimed by Argentina as the Malvinas. In 1982,
Argentine troops overran the archipelago but surrendered to a
British task force after a 74-day war.
   Talks have since deadlocked over Britain's refusal to accept an
Argentine demand that the question of sovereignty be on the agenda.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
