<HEAD>TV Writer-Producer Alex Gottlieb Dies At 81</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alex Gottlieb, a TV producer who staged such
programs as ``The Bob Hope Chrysler Theater,'' ``The Donna Reed
Show'' and ``The Smothers Brothers Show,'' has died of a cerebral
hemorrhage at age 81.
   The Russian-born Gottlieb was a patient at the Motion Picture
and Television Hospital in Woodland Hills, where he died Sunday,
said hospital spokeswoman Jean Ferris.
   Gottlieb, who produced more than 50 television shows during a
career that spanned four decades, also wrote several film scripts
and Broadway plays.
   His film credits include ``I'll Take Sweden,'' ``Susan Slept
Here,'' ``Macho'' and ``Hollywood Canteen.'' He also wrote the
stage version of ``Susan Slept Here,'' ``Separate Rooms,'' ``Two
For The Money'' and ``Your Place Or Mine?''
   Gottlieb is survived by his wife, Ruth, and son, Stephen.
