<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1942EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WellsFargo     10-10 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wells Fargo,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wells Fargo Trial Set To Start After Three Years of Delays</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After more than three years of arguments,
motions and other legal maneuvers, a federal trial is set to begin
Tuesday for five people accused in the $7.1 million theft from a
Wells Fargo depot in 1983.
   The five are accused of participating in a conspiracy to plot
the heist and transport the stolen cash, not of carrying out the
robbery.
   The government contends that the robbery, the second-largest in
U.S. history, was plotted by Los Macheteros, a Puerto Rican
nationalist group with a history of violence.
   The FBI says that a Wells Fargo security guard was responsible
for the theft of the West Hartford depot on Sept. 12, 1983. Victor
M. Gerena, formerly of Hartford, is accused of tying up co-workers,
loading the cash into a car and fleeing to Cuba, where he is still
believed to be hiding out, the FBI says.
   The torn halves of a $10 bill are the only money that has been
recovered. The government contends that the money was used to
finance the activities of Los Macheteros.
   The trial of nine other defendants was postponed after a ruling
by U.S. District Judge T. Emmet Clarie earlier this year tossing
out some wiretap evidence collected by the FBI. The government is
appealing that ruling.
   Two of the seven remaining defendants pleaded guilty last month
during jury selection. They are awaiting sentencing.
   Their pleas left five men who will stand trial Tuesday:
Harvard-educated Segarra, Carlos Ayes Suarez, Norman Ramirez
Talavera, Roberto Maldonado Rivera and Antonio Comacho Negron.
   Ayes' attorney, James W. Bergenn, said Monday he expects the
trial to last until late January.
   There are expected to be few surprises during the trial, with
the possible exception of previously undisclosed evidence the
government collected through wiretaps on the defendants in the
United States and Puerto Rico.
   The attorney for Segarra told the court during jury selection
that his client knew in advance that the heist would occur and
later came into possession of some of the stolen cash. But the
attorney, Leonard Weinglass, said his client didn't plan the
robbery and didn't participate in it.
   Weinglass said he would argue that is not a crime to keep silent
about a planned robbery.
   The U.S. Justice Department has indicated that it considers this
an important case. The defendants' arrests in August 1985 were
announced by then-U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   During arraignments in U.S. District Court three years ago,
heavily armed federal agents closed streets and mounted rooftops to
provide security.
   But security has been relaxed during the more than 18 months of
pre-trial arguments. Some defendants have settled in Hartford,
sending their children to local schools.
   Clarie ordered the names of the 12 jurors and six alternates
kept secret. The judge said he wanted to protect the jurors,
particularly from mass mailings by supporters of the defendants.
</TEXT>
