<HEAD>Catholic Bishop Criticizes Israeli Actions On West Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic Patriarch of Jerusalem
began a month-long tour of the United States and Canada Monday with
criticism of Israel's treatment of Palestinian Arabs on the West
Bank and Gaza.
   All schools have been closed and thousands of Palestinians are
in detentention camps in ``a situation of suffering,'' Bishop
Michel Sabbah said at a luncheon arranged by the Arab League.
   The prelate said the Israeli crackdown had reached the point
where private teachers risk punishment of up to 10 years in jail if
they teach children at home.
   The patriarch, who represents 80,000 Roman Catholics in Israel,
Jordan and Cyprus, is the first Palestinian appointed to the post
by the Vatican. He will visit San Antonio, Boston, New York,
Chicago, Milwaukee, Los Angeles, San Francisco and Maui, Hawaii, as
well as Toronto and Montreal in Canada.
   President Reagan is expected to receive him in the White House
Oct. 18.
   ``The situation is very hard and difficult,'' Bishop Sabbah said
of conditions in Jerusalem and in the Israeli-held West Bank and
Gaza.
   He said the violence was hurting the Israeli soldiers as well as
the Palestinians who began their 11th month of action against
Israeli control.
   ``The Jewish people are suffering,'' the Catholic official said.
In instances of violences wanted their own state on an equal
footing with Israel.
   ``People who are disenfranchised, who are dispossessed, cannot
remain at the margin,'' Maksoud said.
