<HEAD>Thousands Call For More Gov't Action on Athens Smog</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 people gathered downtown
Monday to protest the government's inability to solve the city's
smog problem.
   Demonstrators chanted, ``No to the clouds!'' and held banners
reading, ``The clouds kill. The government has to take more
measures.''
   The brown smog that forms over the capital on warm days ``is a
daily threat for us and our children,'' said Theodoros Katrivanos,
head of a group of anti-pollution legislators.
   In January, the government introduced a series of anti-pollution
measures for the city of more than 3.5 million people that include
traffic restrictions and the abolition of a traditional afternoon
break in favor of a continuous work schedule.
   ``What we really need is the removal and transfer of industry
from Athens,'' Katrivanos said. There are 120 major plants
operating in the area.
</TEXT>
