<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Florida     10-10 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Florida,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Pulls Back Out-Of-State Staffers From Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the fading Florida campaign of Michael
Dukakis got out their sweaters Monday and began heading to Ohio and
Michigan.
   ``I'm going to miss this place,'' said Paul Pezzella, the
Dukakis state campaign director, as he and Steve Rosenfeld, state
political director, handed over their titles and duties to Miami
attorney Alan G. Greer and Volusia County Commissioner Clay
Henderson.
   Pezzella goes to Cleveland as get-out-the-vote director for
Dukakis in Ohio and Rosenfeld will be based in Columbus handling
communications and scheduling. A $1,000-a-head fund raiser on Miami
Beach will go on as scheduled Tuesday without Dukakis, who is
staying home to prepare for his Thursday night debate.
   Five other Dukakis staffers in Florida have been transferred to
Ohio and three are going to Michigan. Last month, the state
campaign press secretary and a handful of other workers were moved
to Illinois. There are no campaign visits to Florida scheduled for
Dukakis or running mate Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen.
   Pezzella said Dukakis wasn't writing off Florida's 21 electoral
votes, but the national campaign obviously decided that Ohio, with
23 electoral votes, and other Midwestern states were better
opportunities than Florida. Republican presidential candidates have
carried Florida in seven of the last nine elections.
   Pezzella, Dukakis' former chief lobbyist in Massachusetts, and
Rosenfeld, the governor's former chief legal counsel, directed
Dukakis' surprising lop-sided victory in the March 8 Democratic
presidential primary in Florida, then returned to the state in
August.
   Greer, who's been a leader of the Florida Dukakis campaign for
more than a year, said every transferred staffer is being replaced
by experienced Floridians and the campaign maintains 30 full-time
staffers and some 15 offices in the state.
   ``Obviously, this is not a Florida election, it is a national
election,'' Greer said. ``We have to have a national surge.
Assuming we get that national surge, we have the organization here
to move.''
   Greer said Dukakis is ``substantially behind in Florida,'' but
not nearly as badly as an Atlanta Constitution survey that gave
Bush a 26-point bulge in the state.
   Cori Zywotow, who has taken over as state campaign press
secretary, said some Florida workers are offended at the idea that
the departure of Bostonians means the campaign is giving up.
   ``We have a lot of talented people,'' she said.
   She came to the campaign after being spokeswoman for the City of
Miami Police Department, rocked in the past three years by
indictments of several police officers on drug charges.
   ``Talking about having experience with crises,'' she said,
adding quickly: ``That's not the right word. I mean experience with
excitement.''
</TEXT>
