<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 2013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     10-10 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christians Authorize Patriarch To Negotiate on Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian members of Parliament
authorized the head of the dominant Maronite Catholic community on
Monday to negotiate with rival Moslems to elect a new Lebanese
president in efforts to end a political crisis.
   ``We have given ... (Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir) authorization to
negotiate in order to reach agreement as soon as possible on the
president who will be elected by Parliament,'' Deputy Speaker
Albert Mokhaiber said.
   ``We have pledged to abide by any agreement the patriarch
reaches in order to resolve the current crisis.''
   Mokhaiber made the statement after the 29 parliamentarians met
for 2{ hours with Sfeir in suburban Bkirki.
   Mokhaiber indicated that a new president might be elected before
Oct. 18, when the term of Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini, a
Shiite Moslem, expires.
   Lebanon has been without a head of state since Sept. 23, when
former President Amin Gemayel's six-year term ended without
Parliament having chosen a successor. That spawned rival Christian
and Moslem governments, with each claiming legitimacy.
   Parliament failed to convene before Gemayel's departure to elect
a successor when Christians boycotted three electoral sessions to
block the election of Syrian-backed candidates.
   The crisis is cementing Lebanon's de facto partition into
sectarian cantons in the nation's 13-year-old civil war.
   The Christians' new move suggested that Sfeir may sound out
Moslem leaders, and possibly Syria and the United States, on a
compromise candidate.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, backs Lebanon's Moslems
and sought to promote a pro-Syrian Christian into the presidency in
a bid to end the civil war.
   Minutes before Gemayel stepped down, he handed power to army
commander Gen. Michel Aoun, a Maronite, naming him caretaker prime
minister of a six-man military Cabinet.
   All three Moslem officers named to the Aoun Cabinet refused to
serve, and Moslem leaders declared allegiance to the incumbent
government of acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Syrian-backed
Sunni Moslem.
   Under an unwritten covenant dating from Lebanon's independence
from France in 1943, Maronites have held the posts of president,
army commander and central bank governor; the premier traditionally
was a Sunni, and the Parliament speaker a Shiite.
   Christians were deemed to be the majority in 1943. Moslems now
comprise an estimated 55 percent of Lebanon's 4 million people,
however, and demand an equal share of power.
   Hoss warned Monday that formally partitioning Lebanon would lead
to endless fighting between Christians and Moslems.
   ``I challenge the advocates of federalization or partition to
draw up the borders of their cantons. This cannot be done,'' Hoss
told The Associated Press.
   He was responding to a suggestion by Samir Geagea, leader of the
main Christian militia, that federalization would end the deadlock
over the presidential crisis and the civil war.
   ``Political decentralization or federalization will not ...
bring an end to the state of war, but will kindle an endless war on
the borders of the cantons. It will also lead to endless wars in
the streets, alleys, hills, villages and towns,'' Hoss declared.
   Right-wing Christians favor a federal system. They believe it
will safeguard their Western way of life from what they perceive as
the threat of Iran's brand of Islamic fundamentalism. Such
fundamentalism is growing among the Shiites here, Lebanon's largest
single sect.
   Shiite fundamentalist leaders held a mass rally in a south
Beirut mosque Monday under Sheikh Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah,
spiritual guide of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   They said later in a statement that they unanimously rejected
any form of partition as a blow against Islam, and also rejected a
French proposal that U.N. forces be sent to Beirut to oversee the
election of a new president.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
