<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Dumped Fuel,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Sprays Fuel in Emergency Return</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines DC-10 returning to Kennedy
Airport with engine trouble Monday was forced to dump its fuel,
which sprayed a neighborhood.
   ``We had reports that it was like a mist coming down,'' said
police spokesman Joseph McConville in Queens.
   The pilot noticed severe vibrations in one of the jet's three
engines shortly after takeoff at 12:12 p.m., said airline
spokeswoman Mary O'Neill.
   The pilot turned off the engine and ``dumped fuel in
anticipation of an immediate emergency landing,'' she said. The
plane landed safely at 12:30.
   Some of the 242 passengers on Flight 3 to Los Angeles were
placed on other flights and some were waiting for another plane to
be readied.
   Dumping fuel is a routine procedure to lighten the aircraft and
make it safer in case of emergency landing. It is released over
water when possible.
</TEXT>
