<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Great Lakes and Southwest Get Scattered Showers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms moved through northern Wisconsin, Michigan and the
lower Great Lakes Monday, but most of the nation enjoyed pleasant
fall weather.
   Scattered showers also dampened parts of southeast New Mexico
and southwest Texas.
   A few snowflakes swirled around Milwaukee at midday, but the
snow soon turned into rain as the temperature went into the low
60s. It was not the earliest snowfall on record for the city; that
record was set on Sept. 23, 1942.
   There were no record-breaking temperatures Monday, but four
record lows for the date were tied. The 41 degrees in Augusta, Ga.,
tied a 1987 mark. Columbia, S.C.'s 38 tied a record set in 1895 and
equaled last year. Midland, Texas, equaled its 1979 record of 43.
Raleigh, N.C.'s 38 matched a 1977 mark.
   The morning low for the nation was 11 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 43 degrees
at Marquette, Mich., to 100 at Palm Springs, Calif.
   Tuesday's forecast called for rain extending over New England,
New York state, eastern Ohio and much of Pennsylvania. Skies should
be cloudy over the Great Lakes and the Pacific Northwest. Strong
and gusty winds were expected over West Virginia.
   High temperatures should be in the 40s and 50s from the Upper
Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley and much
of New England. Highs should be in the 80s for Florida and southern
Texas, rising into the low 90s for the desert Southwest. The rest
of the nation should have highs in the 60s and 70s.
</TEXT>
