<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1814EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0658 10-10 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0658,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Accuses Dukakis of `Sympathy for Criminals,' Says He'd Favor
Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT two grafs after 11th pvs, Bush's criticism..., to give
Bentsen comment; picks up 12th pvs, Bush walked..., and CORRECTS
billiards to pool.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, accusing rival
Michael Dukakis of having ``so much sympathy for criminals,''
proposed on Monday to increase criminal penalties and to give
victims an expanded role in criminal proceedings.
   ``I'm going to bring an attitude to the White House that has
more sympathy for the victims of crime than for the criminals,''
the vice president said in a Columbus Day addresss to an
Italian-American group.
   Bush said victims of crime ``should have the statutory right to
be informed of, be present and be heard at every critical stage of
the criminal justice process.''
   He told his audience at a Knights of Columbus hall that because
of the holiday ``you will be spared my usual political speech.''
Then he proceeded to hammer away at his familiar campaign theme
that Dukakis is soft on crime.
   ``I've spoken at length about the differences I have with my
opponent on this fundamental issue, and that's not my purpose
today. Suffice it to say that I think there is something very wrong
when there is so much sympathy for criminals and very little left
over for victims,'' the GOP nominee said.
   Bush proposed making it easier for victims to collect civil
judgments for restitution and allowing them to get more money
automatically if a convict's financial circumstances improve.
   He also called for expanding a federal fund created to
compensate victims of crimes.
   ``I believe we should consider raising the fees charged
defendents upon conviction so that more money can be channeled to
victims,'' he said.
   ``On this Columbus Day, we are rediscovering America. It is a
kind and gentle nation with opportunities limited only by our
dreams,'' Bush said. ``And we refuse to let criminals snuff out
those dreams.''
   Earlier, meeting with reporters on his Air Force Two campaign
plane, Bush said he favors review of the federal prison furlough
program, although he has no specific revisions in mind. ``I just
... want to be sure it never slips into the Massachusetts model,''
he said.
   Bush's criticism of the Massachusetts program, which until
modified allowed convicted murderers to be released on weekend
furloughs, has prompted Dukakis, the governor of that state, to
criticize the federal furlough system.
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen was quick to
respond to
   Bush's decision to review the federal system. ``After 2,818 days
of sitting on the sidelines, George Bush has finally admitted that
there is something wrong with a federal furlough program that gives
45-day vacations to drug traffickers,'' Bentsen said in a statement
issued in Washington.
   The Bentsen said more than 7,000 drug offenders received
furloughs last year and 138 prisoners on federal furlough escaped
in 1986, including a man who hijacked a helicopter and returned to
prison to free his bank-robber girlfriend.
   Bush walked down the main thoroughfare of an Italian-American
neighborhood. He stopped at a bakery and at an athletic club, where
he briefly joined a game of pool. With a single shot, Bush drove a
purple ``4'' ball diagonally across the length of the table and
into a corner pocket, to the cheers of club patrons.
   The vice president returned to Washington at midday to prepare
for his second debate with Dukakis in Los Angeles on Thursday and
to play tennis with professional ace Pam Shriver and members of the
Bush family.
   The vice president has frequently visited New Jersey, which his
campaign officials regarded as a crucial election battleground with
its 16 electoral votes.
   ``We're going after Reagan Democrats. You're not going to see
many Republicans here,'' Richard Bond, the campaign's political
director, told reporters during the tour of the Chambersburg
section of Trenton.
   Reagan Democrats are traditionally Democratic voters who voted
for President Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
   Bush aides were heartened by a poll in Sunday's editions of The
Record of Hackensack showing him leading Dukakis by eight
percentage points in New Jersey.
   Asked by reporters if he thought the debate performance of
running mate Dan Quayle had hurt the GOP ticket in the polls, Bush
replied: ``The only poll I heard of, I like very much.''
   He was referring to a survey by the Atlanta Constitution and
Journal which showed Bush with a solid lead over Dukakis in 15
Southern states.
   But, Bush said, ``How can I say I believe in polls? I'm the guy
that's been getting kicked in them not so many days ago.''
   Bush leaves Tuesday for an eight-day campaign swing that will
include the Thursday debate and at least four days of campaigning
in California.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
