<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DalaiLama     10-10 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dalai Lama,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dalai Lama Says He Will Shun Politics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dalai Lama said he will shun
politics if Tibet gains independence from China and any talks he
has with the Chinese will center on Tibet's future, not on his own
return home.
   The exiled spiritual leader said he would stay out of any future
government because his status as god-king of Tibetan Buddhists
would inhibit the development of democracy.
   ``My participation would be a hindrance of a healthy democratic
athomsphere,'' he told a news conference at the Swedish
International Peace Research Insitute on the last stop of a Nordic
tour.
   ``Let the young, intelligent Tibetans carry the responsibility
for leading the government. I want to remain a simple Buddhist
monk.''
   He now leads a government-in-exile based in India.
   In a proposal to China this year, the Dalai Lama substituted
limited autonomy for his previous demand of immediate Tibetan
independence, but expressed the hope of independence in his
lifetime.
   The Dalai Lama left Tibet in 1959.
   Asked Monday when he thought he might be able to return, he
said: ``The issue is not my return but the fate of 6 million
people. When the situation inside Tibet becomes satisfactory, then
the refugees will return, including myself.''
   He urged China to ease restrictions on tourists and journalists
``and let them judge'' whether the country is as calm as the
Chinese claim.
   Government officials in Finland, Norway, Denmark and Sweden did
not meet him officially during this tour because Chinese embassies
let it be known Beijing would not approve.
   The Dalai Lama called his visit ``non-political,'' and said he
had ``no special thing to say'' to Scandinavian governments.
   During five days in Sweden, he plans to address the Foreign
Policy Institute and attend public peace functions.
</TEXT>
