<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope-France 1stLd-Writethru a0611 10-10 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-France, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0611,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope, in French Rust Belt, Urges Economic Change</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 ... UPDATE with European Parliament argument,
letter to inmates. Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``Certain human ... with
minor editing to CONFORM and TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NANCY, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Monday urged the
creation of a new economic system providing greater employment as
he toured the rust-belt area of northeastern France.
   John Paul has made the dignity of work and the need for jobs a
persistent theme of his 10-year papacy and one which figured
prominently in his speeches in Metz and Nancy on the third day of
his four-day visit to the Alsace-Lorraine region.
   The pope also announced he was sending a letter of encouragement
to inmates in French jails.
   In Strasbourg, a shouting match broke out during the opening
session of the European Parliament over the speech the pope was
scheduled to deliver Tuesday. Niall Andrews, an Irish Catholic
conservative, accused the Rev. Ian Paisley of planning to disrupt
the speech.
   He called Paisley, another parliamentarian and leader of the
hard-line Irish Protestant Democratic Unionist Party, ``an
institutional terrorist.'' Paisley shouted back that he opposed
both the pope and the Roman Catholic Church and that he planned to
express his opposition during the pontiff's address.
   In Nancy, John Paul told more than 40,000 faithful jammed into a
square that economic and social problems should not blind them to
the presence of God in the world.
   ``Certain human hopes seem to be sinking,'' said the 68-year-old
pontiff, wearing a bright red cape and speaking under a white,
cone-shaped canopy.
   He said mines and heavy industries that once flourished are in
decline, and demanded that ``a whole new economic restructuring be
invented and put in place'' to solve the unemployment dilemma.
   ``If faith does not dictate ready-made answers, it does provide
the courage to undertake the search, to seek the appropriate type
of development. ... It suggests that human work be re-evaluated in
accordance with the dignity of the person.''
   Although Alsace-Lorraine reports an unemployment rate only
slightly higher than the national average of 10.5 percent, the
jobless rate in industrial cities of the region is higher. The
decline in heavy industry and mining has particularly hurt
immigrants who came in waves from elsewhere in Europe and North
Africa during the industrial boom years of the 1960s and 1970s and
make up nearly 10 percent of the population of Metz and the
surrounding area.
   The pope complimented the region for welcoming foreigners and
called on residents to reject the secularizing trends that have
resulted in a sharp drop in French attendance at Mass since World
War II.
   Ultra-conservative elements of the Roman Catholic Church in
France have expressed concern about the large number of Moslem
immigrants. Islam, now the second-largest religion in France,
arrived with the influx of immigrants from North Africa.
   The conservative Catholics were prominent among the suporters of
National Front leader Jean-Marie Le Pen, who won 14 percent of the
vote in the first round of presidential balloting last spring and
campaigned against immigration.
</TEXT>
