<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO     10-10 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Officers Attack Military Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fistfight broke out Monday at the PLO
office here when 51 PLO military officers, angry at being retired,
attacked the office director and hurt three bodyguards, a
Palestinian official said.
   The spokesman for the Palestine Liberation Army, the regular
military wing of the Palestine Liberation Organization, said office
director Samir Khatib suffered facial bruises, but was in good
condition.
   Khatib's three bodyguards were hospitalized with ``minor
injuries,'' the spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said the officers called for a meeting with Khatib to discuss
their retirement plan and ``took the opportunity to attack him at
his office.''
   ``Probably they felt that obligations to them were not being
honored, although we paid them their salaries and compensation,''
the spokesman said.
   The Palestine Liberation Army operates under the supervision of
host countries. An estimated 1,500 Liberation Army soldiers are
based in Jordan.
   The spokesman said the retired officers broke office furniture,
destroyed files and tried to flee when Jordanian officers arrived
to arrest them. He said police are investigating.
   The spokesman said 40 of the officers had been retired because
they reached retirement age and 11 had been dismissed for ``bad
discipline'' but had been called back for reserve duty.
   Also Monday, PLO officials said the Palestine National Council _
the PLO's equivalent of a parliament-in-exile _ will move to form a
provisional government this month despite warnings that elections
in Israel and the United States will immediately block their
proposals.
   ``The success of great incidents cannot be linked to one
person,'' Hani el-Hassan, a senior aide to PLO chairman Yasser
Arafat, said Monday in Cairo, Egypt.
   ``The announcement of a state is an event based on logical
circumstances,' he said. ``The Palestinian people are their own
masters on their land and no American president or Israeli prime
minister can ignore that.
   ``An independence document and the announcement of a Palestinian
state will be presented to the Palestinian National Council in its
next meeting at the end of October,'' el-Hassan said.
   In Israel, a government source, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Monday both Labor and Likud party blocs will reject
any pre-election proposal.
   Palestinian sources have said that Egypt and the Soviet Union
have been pressing Arafat to delay the meeting and the announcement
of the organization's future plans until after Israel's Nov. 1
election and the U.S. presidential vote Nov. 8.
   The PLO seeks to pressure the United States and Israel to
recognize the Palestinians' right to self-determination and break
the impasse in peace negotiations.
   The steps, to be sanctioned by an emergency meeting of the
Palestine National Council, are expected to include a declaration
of independence for the occupied territories and formation of a
Palestinian provisional government.
   Another Arafat aide, Salah Khalaf, was quoted by the Kuwaiti
newspaper Al-Qabas as saying leaders of various Palestinian
guerrilla groups have ``unanimously adopted a decision to set up an
independent Palestinian state and declare sovereignty on
Palestinian land.''
   Khalaf emphasized that the Palestine National Council meeting
will be held before the Israeli elections and said ``This is our
final decision,'' the newspaper reported.
   The mounting casualties in the 10 months of riots against
Israel's military occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip
persuaded some leaders that the PLO must act quickly to gain
politically from the confrontations.
   They also want to strengthen PLO links with the 1.5 million
Palestinians there following King Hussein's July decision to sever
Jordan's administrative links with the occupied lands.
</TEXT>
