<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Egypt-Opera 1stLd-Writethru a0639 10-10 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Opera, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese-built Opera House Inaugurated</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with opening</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trumpets blared and fireworks lit the sky
Monday night as President Hosni Mubarak inaugurated Cairo's new
Opera House, 17 years after fire destroyed the one built a century
ago for the opening of the Suez Canal.
   Japan paid for the $50 million ivory-colored, neo-Islamic
cultural complex, which is officially called the Cairo Education
and Culture Center and presented the first Kabuki theater
performance on the Nile. Its unofficial name is the Opera House,
for the building destroyed by fire in 1971.
   Floodlights bathed the ivory domes as officials and members of
the art world walked into the 1,300-seat main theater Monday night.
   The center represents Japan's largest aid outlay for a project
with a primarily cultural function. Mubarak specifically requested
money for such a project during a visit to Japan in 1983.
   Because of Emperor Hirohito's grave illness, the Japanese royal
family was not represented at the inaugural. Official Japanese
parties and receptions were canceled.
   Kajima Corp. began construction 40 months ago. The complex was
completed ahead of schedule and turned over to Egypt last March.
   On Monday night, vans full of security police stood by the white
gates and traffic was diverted from the area. Hundreds of people
gathered near the gates, and between mounted soldiers on a nearby
bridge, to catch watch the pomp and ceremony.
   Mubarak arrived in a convoy of at least 10 Mercedes automobiles,
preceded by Cabinet ministers. He unveiled a plaque and cut a
ribbon.
   In the rose-colored hall Egypt's national anthem played before
the Japanese music-dance drama performed by male actors dressed in
exquisite costumes.
   Khedive Ismail built the original Opera House, which was
inaugurated in 1869 as part of an extravagent Suez Canal
dedication. Ismail commissioned the opera ``Aida'' from the
Giuseppe Verdi for the opening, but the Italian composer did not
finish it in time and the work premiered in the Opera House two
years later.
   Two bronze sculptures recovered from the ashes in 1971 stand at
either end of the lawn in the new complex on Gezira Island in the
Nile, one of Cairo's wealthiest quarters.
   In addition to the main space, the Education and Culture Center
also has two smaller theaters, a museum, an art gallery, a
conference hall and training facilities.
   Japanese artists worked until less than two months ago with
complex director Magda Saleh to prepare the opening night's Kabuki
performance and for later musical and ballet shows.
   Then a new director, Ratiba Hefny, was named without explanation.
   ``We weren't even told officially about the change until two
weeks after it was made,'' said Hiroshi Shiojiri, first secretary
for cultural affairs at the Japanese Embassy.
   Customs officials also had delayed the arrival of 40 crates of
equipment and luggage for Monday night's show. Officials said they
held up baggage because of a rumor that a drug smuggler was on the
Egypt Air flight bringing the troupe of 50 from Tokyo.
   The baggage was delivered later.
   ``The Japanese give grants only for educational, not cultural,
purposes,'' said Mohammed Salmawi of the Culture Ministry. ``So we
agreed to call it an educational and cultural center, but it's
really mainly cultural.''
   Kajima employed about 500 Egyptians on the project with 30
Japanese engineers and administrators.
   The opening prompted last-minute cleanup jobs on Gezira Island.
   Four huge bronze lions guarding the bridge were washed down,
nearby buildings painted and fences mended. Workers planted
greenery and cleared trash from nearby plazas.
   Some Egyptians grumble about so much money being spent on a
complex to bring basically alien culture to the nation. They say
Egypt, with a population of 54 million and a per capita annual
income of $600, would be served better by a hospital, low-cost
housing or schools.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
