<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EGermany-Protest     10-10 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EGermany-Protest,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Berlin Security Breaks Up Demonstration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Berlin security officials broke up a protest
march by about 200 activists Monday, detained dozens and roughed up
West German journalists, witnesses said.
   The demonstrators were protesting government censorship of
Lutheran Church newspapers.
   Communist East Germany's official news agency ADN said about 80
people were ``momentarily detained'' for ``going against state
measures for public order'' but were released after a warning.
   It made no mention of any rough treatment.
   West Germany issued a statement saying the incident was ``in
crass contradiction'' to human rights accords and ``violates the
(West German-East German) agreement'' on journalists' coverage of
events in East Germany.
   In its evening news broadcast, the West German television
network ZDF showed East German plainclothes security officials
shoving demonstrators and West German journalists covering the
march.
   It said ZDF correspondent Michael Schmitz was struck in the
stomach by a security official.
   Demonstrators, many singing protest songs, were loaded into
trucks and taken away.
   The protesters carried banners saying ``Press Freedom for the
Church.'' Some demonstrators carried children on their shoulders.
   Police broke up the march after the protesters had gone about
100 yards, witnesses said.
</TEXT>
