<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Indians-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0662 10-10 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indians-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0662,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Acquits One Defendant of Some Charges in Indians' Newspaper
Takeover</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS state to dateline and ADDS 5 grafs with afternoon
session.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Monday acquitted one of two
Indian activists on a hostage-taking charge in the takeover of a
newspaper office, but let stand weapons charges against both
defendants.
   U.S. District Judge Terrence Boyle, in dismissing the charge
against Timothy Jacobs, said his reading of the statute showed that
a demand on the government had to be ``not just incidental, but
material.''
   Boyle said he would let the jury decide if co-defendant Eddie
Hatcher was guilty of the charge.
   ``We have achieved a great victory,'' Jacobs' attorney, Lewis
Pitts, said at a news conference during a court recess. ``We
predicted several months ago that the federal hostage-taking
charges would be dropped and they have been, at least against
Jacobs.
   ``We believe the judge should have, in fact, ordered an
acquittal on those charges against Eddie Hatcher,'' Pitts said.
``It underscores how unfair it is to Eddie not to have his lawyer
with him.''
   Boyle ordered Hatcher to represent himself after Hatcher refused
to accept other counsel. His attorney, William Kunstler, is
involved in a case in New York and has been unable to participate
in Hatcher's trial.
   Attorneys for Jacobs argued Friday that prosecutors had failed
to prove that he and Hatcher had made a demand on the federal
government during their takeover of The Robesonian newspaper in
Lumberton on Feb. 1.
   ``The court is of the opinion that it is premature concerning
the evidence with respect to defendant Hatcher to make a ruling and
that this should proceed to the jury,'' Boyle said.
   But he said prosecutors had presented no evidence that Jacobs
had made a demand on the government or had aided Hatcher in making
a demand.
   The hostage-taking charge was linked with a second charge of
committing a violent crime with an illegal firearm. Boyle also
dismissed that charge against Jacobs.
   Hatcher and Jacobs still face charges of conspiracy, making an
illegal firearm, possessing an unregistered firearm and conveying
false information concerning explosives.
   In a written order, Boyle advised defense attorneys that he
would not accept their ``necessity defense.'' The judge said there
was no direct relationship between the hostages taken at The
Robesonian and the threats perceived by Hatcher and Jacobs.
   The two had argued that their lives were in jeopardy because of
information they said linked law enforcement officers to drug
trafficking in Robeson County. They claimed they had no choice but
to take hostages at the newspaper to publicize their case.
   But Boyle wrote that the action should have been taken against
the people who posed the threat, not innocent people.
   Pitts said that decision would force lawyers to try an alternate
defense.
   ``The judge in his ruling said allowing the `necessity defense'
would create chaos and anarchy, but chaos and anarchy already
existed in Robeson County prior to Feb. 1,'' Pitts said.
   Monday afternoon, Hatcher attempted to call one witness and
questioned another witness, ending his two-week refusal to
participate in the trial. Hatcher agreed to question former
Pembroke Police Chief Kirby Ammons, who had been called by Jacobs'
attorneys.
   ``I'm not an attorney, but yes, sir, I do have some questions,''
Hatcher responded when Boyle asked him if he wished to question
Ammons.
   ``Did you not tell me my life was in danger with this
information I had?'' Hatcher asked Ammons, referring to alleged
information on drug dealing involving law enforcement officers.
   ``I don't remember that,'' Ammons said.
   Hatcher also attempted to call a witness to the stand, but Boyle
said he would hear defense evidence for Jacobs first and then hear
from Hatcher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
