<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Spies     10-10 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Spies,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alleged Hungarian Spies Say They Approached CIA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian-born brothers charged with
spying against NATO said Monday they approached the CIA about
selling classified material but were turned down, according to a
news report of the trial.
   Sandor and Imre Kercsik, naturalized Swedish citizens ages 48
and 34 respectively, were arrested in August after a spy ring
allegedly run by former U.S. Army Sgt. Clyde Lee Conrad was
uncovered.
   Conrad was stationed at a NATO base in West Germany and had
access to classified data on operations of the Western alliance. He
faces espionage charges that carry a maximum penalty of 10 years in
prison.
   The trial of the Kercsik brothers began Monday at Molndal
District Court outside Goteborg in southwestern Sweden.
   The report said the brothers told the court Conrad invented an
imaginary high-ranking intelligence officer named David in Hungary,
then had them write a letter offering classified material and
saying Conrad wanted to defect.
   According to the Swedish news agency TT, the brothers testified
the CIA paid tens of thousands of dollars for sample material but
ended the contacts later because of dissatisfaction with the
information.
   It said the brothers contested prosecutor Sven Olof Hakansson's
suggestion they wanted to approach the West out of fear of being
disclosed as East bloc agents, saying their only aim was getting
money from the Americans.
   The agency's report said Conrad tricked the brothers by
inventing a man named Mike who provided information from the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization and saying he needed money to pay the
fictitious agent.
   According to the charges, the Kercsik brothers were couriers in
Europe for Conrad, who sold NATO secrets to Hungary.
   Hungary enlisted the elder brother in the 1960s and the younger
in 1980, they told the court, and they were pressured by agents who
constantly reminded them of their sister and ailing mother in
Hungary.
   They have denied espionage charges, claiming they did not
collect secret material but only acted as couriers. The defense
says they did not operate in Sweden and their activities were not
directed against this neutral nation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
