<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Polio     10-10 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Polio,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Inoculates Residents Against Polio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel inoculated more than 500,000 residents
against polio Monday on the second day of a nationwide vaccination
campaign that began after nine cases of the paralyzing disease were
diagnosed.
   Israeli television meanwhile reported that two infants from
northern Israel were hospitalized with symptoms of the disease.
Their diagnosis has not yet been confirmed, hospital officials said.
   Polio was thought to be eradicated in the region, and the recent
cases have been blamed on inadequate sewage systems.
   Health Ministry spokesman Shmuel Algrabli said 1.4 million
Israelis have been inoculated since the country was alerted last
month.
   The army's Civil Administration began vaccinating Palestinian
residents of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip Sunday, Algrabli
said.
   ``There have been no problems with the intefadeh in this
regard,'' he said, referring to the 10-month-old Palestinian revolt
against Israeli rule. ``We have had the complete cooperation of the
residents and the physicians.''
   No figure was available on the number of Arab residents
inoculated.
   The campaign, to encompass 3.2 million Israelis under 40 years
of age and more than 1 million Palestinians in the same age group,
is expected to be over in four weeks.
   Tourists planning to visit Israel do not need an extra polio
vaccination but those now in the country may be inoculated free of
charge, the Health Ministry said.
</TEXT>
