<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 2053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru     10-10 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Guerrillas Killed In Attack on Jungle Police Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight leftist guerrillas were killed when
an outmanned police force repelled a rebel attack in Peru's eastern
Amazon jungle, officials in this state capital said Monday.
   About 100 combatants of the Mao-inspired Shining Path guerrilla
group attacked the police post in Villa Rica, 100 miles north of
here, before dawn Sunday, police officials said.
   The 20 police troopers inside the post drove off the rebels, who
were armed with automatic weapons and dynamite, without suffering
casualties, according to the police report.
   The rebels dynamited and torched three government offices during
the attack on Villa Rica, a town of 8,000 inhabitants.
   Police in Huancayo, in the Andean highlands 140 miles east of
Lima, said the attack lasted 45 minutes before the rebels withdrew
into the surrounding jungle, leaving their dead behind.
   They said blood stains along the road used by the escaping
rebels indicated some of them were wounded.
   Officials said police reinforcements left Huancayo Monday to
pursue the guerrilla column.
   Villa Rica is in a lumber and coffee-growing region. Many of the
area's residents are descendants of German immigrants from the last
century.
   Police said it was the first time guerrillas have attacked Villa
Rica.
   The Shining Path launched its insurgency in Peru's southern
highlands in 1980 to overthrow the elected government.
   Since then the fighting has spread to coastal cities and into
Peru's eastern jungles, and more than 12,000 people have died.
</TEXT>
