<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0656 10-10 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0656,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Secretary of State Hails Soviet Move On Economy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with speech delivered, additional remarks.
ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz on
Monday warned America to steer clear of protectionism and
isolation, which he said is an ingredient in ``a recipe for
economic and political disaster, not success.''
   Shultz said the concept of democratic and free market values is
taking hold in Latin America, Asia and Africa, and ``the failure of
the socialist command model has become plain to everybody.''
   ``The tide of Marxism, and with it communism as a model for
development, is a tide that is going out,'' he told the Financial
Executives Institute.
   Shultz said he was surprised but pleased with a call for a freer
economy by the new chief ideologist in the Soviet Union.
   ``I had to keep pinching myself. This is a communist talking,''
he said.
   But, Shultz said, ``the words he says are important words.''
   Shultz referred to a speech by Vadim A. Medvedev, published last
week in Pravda, in which the Kremlin ideologist called for
borrowing ideas from the West in order to restructure the Soviet
economy.
   Medvedev spoke of expanding to heavy industry the experiments
already under way on cooperatives and rentals for farmers and small
entrepreneurs.
   Shultz related the Soviet official's statement to a worldwide
expansion of the open market system, and in an obvious nod to the
Soviet Union's ``glasnost,'' or ``openness'' reform policy, the
secretary used the English word himself some half-dozen times.
   ``The big communist countries, China and the Soviet Union, are
also discovering these truths,'' he said.
   ``We will welcome the actions and ideas of others on the world
stage _ whether developed or developing, capitalist or communist _
if they are pared to promoting openness and world economic
growth,'' he said.
   Shultz, in a swipe at the ``stifling regulatory overlay on much
of Europe,'' added, ``It would be a tragic irony for a group of
nations to create a common market among themselves and then erect
new trade barriers against countries outside its bounds.''
   Reminding the financial officers that the world economy cannot
get along without the United States and the economic clout it
represents, Shultz added: ``In order to ensure continued national
and global economic expansion, the U.S. budget and trade deficits
must shrink _ the sooner the better.''
   He counseled not to forget that ``the wealth and size of our
market are vital to many countries and to the world economy.
American purchases of manufactured goods from developing countries
nearly doubled between 1982 and 1986, from $41 billion to $81
billion.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
