<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Wildfires     10-10 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arson, Gunfire, and Campfire Blamed For Three Wildfires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HEMET, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three wildfires in southern California
burned nearly 3,000 acres and left two firefighters injured Monday.
   The fires were blamed on arson, a poorly tended campfire and
sparks from target practice ricochets. Dry desert winds and
temperatures topping 100 degrees aggravated firefighting efforts.
   California Department of Forestry Capt. Dave Howard was caught
in a firestorm as he battled a 700-acre arson blaze about 85 miles
southeast of Los Angeles and suffered severe burns to about half
his body, said CDF spokesman Tim Span.
   Howard, one of about 200 firefighters working the blaze, was
airlifted to the burn center at Sherman Oaks Community Hospital in
Los Angeles, where he was listed in critical but stable condition,
Span said.
   The other injury was to a female jail inmate who had been put to
work on a fire line. The woman suffered burns over a small portion
of her body. She was treated at the jail.
   An 1,800-acre blaze in Riverside County blackened 1,800 acres
after a campfire spread to nearby brush on Sunday, Span said. And
in San Bernardino County, a 200-acre brush fire sparked Sunday by
gunfire ricochets off scrap metal briefly threatened homes before
it was encircled early Monday.
</TEXT>
