<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Gulf     10-10 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Gulf,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Will Return To Geneva For Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said Monday he will return to Geneva this month to mediate peace
talks between Iran and Iraq, but expressed misgivings about the
pace of the negotiations.
   ``I am satisfied in the sense that the meetings are useful, but
not in the sense that we are moving too slowly. The parties are
presenting their positions, and that takes time,'' the U.N. chief
said.
   He spoke to reporters after briefing the Security Council on his
meetings in New York over the last 10 days with foreign ministers
Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran and Tariq Aziz of Iraq.
   Perez de Cuellar said the date for resuming the talks is still
not settled, but will be announced soon. He indicated it would be
the last week of October.
   The secretary-general's decision to return to Geneva was seen as
a possible indication that he hopes for progress soon after the
talks resume.
   U.N. officials and sources close to the Iraqi and Iranian
delegations have said both sides agreed to a compromise suggested
by Perez de Cuellar to break a stalemate in the talks.
   The compromise involved the issues of Iran's searching ships in
the Persian Gulf and Iraq's insistence that the Shatt-al-Arab
waterway between the two countries be reopened.
   The U.N. and Iraqi sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said both Iran and Iraq will withdraw their troops to the
internationally recognized border and will discuss repatriating
prisoners of war.
   Perez de Cuellar also told council members Monday about his
recent visit to South Africa and Angola to discuss the Nov. 1
implementation date for an independence plan for South-West Africa,
or Namibia, ruled by South Africa in violation of U.N. resolutions.
   Iran and Iraq began fighting in September 1980, accepted a
U.N.-sponsored truce Aug. 20, and started peace negotiations five
days later in Geneva. The talks had moved to New York last month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
