<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SchoolBus 2ndLd-Writethru a0661 10-10 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Bus, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0661,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>16 Hurt as Truck Hits School Bus</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf, `Bus driver...' to CORRECT figure to 12 sted
16</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EVERETT, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tractor-trailer truck slammed into the
back of a school bus Monday, injuring 16 students and both drivers
as the vehicles tumbled down an embankment, authorities said.
   Four students were seriously injured.
   The tractor-trailer, which was carrying brewer's grain, flipped
over once to land upright and the bus slid onto its side after
falling the 15 to 20 feet, witnesses said.
   The bus carried 20 students ages 5 through 17 on their way to
the Everett Area Elementary School and Everett Area High School.
   Bus driver Randy Mearkle, 33, of Everett, and 12 students were
treated for minor injuries and released at Memorial Hospital of
Bedford, said nursing supervisor Beth Arnold. Melissa Cottle, 10,
was hospitalized for a back injury and Jennifer Veach, 16, was
admitted for observation, she said.
   Truck driver Anthony W. Ritchie, 23, of Criders, Va., was also
admitted for observation.
   Candice Crawford, 15, and Jody Veach, 14, were transferred to
Conemaugh Valley Memorial Hospital in Johnstown, where they were
admitted in critical condition with head injuries, according to
hospital officials.
   Ritchie's truck hit the school bus shortly after 7:30 a.m. while
both were traveling northbound on the Pennsylvania 26 Bypass, said
Dick Weaver, state police communications operator in Bedford.
   The bus was hit from behind as it accelerated from a bus stop,
said Edward A. Vollbrecht, school district superintendent.
   ``He never stopped. ... I looked in the mirror and there he
was,'' said Mearkle, a bus driver for seven years. ``It was chaos.
The children were screaming.''
   The careening truck barely missed two students waiting for the
bus on the side of the road, witnesses said.
   Floyd Roberts of the Everett Volunteer Fire Department said some
students were taken to the hospital in a fire truck.
   ``Most of them were just shook up,'' Ms. Arnold said of the
students. ``They had a few cuts, bumps and bruises, but most of
them were fine. They were pretty good.''
   Everett, about 10 miles east of Bedford, has about 1,800
residents.
</TEXT>
