<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Vlasov     10-10 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Vlasov,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Russian Republic Premier Relieved Of Duties As Interior Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The recently elected premier of the Russian
republic was relieved Monday of his duties as interior minister,
the Soviet Union's top uniformed police official, Tass reported.
   Removal of Alexander Vlasov, also promoted to non-voting
membership on the ruling Politburo, as interior minister had been
expected after his election last week to the Russian premiership.
   Tass, the official news agency, said the decision was made by
the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the country's highest
executive body. It did not say who would be named interior minister.
   Vlasov, 56, received the premiership on the recommendation of
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   He replaced Vitalty Vorotnikov as premier of the largest of the
15 republics that make up the Soviet Union. Vorotnikov was moved to
the largely ceremonial job of president of the Russian republic.
   Vlasov was named interior minister in early 1986 after serving
as Communist Party leader in Rostov, near Gorbachev's southern home
city of Stavropol.
   He was named to his new positions as part of a series of recent
changes in which Gorbachev retired several long-time Politburo
members, streamlined the work of the policy-making Central
Committee and moved key supporters into important jobs.
</TEXT>
