<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PresidentialPolls     10-10 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Polls,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls Show Bush, Dukakis In Dead Heat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of surveys released Monday showed the
Republican ticket of George Bush and Dan Quayle ticket in a virtual
dead heat with Democrats Michael Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen, and
Quayle was seen as having a negative impact in both surveys.
   One of the surveys, by The Los Angeles Times, also showed that
Dukakis had a comparable negative rating with Quayle.
   The Times survey showed the Republican ticket leading the
Democratic ticket 44-41. But when Bush and Dukakis were pitted
against against each other without their respective running mates,
Bush led 48-39. A 5 point margin of error closed the difference in
both cases.
   In an ABC News-Washington Post poll, Bush had 50 percent to 47
percent for Dukakis. That survey also had a 5 point margin of error.
   The Times poll, conducted over the weekend by telephone, also
found that Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen far outperformed Quayle in last
week's vice presidential debate. But it also found that Dukakis had
a 45 percent unfavorable rating, compared with 40 percent
unfavorable rating for Quayle.
   The ABC-Post poll, in an effort to assess the Quayle ``drag''
among the electorate, found that 2 percent of all voters supported
Dukakis only because of their negative feelings about Quayle, and 6
percent said Quayle was the ``major'' reason for supporting Dukakis.
   The ABC-Post survey of 600 likely voters was conducted
nationwide by telephone from Wednesday through Sunday. The Times
survey of 893 registered voters was conducted over the weekend.
That group was split into two groups to ask the questions about the
ticket and the individual presidential contenders.
</TEXT>
