<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Rebels     10-10 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Rebels,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim Killing 62 Soldiers, Capture Town</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels in southern Sudan claimed Monday
that they killed 62 soldiers in a three-day battle that ended in
the capture of a small town near the Uganda border.
   The Sudan People's Liberation Army's clandestine radio said 300
government soldiers fled into Uganda on Friday when the guerrillas
captured Ikotos, a town in eastern Equatorial Province 46 miles
from the border.
   ``SPLA fighters have taken positions on the Sudanese side, but
because of the respect we have for international borders we cannot
cross into Uganda,'' the radio, monitored in Nairobi, said.
   ``We urge the fugitives to surrender. If they surrender without
their arms, no harm will be done to them.''
   The radio made no mention of rebel casualties and it was
immediately impossible to independently verify its report.
   The guerrilla group took up arms in 1983 against the
Moslem-dominated government in Khartoum, demanding more autonomy
for the mainly Christian and animist south. The rebel movement
claims control of 90 percent of the southern countryside and small
towns.
   Thousands of civilians fleeing the war and hunger headed to
larger towns or to northern Sudan, but relief officials say many
have starved to death on the way.
</TEXT>
