<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 2301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Koran     10-10 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Koran,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Huge Page Of Manuscript Of The Koran Sold In Sotheby's Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A page the size of a door from a 550-year-old
manuscript copy of the Koran, the sacred book of Moslems, sold for
$272,745 Monday at Sotheby's auctioneers.
   The page, measuring 6 feet by 3.7 feet came from a work
commissioned by Prince Baysanghur of the Persian Timurid dynasty to
embellish the tomb in Samarkand of his grandfather Timur, the
mighty Mongol conqueror known in the West as Tamerlane or
Tamburlaine.
   Before the sale, appraisers estimated the page would fetch up to
60,000 pounds ($102,600) in Monday's auction in London of Oriental
manuscripts and miniatures, said a Sotheby's spokeswoman, who spoke
on condition she not be indentified.
   The Middle Eastern buyer of the manuscript page wanted to remain
anonymous, she said.
   Sotheby's said only two other pages of this size from the
manuscript are known, both owned by private collectors.
   The page sold Monday contained a seven-line fragment in Arabic
of two of the Koran's 6,236 verses. It read: ``As for those, their
portion of the book shall reach them until our messengers come to
them causing them to die ...''
   Scholars doubt whether a complete version of the manuscript was
ever completed because the project was so huge, the spokeswoman
said. A complete volume of the manuscript would have been 3,500
pages long.
   Nabil Saidi, Sotheby's expert on Oriental manuscripts, said:
``Nobody knows why it is so big but it may have been just for the
grandeur, the lavishness of it. The prince wanted to impress.''
   Sotheby's said the paper pages had not been bound into a book
but were stacked like laundry.
   The completed pages were looted two centuries ago when war lord
Nadir Shah and his troops captured Timur's former capital
Samarkand, now part of the republic of Uzbekistan in the Soviet
Union. Many pages were subsequently lost or badly damaged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
