<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 2306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     10-10 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Round-Table Talks Could Last A Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The round-table talks between communist
authorities and the opposition could last three to four weeks and
should focus on basic issues of political and economic reform, a
Politburo member said Monday.
   In an interview with the state-run news agency PAP, Jozef Czyrek
said the talks would be held in the ``latter half of this month,''
but gave no date. Last week, opposition mediator Andrzej
Stelmachowski said they were tentatively set for Oct. 17.
   Czyrek said the talks should aim for an agreement on a
pro-reform coalition that would help work out and implement reforms
agreed upon at the round-table.
   Czyrek did not mention the banned labor movement Solidarity by
name, but said agreement on a model for trade union activity in
Poland would be an important aspect of the talks.
   ``Another key task would consist in arriving at joint
conclusions on accelerating economic reform and, consequently,
working out a Polish economic model as well as reaching agreement
on the matter of the trade union model in Poland,'' PAP quoted him
as saying.
   Solidarity leaders met over the weekend and agreed that
legalizing the movement was essential if the talks were to succeed,
a Solidarity communique said.
   The statement was issued by Solidarity national spokesman Janusz
Onyszkiewicz and was released Monday.
   It also said more than 100 people were fired from their jobs
after the August strikes and that ``stopping all the repressions is
a necessary condition to create the atmosphere of good will during
the coming talks.''
   Authorities agreed to talks with the opposition during a 19-day
wave of strikes in August, Poland's worst labor strife in seven
years.
   Onyszkiewicz also said Monday that a statement he made at a U.S.
congressional hearing last month concerning human rights in Poland
should be published in the Polish press.
   He was responding to a statement by a Foreign Ministry spokesman
on Sunday that his appearance before Congress had done ``some
harm'' to Poland abroad.
   Last week the government said a prosecutor would look at the
statement to see if Polish law was violated.
   Onyszkiewicz said the Helsinki commission of Congress invited
him to talk about human rights in Poland and he told the group when
he appeared Sept. 23 that Polish authorities did not respect rights
guaranteed by international conventions.
   He said in a prepared statement Monday that he demanded
publication of the full text of his testimony before Congress ``in
the mass media, as well as questions and answers. Polish society
will be able then to judge the groundlessness of accusations and
only then it will appear who serves whom.''
</TEXT>
