<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-US,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Says Soviet Threat Still Alive in Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. deputy defense secretary said Monday that
Soviet war capabilities remain a threat to European security and
that defense officials of allied countries are aware of it.
   The U.S. official, William H. Taft, met with Italy's defense
undersecretary, Giuseppe Pasanu, to discuss allied relations and
sharing the cost of the West's defense among NATO countries. Taft
is completing a tour of European NATO allies.
   Taft told reporters later that although all the officials he's
met on this trip agree that NATO efforts should be continued,
public opinion in some of these countries does not agree.
   ``They see the (U.S.-Soviet missile) reductions, which I believe
are the result of keeping a strong defense, and want to use them as
an excuse to decrease defense spending,'' he said.
   When asked about U.S. financial support of NATO, Taft replied,
``We believe that the U.S. should continue to support (NATO)
expenses, and even increase its financial support. The continuation
of the Soviet military threat calls for it and we can afford it.''
   Taft praised Italy as having a good record in the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
   ``Our friends in Italy have developed a defense program that
will increase the capabilities of the European armed forces and
make a more effective contribution to NATO,'' he said.
</TEXT>
