<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers put down tools, students
went on a hunger strike and Serbs rallied to condemn a government
crackdown on growing protests, but the nation's president
threatened tougher security measures.
   In an unusual 30-minute radio and television address Sunday,
President Raif Dizdarevic also promised a shake-up in Communist
Party leadership and called for economic reforms. A national
economic crisis has combined with tensions between Serbs and ethnic
Albanians to fuel three months of protests and calls for an
overhaul in the party hierarchy.
   In the southern republic of Montenegro, hundreds of Titograd
University students began a hunger strike Sunday to protest the use
of force by police. They also pressed their demands for an overhaul
of regional and national Communist leadership.
   In an unusually outspoken demand for democracy, the official
Communist youth union also called for ``direct and secret''
elections to get leaders the people would support.
