<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0822EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-LaboriteQuandary Adv14   10-10 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Laborite Quandary, Adv 14,0823</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs Oct. 14 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Britain's Laborites Seek to Win Power without Looking Thatcherite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The quandary facing Britain's Labor
Party emerged starkly at its recent annual convention here: how to
broaden its appeal without seeming to clutch at Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's coattails.
   Splits were apparent across the spectrum. At one end was Bryan
Gould, the polished, college-educated Labor campaign manager,
pleading for more openness to market forces; at the other was
miners' leader Arthur Scargill ridiculing Labor's leadership as
yuppies and capitalists.
   Speaker after speaker rose to level roughly the same accusation:
that by diluting its left-wing doctrines, the Labor Party was
simply trying to copy Mrs. Thatcher's Conservatives.
   ``I didn't join the party to have a yuppified approach, to run
capitalism better than the Tories,'' grumbled Scargill during the
week-long conference in early October.
   But Labor has lost three elections in a row to Mrs. Thatcher
since 1979 and has lurched further left in opposition. So when
party leader Neil Kinnock spoke of the need for realism, he meant
recognizing the irrevocable change wrought by nearly 10 years of
Mrs. Thatcher's rigorous brand of conservatism.
   ``The kind of economy we are faced with is a market economy .. .
and we have got to run it better than the Tories,'' Kinnock told
delegates in this north England resort. ``There is no concession to
Thatcherism as great as letting it win again.''
   On the economy, Kinnock succeeded in edging the party to the
right with broad endorsement for the first stage of a two-year
reform package.
   But to his dismay, the big blue-collar unions used their
overwhelming voting power to narrowly reaffirm the party's most
proven vote-loser: unilateral nuclear disarmament.
   It is a decision Kinnock signaled he may ignore when the
conference votes next year on the final version of a new platform
to try to win again in a changed nation.
   The fact is that in Britain, stockholders have trebled in number
to 9 million since 1979, roughly equal to the number of labor union
members.
   The Trades Union Congress, the national labor federation, is
down from 12.2 million members in 1979 to 9.1 million this summer.
   Smokestack industries, such as that state-owned British Steel
which now is being readied for privatization, have shed thousands
of workers in Thatcher-ordered shakeups.
   The manufacturing industry now employs 5 million people, 2
million fewer than in 1979. Service industries, often
non-unionized, employ 1.5 million, up 200,000.
   The economy is growing at 4 percent a year, faster than most
other industrialized countries, fueled by credit-card buying that
has sent the trade deficit heading toward $20 billion this year,
four times higher than originally estimated.
   But opinion polls indicate that most Britons still feel better
off and doubt the Labor Party can preserve their prosperity.
   Two-thirds of Britons own their homes, up from 50 percent when
Mrs. Thatcher came to power and enabled tenants, mostly
blue-collar, to buy state-subsidized houses. The Laborites
initially opposed the policy but now espouse it.
   Kinnock wants to ready Labor for the next general election,
probably in 1991, but the conference left question marks over how
far the party will let him go.
   The unions' block votes helped Kinnock crush a left-wing bid to
unseat him and adopt the first-stage policy reforms. These include
jettisoning commitments to renationalize all state-owned industries
sold by Mrs. Thatcher and to repeal all her union-curbing laws.
   But the resentments, conflicts and class overtones burst through
when Ron Todd, leader of the powerful 1.25 million-member Transport
and General Workers' Union, turned against the leadership, calling
it ``all sharp suits and cordless telephones, clipboards and
scientific samples.''
   Todd, a working-class Cockney, further embarrassed Kinnock by
using his union's block vote to kill an attempt to water down the
pledge of unilateral nuclear disarmament.
   It illustrated Labor's main problem. The party is funded by the
unions that founded it in 1900. But the very power the union bosses
exercise _ 90 percent of the conference voting strength _ portrays
Labor as a prisoner of trade union militancy.
   Todd, 61, characterizes an old and shrinking working-class
constituency.
   Kinnock, a Welsh miner's son, is a university graduate and, at
46, a generation away from his working-class origins.
   Gavin Laird, moderate leader of the engineers' union, saw the
Kinnock-Todd battle as hastening the day when Labor governments
finally disengage from the unions.
   ``Come the day when we have the next Labor government, there
will be no tea and cookies at Downing Street any more,'' he said.
``We will have a healthy, arms-length relationship.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Maureen Johnson, a correspondent in London for
The Associated Press, specializes in British politics.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Oct. 14</NOTE>
