<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0757EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Greece-Papandreou Adv18   10-10 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Greece-Papandreou, Adv 18,0829</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs Oct. 18 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>After Heart Surgery, Papandreou's Political Future In Doubt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou came through
open-heart surgery in London, but politicians here at home are
already discussing what they call the post-Papandreou era.
   The 69-year-old Socialist leader had a heart valve replaced and
triple bypass surgery in a seven-hour operation Sept. 30.
   But the health problems, together with his plans to divorce his
American wife and marry a 34-year-old Greek airline stewardess,
suggest to some politicians that Papandreou is likely to put his
private life ahead of politics in future.
   ``The Papandreou government has been a one-man show. With him
unfit it's hard to see how the Socialists are going to carry on,''
said Dimitris Nianias, a member of Parliament from the small
liberal Democratic Renewal Party.
   Leading personalities in Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist
Movement (PASOK) are already cautiously lobbying to stand in for,
or to even succeed, the premier if he steps down.
   Elections are due in eight months, but with a weakened leader,
PASOK may find it hard to repeat the easy victories of 1981 and
1985.
   ``Papandreou will come back from London a hero and the
government will muddle along for the next few months,'' said
political columnist Haris Bousbourelis. ``But after that, will
people really be prepared to vote for a sick man?
   ``PASOK could have an Indian summer, but the feeling around
Athens is that the Socialist era is coming to an end.''
   A U.S. citizen for more than 20 years and an economics professor
at the University of Minnesota and the University of California at
Berkley, Papandreou swept to power in 1981 on an anti-American,
anti-NATO platform, pledging a ``socialist transformation'' of
Greece after a generation of right-wing rule.
   The pledge failed to materialize but the charismatic premier
kept voters' loyalty despite reversing his promises to shut down
U.S. military bases and loosen Greek ties with the West. PASOK won
a second four-year term in the 1985 election with 46 percent of the
vote, down from 48 percent in 1981.
   Papandreou's autocratic style has triggered charges from
opposition conservatives that the Socialists practice
``parliamentary tyranny.'' Left-wingers accuse him of betraying his
radical past and ``backsliding into social democracy.''
   His much-publicized relationship with Dimitra Liani, the airline
stewardess, is likely to have a negative effect on the Socialists'
popularity, according to other politicians.
   The tall, blond Ms. Liani stayed with Papandreou in London,
cooking his favorite Greek food, and posing for photographers in
the hospital corridors. His American wife, Margaret, did not go
there.
   ``There is a broad margin of tolerance about these things in
Greece,'' said Leonidas Kyrkos, who heads the small Greek Left
Party. ``But people already think the Dimitra affair has damaged
the country's image and there will be real trouble if she seems to
be actively involving herself in politics.''
   Socialist officials said that even if his recovery stays on
track, Papandreou will have a sharply reduced workload in the
coming months.
   The officials said the premier will handle only pressing foreign
policy issues like the U.S. bases negotiations and a delicate
10-month-old rapprochement with fellow NATO-member Turkey after
years of rivalry over control of the Aegean Sea.
   The bases negotiations are stalling over Greek insistence that
the high-profile U.S. Air Force base at Athens Airport close down
after the current agreement runs out in December.
   Domestic issues, such as a sagging economy, a 14 percent
inflation rate and huge deficits, along with grass-roots
preparation for next year's election campaign, will be left to
trusted aides, the officials said.
   In keeping with his personalized style of rule, Papandreou
refused to name a stand-in during his absence. Cabinet ministers
have been flying to London for instructions and the conservative
opposition has charged the premier was trying to ``fill a power
vacuum with government by telefax.''
   To avoid the suggestion that he was appointing a successor,
Papandreou asked both deputy premiers, Yiannis Haralambopoulos and
Agamemnon Koutsogiorgas, to supervise day-to-day running of the
government.
   Papandreou hasn't given any hints about who might eventually
succeed him as PASOK leader, but Koutsogiorgas, 69, the premier's
personal lawyer and his closest political confidant, is considered
the strongest contender.
   PASOK's membership includes old-fashioned centrists, ambitious
technocrats and radical left-wingers who are likely to clash if
Papandreou steps down. Papandreou founded the party in 1974 and has
always kept a tight grip on its decision-making.
   There is speculation, too, that Koutsogiorgas might eventually
hand over the Socialist leadership to 36-year-old George
Papandreou, the premier's son, and current education minister,
keeping alive the family political dynasty.
   The premier got his start in politics when his father, centrist
Premier George Papandreou, appointed him to a Cabinet job in 1963.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Oct. 18</NOTE>
