<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 16,0507</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, Oct. 16, the 290th day of 1988. There are 76
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   One hundred years ago, playwright Eugene O'Neill was born in New
York City. O'Neill wrote more than 45 plays, including such
classics of American theater as ``The Iceman Cometh'' and ``Long
Day's Journey into Night.'' O'Neill, who won four Pulitzer Prizes
and the Nobel Prize for literature, died in 1953.
   On this date:
   In 1793, Queen Marie Antoinette of France was beheaded.
   In 1846, dentist William T. Morton demonstrated the
effectiveness of ether as an anesthetic by administering it to a
patient undergoing jaw surgery before an audience of doctors in
Boston.
   In 1859, abolitionist John Brown led a group of about 20 men in
a raid on Harper's Ferry.
   In 1916, Margaret Sanger opened the first birth control clinic,
in New York City.
   In 1943, Chicago Mayor Edward J. Kelly snipped a red, white and
blue ribbon to open the city's new subway system.
   In 1946, ten Nazi war criminals condemned during the Nuremberg
trials were hanged.
   In 1957, Britain's Queen Elizabeth and Prince Philip arrived in
Virginia to begin a U.S. tour.
   In 1962, the Cuban missile crisis began as President John F.
Kennedy was informed by his aides that reconaissance photographs
had revealed the presence of missile bases in Cuba.
   In 1964, China became the world's fifth nuclear power as it
detonated its first atomic bomb.
   In 1970, Anwar Sadat was elected president of Egypt, succeeding
the late Gamal Abdel Nasser.
   In 1973, Henry Kissinger and Le Duc Tho were named winners of
the Nobel Peace Prize for negotiating the Vietnam cease-fire
agreement; however, the Vietnamese official declined the award.
   In 1984, Anglican Bishop Desmond Tutu was named the winner of
the Nobel Peace Prize for his decades of non-violent struggle for
racial equality in South Africa.
   Ten years ago: The College of Cardinals of the Roman Catholic
Church, meeting in Vatican City, chose Cardinal Karol Wojtyla of
Poland as pope. The first non-Italian pontiff in 456 years chose
the name John Paul II.
   Five years ago: U.S. Marine Capt. Michael J. Ohler was killed
and three other Marines wounded in a sniper and grenade attack at
Beirut International Airport. The Baltimore Orioles won the World
Series by defeating the Philadelphia Phillies 5-0 in the fifth game
in the best of seven.
   A year ago: A 58{-hour drama in Midland, Texas, ended happily as
rescuers freed Jessica McClure, an 18-month-old girl who had fallen
22 feet down an abandoned well.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Angela Lansbury is 63. Former
presidential adviser Charles W. Colson is 57. Actress Suzanne
Somers is 42.
   Thought for today: ``Each child comes with the message that God
is not yet discouraged of man.'' _ Sir Rabindranath Tagore, Indian
Nobel Prize-winning poet (1861-1941).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
