<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv17   10-10 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 17,0439</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, Oct. 17</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, Oct. 17, the 291st day of 1988. There are 75
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1777, British forces under Gen. John Burgoyne surrendered to
American troops in Saratoga, N.Y., in what was a turning point of
the Revolutionary War.
   On this date:
   In 1919, the Radio Corp. of America was created.
   In 1931, mobster Al Capone was convicted of income tax evasion
and sentenced to 11 years in prison. (He was released in 1939.)
   In 1933, Albert Einstein arrived in the United States as a
refugee from Nazi Germany.
   In 1941, the U.S.Kearney was torpedoed by a German submarine off
the coast of Iceland. Eleven people died.
   In 1945, Juan Peron staged a coup in Buenos Aires, becoming
absolute dictator of Argentina.
   In 1957, Britain's Queen Elizabeth and Prince Philip paid a
visit to the White House.
   In 1957, French author Albert Camus was awarded the Nobel Prize
in literature.
   In 1973, Arab oil-producing nations announced they would begin
cutting back on oil exports to Western nations and Japan. (In the
days that followed, the Arab producers cut off all oil shipments in
an embargo that lasted until March 1974.)
   In 1977, West German commandos stormed a hijacked Lufthansa
jetliner that was on the ground in Mogadishu, Somalia, freeing all
86 hostages aboard and killing three of the four hijackers.
   In 1979, Mother Teresa of India was awarded the Nobel Peace
Prize for her years of work on behalf of the destitute in Calcutta.
   Ten years ago: The New York Yankees won the World Series as they
defeated the Los Angeles Dodgers, 7-2, in the sixth game of the
best of seven. President Jimmy Carter signed a bill restoring U.S.
citizenship to Confederate President Jefferson Davis, who died in
1889.
   Five years ago: President Reagan appointed Robert C. McFarlane
to be his national security adviser, succeeding William P. Clark,
who had become interior secretary.
   A year ago: First lady Nancy Reagan underwent a modified radical
mastectomy at Bethesda Naval Hospital in Maryland to remove her
cancerous left breast.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Jean Arthur is 80. Playwright Arthur
Miller is 73. Actor Tom Poston is 61. Newspaper columnist Jimmy
Breslin is 58. Daredevil Evel Knievel is 50. Actress Margot Kidder
is 40. Actor George Wendt is 40.
   Thought for today: ``It is amazing how complete is the delusion
that beauty is goodness.'' _ Leo Tolstoy, Russian author
(1828-1910).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881010-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0827EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-History Adv18   10-10 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 18,0533</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, Oct. 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, Oct. 18, the 292nd day of 1988. There are 74
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1767, the boundary between Maryland and Pennsylvania, the
Mason-Dixon line, was agreed upon.
   On this date:
   In 1685, King Louis XIV of France revoked the Edict of Nantes,
which had established the legal toleration of France's Protestant
population, the Huguenots.
   In 1867, the United States took formal possession of Alaska from
Russia.
   In 1873, representatives of Columbia, Princeton, Rutgers and
Yale universities drew up the first rules for intercollegiate
football.
   In 1898, the U.S. flag was raised in Puerto Rico shortly before
Spain formally relinquished control of the island to the United
States.
   In 1931, inventor Thomas Alva Edison, died in West Orange, N.J.,
at age 84.
   In 1944, Soviet troops invaded Czechoslovakia during World War
II.
   In 1950, Connie Mack, the ``Grand Old Man'' of major-league
baseball, announced he would retire as the Philadelphia Athletics
manager.
   In 1962, Dr. James D. Watson of the United States and Drs.
Francis Crick and Maurice Wilkins of Britain were named winners of
the Nobel Prize for medicine and physiology for their work in
determining the double-helix molecular structure of DNA
(deoxyribonucleic acid).
   In 1968, the U.S. Olympic Committee suspended two black
athletes, Tommie Smith and John Carlos, for giving a ``black
power'' salute as a protest during their victory ceremony in Mexico
City.
   In 1969, the federal government banned use of the artificial
sweeteners known as cyclamates because of evidence they caused
cancer in laboratory rats.
   In 1977, Reggie Jackson of the New York Yankees tied Babe Ruth's
record of three home runs in one World Series game as New York beat
the Los Angeles Dodgers 8-4 in sixth game of the best-of-seven fall
classic.
   In 1982, former first lady Bess Truman died at her home in
Independence, Mo., at age 97.
   Ten years ago: Former President Gerald R. Ford and his wife,
Betty, announced the engagement of their only daughter, Susan, to
Charles F. Vance, a Secret Service agent.
   Five years ago: Administration sources told The Associated Press
that Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger had recommended to
President Reagan that the United States develop a space-based
missile defense system.
   A year ago: President Reagan summoned congressional leaders to
the White House for a briefing, saying he had decided on what
action to take in response to the Iranian missile attack on a
U.S.-flagged tanker off Kuwait two days earlier.
   Today's birthdays: Former Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Elliott
Trudeau is 69. Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., is 67. Rock star Chuck
Berry is 62. Actor George C. Scott is 61. Sportscaster Keith
Jackson is 60. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci is 58. Football
coach Mike Ditka is 49. Actress Pam Dawber is 37. Tennis star
Martina Navratilova is 32. Jazz trumpeter Wynton Marsalis is 27.
Actress Erin Moran is 27.
   Thought for today: ``The inventor tries to meet the demand of a
crazy civilization.'' _ Thomas Alva Edison (1847-1931).
</TEXT>
