<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek ADV23   10-10 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, ADV 23,0672</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernadette Peters, starring in her first
dramatic TV movie, plays the role of the mother in ABC's ``David,''
which is based on the true story of a 6-year-old boy horribly
burned by his father during a custody dispute.
   It's the story of David Rothenberg, who suffered severe
disfiguring facial burns and is still undergoing therapy at age 12.
The father is currently in prison and comes up for parole late next
year.
   In the movie, which ABC will televise next Tuesday, Peters plays
David's mother, Marie Rothenberg, John Glover portrays the father,
Charles Rothenberg, and Matthew Lawrence plays young David.
   During the filming of one of the earlier scenes, Peters is in
the kitchen furiously fixing spaghetti sauce and arguing with her
ex-husband over his demand to see more of their son.
   Director John Erman calls for another run-through. Peters,
dressed in a brown suit, pauses at the kitchen door with a bag of
groceries in one hand. She wears a lacy white blouse and pearl
earrings, with her brown hair pinned up. At the call of ``action,''
she enters, throws canned goods into the cabinets and starts making
the sauce.
   ``It's Wednesday, the first day,'' Peters explains after
completing the scene. ``The father takes David for the weekend on
Friday. She doesn't find out what happens to David until the
following Thursday. She has another confrontation with Charles on
the telephone. She's beside herself. She wants him to bring David
back.''
   Before starting work on the movie, Peters met with Marie
Rothenberg, who has since remarried, and David.
   ``I asked her what she felt,'' Peters says. ``She said she
thought at first David was going to die. There was only a
thousand-to-one chance he would live. She said if he was going to
live, two minutes, two days or two years, she wanted him to feel
love.
   ``A little boy goes on vacation with his father and wakes up in
a hospital. He can't speak, he can't see. His lungs were badly
burned, so he talks now with a rasp. All she could do was zero in
on the child. All her emotions focused on the child.''
   Peters says David doesn't remember much about the incident.
   Although ``David'' is the first dramatic television movie for
Peters, she began working as a child in New York City, first in a
local children's show. She was on ``Kraft Theater'' at 9 and did a
``Hallmark Hall of Fame'' at 11.
   ``The first big thing I did was `Dames at Sea,''' she says. ``I
was like 19 at the time. I was on Carol Burnett's show a lot. I did
`The Tonight Show' and the `Merv Griffin Show.'''
   Peters starred in numerous Broadway productions, winning a Tony
for her performance as Emma in ``Song & Dance'' in 1985-86. Her
movies include ``The Longest Yard,'' ``W.C. Fields & Me,'' ``Silent
Movie,'' ``The Jerk,'' ``Pennies From Heaven'' and ``Annie.''
   Her latest movie is ``Slaves of New York,'' based on Tama
Janowitz's stories. She plays Eleanor, a designer who is part of
the art world Janowitz writes about.
   Her only series was ``All's Fair'' in 1976-77, which also
starred Richard Crenna.
   ``I think doing a series is very hard,'' she says. ``I haven't
wanted to do one again. I prefer to play all kinds of roles. I
don't want to play the same character for five years. It's more
interesting and more fun to do all kinds of things.''
   She had hoped to take some time off after ``David,'' since she
went into that direct from Stephen Sondheim's musical, ``Into the
Woods.'' But she is currently in Nevada co-starring with Clint
Eastwood in ``Pink Cadillac.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
