<DOCNO> AP881010-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1404EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek ADV23   10-10 1055</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, ADV 23,1083</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The masters are gone, but today the Rodgers and
Hammerstein office is more than just a clearing house for the great
shows of Broadway's most successful musical partnership.
   From what was once Richard Rodgers' Madison Avenue office,
theatrical properties are licensed, protected, polished and even
rediscovered for an empire built upon such smash hits as
``Oklahoma!,'' ``Carousel,'' ``South Pacific,'' ``The King and I''
and ``The Sound of Music.''
   From high school drama society to a big producer in London's
West End, if you want to do a Rodgers and Hammerstein show, you
start there at the office. When the Beef & Boards Dinner Theater in
Indianapolis, for example, decided to do ``The Sound of Music'' in
September, its first task was to contact the R&H office.
   What the dinner theater eventually received, according to its
artistic director-producer Douglas Stark, was a stack of ``Sound of
Music'' scripts and orchestrations which the theater adapted for
its own five-piece orchestra. Royalties were based on a percentage
of box-office gross for the 400-seat theater which has a top price
of $27.95 for dinner and a show on Saturday night.
   That's ``a standard package of material'' says Theodore S.
Chapin, the ebullient 37-year-old executive director of the Rodgers
and Hammerstein office, and son of Schuyler Chapin, once general
manager of the Metropolitan Opera.
   The history of the R&H office dates to 1943, somewhere between
the time ``Oklahoma!'' went into rehearsal and when it opened on
Broadway, when Rodgers and Oscar Hammerstein II realized what
valuable commodities they had created.
   The two men had worked for years with other collaborators _
Rodgers with Lorenz Hart and Hammerstein with Jerome Kern, Sigmund
Romberg and Rudolf Friml, among others.
   ``Their goal was to keep as much in-house as they could,''
Chapin says. ``They got to the point where they were writing,
producing, managing and publishing their own music through the
Williamson Music Co. Both had fathers named William.''
   Among the successful non-Rodgers and Hammerstein shows they
produced were Irving Berlin's ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' ``I Remember
Mama,'' ``John Loves Mary'' and ``The Happy Time.''
   ``What we know today as the stock and amateur market never did
musicals,'' Chapin says. ``High schools did straight plays like
`Charley's Aunt.' It wasn't until the rise of summer tent theater
in the 1950s that the whole secondary market for these musicals
opened up.''
   ``Oklahoma!'' has always been the most popular Rodgers and
Hammerstein musical with strong competition from ``South Pacific''
and ``The Sound of Music.''
   ``One of the amazing things about the Rodgers and Hammerstein
canon is that there are five big shows,'' Chapin says. ``And five
big shows are enough to go in cycles so that when one of them is
dormant, another comes back strong.''
   The rented scripts used for most of the big shows are the London
scripts, Chapin says. One of the things his staff is trying to do
is go through them and change the dialogue to more American
English, taking out the Anglicized words. ``Oklahoma!'' has already
been done and ``South Pacific'' is being worked on now.
   Chapin also got the original scores from the Library of Congress
and had the orchestrations recopied, so copies sent to theaters
could be more authentic.
   ``You would think that there would be absolutely letter-perfect
scripts and orchestrations,'' Chapin says. ``But there weren't.
These two men were savers, but in the backroom and the trunk. They
would change things to make them work on stage.''
   The company's rental library also handles shows by other
authors. It rents most of the Rodgers and Hart musicals, like ``The
Boys from Syracuse,'' ``Babes in Arms'' and ``Pal Joey.'' It also
has Kurt Weill's ``The Threepenny Opera'' and the recent musical
hit ``Big River'' in its catalog.
   When he has a chance, Chapin keeps an eye on different
productions Rodgers and Hammerstein license. In one recent week he
was in Dallas to catch a ``Sound of Music'' with Debby Boone and
then in Chicago to take in ``Pal Joey'' starring Kevin Anderson and
Carlin Glynn.
   One of the strangest productions he has seen was a
show-within-a-show version at New York University. The director set
the musical in a rehabilitation ward, where the recovering veterans
put on ``South Pacific.''
   ``It was a little peculiar,'' he says. ``What we did in that
instance was let them run the contract out. They wanted to extend
the run, but we said no to that.''
   Chapin has not permitted anyone to videotape their productions
because it violates the various shows' movie contracts.
   ``I am very aware of the fact that the authors are not alive,''
Chapin says. ``We are basically in a caretaking position. Their
families have some very strong ideas on how to keep their fathers'
and their husbands' work alive and what changes will or will not be
allowed.''
   Chapin has his own ideas for Rodgers and Hammerstein revivals.
One is a television production of ``Pipe Dream,'' an unsuccessful
musical written for Wagnerian opera singer Helen Traubel. Chapin's
version would star the Muppets.
   ``The musical is based on John Steinbeck's `Sweet Thursday,'
which has a great collection of people who are just hanging around
a skid row,'' Chapin says. He envisions Miss Piggy playing the
Helen Traubel role.
   Chapin is also gearing up for the 50th anniverary of
``Oklahoma!'' in 1993, which should prompt an avalanche of
productions and interest in song-writing team.
   ``America has not forgotten who Rodgers and Hammerstein are,''
Chapin says. ``Hammerstein died in 1960 and Rodgers in 1979, but
their music is still around. `The Sound of Music' is played on
television every year. It has been on the video sales charts for
more than 150 weeks, the last time I looked.''
   And they still get live productions.
   ``These shows are classics,'' says Stark, whose production of
``The Sound of Music'' is running in Indianapolis through Nov. 6.
``People love them and keep coming back. Six years ago, we did `The
Sound of Music' and it's selling better now that it did the last
time.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
