<2ND_LINE>BC-Soviet Stalwarts, Adv 16,0773</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 16, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dreary Soviet Far East has its Stalwarts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Soviet Far East, b0689-b0690</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEVEK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Kirakasyants flies in an old
airplane over frozen seas and tundra. Yuri Moskvin and Boris
Savekin work deep down in the frozen earth.
   Along with thousands of others with roots in more accommodating
places like Leningrad or Moscow, these three men are stalwarts
drawn to the Soviet Far East by the promise of adventure, premium
pay and perhaps a future.
   Pilot Kiraksyants flies research missions over Arctic ice floes
and tundra.
   Polar bears and a harsh, unforgiving climate are facts of life
on the extreme edges of the extreme land where the 28-year-old
Kirakasyants and five other crew members work.
   Flying eight to nine hours a day in their propellor-driven,
35-year-old Ilyushin 14, they chart passages through dense ice
packs for the Soviet Arctic fleet to tiny outposts like Pevek on
the East Siberian Sea, check water temperatures and observe the
movement of whales and walruses.
   And although Kiraksyants is proud of his work and is accustomed
to many of the difficulties of life in the Far East, he sometimes
questions whether it's worth the struggle.
   Like most others who live in the isolated territory,
Kirakasyants was born elsewhere. His father's decision a generation
ago to take a mechanic's job in Pevek led the family from
Leningrad, the Soviet Union's second-largest city, to a settlement
only a handful of Soviets will ever see.
   Thousands of Soviets have made a similar decision, heading north
and east for adventure or pay that averages three to four times
more than workers in the European part of the country.
   ``I went with my father to the airport many times, and he showed
me the planes,'' Kirakasyants said, taking a break during a recent
flight to Lavrentiya on the Bering Strait. ``It determined my
future. I always dreamed of being a pilot.''
   Like many residents here in the Arctic Circle, Kirakasyants
brushes off the effects of temperatures that reach 67 degrees below
zero. The cold is bearable, he said, because the air is dry.
   But life in Pevek is hardly stimulating, he said. Touring groups
from the big cities to the west provide what little cultural
activities are available.
   Food is flown in or brought by ships when ice conditions permit.
   In September, harvest time in the southern Soviet Union, stores
here had grapes, watermelons, plums and other fresh foods. But at
other times of the year such perishables are unavailable and the
supply of staples, other than canned goods, is uncertain.
   Kirakasyants hopes to move someday, but not necessarily back to
a European city. Perhaps, he said, he'd go to Magadan, the
provincial capital of 160,000 people to the southeast on the Sea of
Ohkotsk, and fly passenger jets for Aeroflot, the Soviet airline.
   ``Life is getting better for us here,'' he said, ``but not as
fast as I would like.''
   Yuri Moskvin, 37, and Boris Savekin, 38, the men of the earth,
live south of Pevek in Palatka, a gold-mining area just inland from
Magadan where Kirakasyants would like to go.
   They, too, are thinking of where they might want to go once they
have reaped their rewards from the Soviet Far East and retire.
   Moskvin, a gold-mine shift leader, already knows he's going
someplace warmer and less remote; Savekin, a mechanic in the same
mine, isn't so sure.
   Savekin came to the mine near Palatka 14 years ago and now earns
a salary of 800 rubles ($1,200) a month, four times more than the
nationwide average for an industrial worker. Like others with jobs
underground, he works a six-hour shift, gets 54 days of vacation a
year and will be eligible to retire at age 50.
   Palatka, where Savekin and Moskvin live, is a town of
broken-down wooden buildings and dreary housing blocks.
   Moskvin, a 12-year veteran of the mine, told visiting reporters
that his mother was one of the first Komsomol, or Young Communist
League, workers sent to open up the Far East, so his ties to the
area are long.
   But he said he already has decided to retire somewhere in the
European part of the country.
   Savekin, who hasn't made any definite plans for his future, said
he is satisfied here with the two-room apartment he shares with his
wife and two children, ages 10 and 16.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Oct. 16</NOTE>
