<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Sex Goes With Rock 'n' Roll</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENS FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sex, says Lita Ford, goes with rock 'n'
roll like tires on a cab.
   The compact blonde offers no apologies for the skimpy outfits
and pouty looks she displays on the cover of her third album,
``Lita,'' which produced the hit single, ``Kiss Me Deadly.''
   ``It's advertisement,'' Ford said during a recent dressing room
interview at the Glens Falls Civic Center. ``Besides, you make
money off selling merchandise. I mean, how do you sell a pack of
cigarettes without advertising?''
   Ford, a brash 29-year-old rocker who's posed for publicity
photos wearing nothing more than her guitar, may or may not have
benefited from her particular form of advertising, but she's
leaving little in her career to chance.
   She's taken lessons from vocal coaches and called on well-known
producer and writer Mike Chapman to add his pop sheen to her songs.
Chapman, who produced much of Blondie's best work, helped Ford
write some of her material and convinced his friend, Mick Smiley,
to give her the song ``Kiss Me Deadly.''
   The love, or lust, song with a chiming melody and metallic
crunch made it all the way to No. 12 on the Billboard Top 40 chart,
and the video earned Ford a nomination for best video of the year
by a female artist. Suzanne Vega's ``Luka'' beat her for the trophy.
   ``Our main goal on this album was to go gold and we're almost
platinum so we definitely accomplished what we were looking to
accomplish,'' said Ford, whose first record for RCA has already
sold about 800,000 copies. ``It's not over yet.''
   Ford angrily eschews the label ``heavy metal,'' but she's
co-written songs on ``Lita'' with two of that genre's major stars:
Ozzy Osbourne and Nikki Sixx of Motley Crue.
   And she's parlayed her success with the album into opening act
slots on tours led by metal popsters Poison and Bon Jovi, assuring
her of captive audiences of rabid teen-agers for the next few
months to come.
   Her songs run the gamut of easily-identifiable teen-age
emotions, with such titles as ``Broken Dreams,'' ``Back to the
Cave'' and ``Fatal Passion.''
   The blunt ``Can't Catch Me'' advises a potential boyfriend to
stay away from strong-arm tactics. ``You'd better think twice, I
ain't no Sandra Dee,'' Ford sings. ``Don't think I'm easy, I wasn't
born blonde.''
   Ford, who's pictured on the back cover of her record hoisting a
belt of silver bullets, said she considers herself a role model for
girls who want to enter the world of rock 'n' roll. She advises
them to toughen up.
   ``If that's what they really want to do, just go with it. ...
Don't let any idiots steer you the wrong way,'' she said.
   Her own career started young, at age 16, with the all-female Los
Angeles band the Runaways.
   The Runaways, who played punk rock, were never big sellers and
they took their share of critical lumps before breaking up in the
late 1970s over fights about future direction. But they boast two
successful alumni in Ford and Joan Jett, currently riding high
herself with the hit, ``I Hate Myself for Loving You.''
   ``We were all poor, but we all loved what we were doing,'' Ford
said of her days with the Runaways. ``It was my way of going
through life.''
   She said she keeps rocking because ``it's what I do best,''
though it's not always the easiest career. As she watched a road
crew member drag a cooler of beer and soda across the dressing room
floor, she mused that she'll spend her day off horseback-riding.
   ``Every business has its ups and downs, whether you're a taxi
driver or a rock 'n' roller,'' she said. ``It gets lonely on the
road sometimes. The guys can pal around with the guys, but it gets
real hard for me to just go out and pal around with the guys,
because I'm not one of the guys.''
   Although she appreciates the power and excitement of the music,
Ford also recognizes it's a job _ leading to a slightly cynical
view of what she's doing.
   ``It's a product, it's something that you sell,'' she said.
``Music, cigarettes, an amp, a carpet _ what's the difference? It's
all a material thing that you sell.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct 21-23</NOTE>
