<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct 21-23 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Bob Bailey's Odyssey Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Bailey has been fired by Jim Bakker
and appeared in the movie ``Animal House.''
   His odyssey now continues in Nashville where he sings rhythm and
blues in a city more famous for its country licks and
cry-in-your-beer weepers. He has a new, well-crafted album, ``Bob
Bailey,'' with his version of Marvin Gaye's ``Inner City Blues''
and Stevie Wonder's ``Heaven Help Us All.''
   The LP is the latest addition to Bailey's bulging resume that
darts from the silver screen to the PTL Club to the Nashville
recording studios.
   Thirteen years ago, Bailey was singing in a nightclub in Eugene,
Ore., when the late John Belushi walked in and asked him to play a
bit part in ``Animal House.'' Bailey played piano in the movie as a
member of the band Otis Day and the Knights _ a band that also
included guitarist Robert Cray, later to become a top rock singer
and musician.
   ``He was a nice man,'' the 32-year-old Bailey recalled about
Belushi. ``He was out of control even back then. Several times they
delayed production so he could get his thoughts together. He loved
to party.
   ``He was a gifted performer and in the way he handled himself in
front of the camera, he was a master.''
   In 1978, Bailey began a three-year stint as a singer on the PTL
Club on television. He was one of seven members of the PTL Singers
and did some solos.
   He was fired in 1981 for refusing to sing on Sundays, his day
off, in the music department of a new PTL church in Charlotte, N.C.
   Bailey has mixed memories of Jim and Tammy Bakker, the leaders
of the PTL ministry at that time and stars of the PTL Club show.
   ``I think both Jim and Tammy were quite covetous of their
stardom and were not willing to share it with anyone,'' he said in
an interview. ``I think they misunderstood the concept of family
and that when one aspect or one member of the body does well, it
reflects on everybody and doesn't take away from anybody. They were
afraid their stardom or their position was being threatened by
myself and others. ...
   ``But on the other side, they could be very warm, giving,
supportive people. They were extremely kind to me and others on the
singing staff.
   ``It was a marvelous learning opportunity for me both
spiritually and musically and otherwise. This was one of the best,
if not the best, examples of how to do live television.''
   After leaving the PTL show, he moved to Nashville and continued
singing gospel music. In 1981, he released his first album, a
gospel LP titled ``Looking Forward.'' Then in 1984, he was a
finalist for a Grammy Award in gospel music for his second album,
``I'm Walkin'.''
   ``It was an interesting year,'' said Bailey, a native of
Middletown, Ohio, who was raised in Portland, Ore.
   Bailey, a native of Middletown, Ohio, who was raised in
Portland, Ore., also participated in the ``Exaltation'' album that
won a Dove Award from the Gospel Music Association for best worship
LP.
   He developed his songwriting talents and planned his move into
the rhythm and blues-urban contemporary field _ a step previously
undertaken by such stars as Aretha Franklin, Sam Cooke and Al Green.
   The first single release from his current album is ``Project
Girl,'' which carries a message of hope to young people born into
ghetto poverty. The song has the compelling line: ``She might be
poor but she ain't cheap.''
   ``I believe in music with a message,'' Bailey said. ``I believe
in the power of music. It reaches people's lives that can not be
reached otherwise. I want to be positive and sing songs that
inspire people and change their lives.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct 21-23</NOTE>
</DOC>
