<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--Briefs ADV13   10-10 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Briefs, ADV 13,0825</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday, Oct. 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bacterial Illness Linked To Raw Hot Dogs, Undercooked Chicken</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bacteria that can cause an often fatal infection
in infants and the elderly has been linked to the consumption of
raw hot dogs and undercooked chicken, says a government report.
   The U.S. Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta found that
people infected with the bacteria listeria monocytogenes were
significantly more likely than others to have eaten raw hot dogs or
undercooked chicken, suggesting that those foods were the source of
the infection.
   In a report in The Lancet, a British medical journal, the CDC
said that infection with listeria, or listeriosis, was reported in
154 Americans in 1986 and 1987. One-third of the cases occurred in
newborns, who got the infection before birth from their mothers.
The rest occurred in the elderly and in people whose immune systems
were impaired for other reasons.
   Twenty-eight percent of those infected died, the CDC said.
   Several outbreaks of listeria have attracted wide attention
during the past few years. The outbreaks have occurred in
vegetables and more often in cheese or other dairy products.
   One of the most notable outbreaks, which occurred in 1985 in
California, led to 239 illnesses and 81 deaths.
   ``Our results add to a growing body of evidence that consumption
of contaminated food is a risk factor for listeriosis,'' the CDC's
report said. ``Although our findings need to be replicated, they
suggest that undercooked poultry and uncooked hot dogs need to be
added to a list of foods associated with listeriosis _ a list that
already includes vegetables and dairy products.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pediatricians Discourage Infant Exercise Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics has
recommended against structured exercise programs for infants,
saying there is no evidence they promote skills or provide any
long-term benefit to normal children.
   Adults may inadvertently exceed an infant's physical limitations
in such programs, the academy's committee on sports medicine said
this month in a policy statement.
   Most programs involve massage techniques and passive exercises,
and some involve the purchase of exercise equipment, the academy
said.
   Parents do not need specialized skills or equipment to provide a
stimulating environment, which is very important for infant
development, the committee said.
   ``An infant should be provided with opportunities for touching,
holding, face-to-face contact, and minimally structured playing
with safe toys. If these opportunities occur, an infant's intrinsic
motivation will guide his or her individual development course,''
the committee said.
   Later in the child's life, parents should exercise to set a good
example, prevent television-watching from taking up exercise time
and stress physical activities that the child can continue for a
lifetime, academy president Richard Narkewicz said in a telephone
interview.
   Lifelong activities including cycling, jogging, swimming,
running, fast walking and tennis, he said. Parents should also ask
schools to stress such activities, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nursing Home Residents To Get Massages In Psychiatric Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen nursing home residents will get
frequent massages in a study aimed at learning if the human touch
is better than medication in treating depression, withdrawal and
other behavior problems.
   ``Previous studies have demonstrated a strong psychological need
for touch in both humans and animals,'' said Dr. James Dietch, a
psychiatrist at the University of California, Irvine. ``Some
studies suggest touch may be as important as food.''
   Dietch said his study is meant to determine if inadequate
physical stimulation contributes to anxiety, withdrawal, violence
and depression among elderly nursing home residents suffering
Alzheimer's disease or other loss of mental powers.
   The study, supported by a $15,000 grant from the Retirement
Research Foundation, involves 30 patients at the Hillhaven Special
Care Unit, a 60-bed skilled nursing facility in Anaheim.
   After two weeks of physical tests and behavioral assessments, 15
of the patients will receive hour-long upper back and shoulder
massages three or four times weekly for six weeks starting in
mid-October. Nurses' aides will perform the massages. The other 15
patients won't get massages.
   ``We will try to address such issues as the extent to which
massage therapy can reduce a patient's need for tranquilizing
medication, the optimum amount of therapy needed to produce the
maximum benefit, identification of patients most likely to respond
to such treatment, and the cost effectiveness of the treatment,''
Dietch said.
   Sedatives and tranquilizers usually are used to treat behavior
problems among nursing home patients.
   Yet ``studies show that less than half the behaviorally
disturbed patients who receive these drugs benefit from them, and
many suffer adverse effects such as sedation, dizziness and
increased confusion,'' Dietch said. ``These drugs also have been
shown to increase the risk of falling, which can lead to serious
problems such as hip fractures.''
</TEXT>
