<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Home Electronics: Radio,0109</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Electronics: Radio</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY701</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1932, when the General Electric J100 radio was introduced, it
cost a then-impressive $99 for the family to gather around and
listen to comedian Jack Benny, bandleader Benny Goodman and the
``Buck Rogers'' serial.
   Today, GE is selling a re-created version of that living room
radio, at three-quarter scale, for $75.
   Fifty-six years ago, the typical table radio had a wooden
cabinet, weighed 40 pounds, consumed 100 watts of electricity and
required a 50-foot antenna, GE says. The replica consumes
one-twentieth of the power, has two built-in antennas and weighs
five pounds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
