<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 0718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   10-10 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0557</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the New York Stock Exchange said
last October's crash was caused by internal technical market
problems and not economic changes, and he defended trading halts to
avoid another meltdown.
   In an interview Friday, John Phelan conceded the ``circuit
breakers'' proposal for coordinated trading halts with other
exchanges is an artificial restraint on the free-trading system,
which he dislikes in theory.
   ``I think all of us in general don't like to shut markets down
because it ruins liquidity,'' Phelan said. ``But there are a few
points in time when you need to shut it down.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia, seeking to restore order
to OPEC's pricing system, is increasing pressure on overproducing
cartel members by stepping up its own oil output _ and industry
analysts predict the tactic will work.
   The strategy _ which has forced the price of oil dramatically
lower _ will enable the Saudis and other members of the 13-nation
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to stake out
positions prior to key meetings expected to be held this month and
next, the analysts said Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Budget Rent a Car Corp., the nation's only
remaining publicly held rental-car agency, announced it is
exploring a sale of the company.
   Clifton E. Haley, Budget's president, said Friday the company
``has retained the firm of Morgan Stanley and Co. to explore
strategic alternatives to enhance stockholder values, including a
possible sale of Budget.''
   The decision reflects the board's belief that the market price
for Budget stock does not adequately reflect the company's true
value, Haley said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. is fighting back from its
losses in the retail market with innovations ranging from in-store
post offices to ``McKids'' clothing, in hopes of catching up with
nimble specialty merchandisers.
   Sears on Friday launched a test of post offices within stores at
10 Chicago-area sites and one in Wisconsin in a cooperative project
with the U.S. Postal Service.
   Sears also has opened a handful of in-store appliance and home
electronics outlets known as Brand Central, which offer brand-name
goods along with Sears' private-label brands.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oil Barrel Special, a four-course meal that
costs the same as the day's price of a barrel of crude, is back on
the menu at La Colombe d'Or.
   The restaurant began the lunch promotion two years ago but
stopped when oil prices began inching upward.
   ``As soon as the oil price drop hit the papers this week, we had
people calling us up and asking whether we still had the Oil Barrel
Special,'' proprietor Steve Zimmerman said. ``I said, `Why not?'''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose sharply Friday to some of their highest levels
since last year's crash, inspired by news of smaller-than-expected
employment growth last month. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials jumped 42.50 points to 2,150.25.
   The dollar closed narrowly lower. Gold prices were little
changed.
   Bond prices surged.
   Soybean futures prices plunged, wheat prices rallied, corn
prices dipped, cocoa prices surged, oil prices advanced, cattle and
hog prices were mixed, and frozen pork bellies were sharply lower.
</TEXT>
