<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BritainStocks     10-10 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain Stocks,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Move Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices moved higher Monday, gaining ground
mostly on the back of Wall Street's buoyant performance on Friday.
   However, trading activity was quiet and further gains were
limited by weekend statements by Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel
Lawson, dealers said.
   Lawson indicated in a television interview he would push up
interest rates if the pound fell. On Monday, the pound was trading
higher than Friday's closing levels.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was up 6.9
points, or 0.4 percent, at 1,851.6 at midday.
   Volume was light, as 236.9 million shares changed hands,
compared with 373.1 million shares at the same time Friday.
   Trading activity focused primarily on special situations, as a
handful of stocks rose on takeover speculation.
   But underpinning the overall market was Friday's sharp gain in
New York, where the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 42.50
points to 2,150.25. The Wall Street rally followed the release of
U.S. unemployment figures, which showed slower-than-expected growth
in September, helping to ease fears of a further increase in
interest rates.
</TEXT>
