<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Griffin-Resorts     10-10 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Griffin-Resorts,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Griffin To Earlier Merger Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merv Griffin's organization said today it had
given itself an option to drop its bid for Resorts International
Inc., a move that could give it leverage to lower its takeover
offer.
   ``We have not made any decision that we're going to terminate.
On the other hand, we're not giving them any assurance that the
deal is going to go forward,'' said Thomas Gallagher, a spokesman
for Griffin Co.
   Griffin is offering $36 a share for Resorts, which owns Resorts
International Casino Hotel in Atlantic City, N.J., and vast real
estate holdings there, as well as a casino and property in the
Bahamas.
   Under his plan, Griffin would take the company private by buying
out all the stock, including that held by billionaire developer
Donald Trump.
   Griffin's latest move could be a signal that the millionaire and
former talk-show host believes he can get Resorts at a lower price
by threatening to withdraw from the deal altogether.
   Griffin's acquisition depends on several conditions, including
approvals by the New Jersey Casino Control Commission and
authorities in the Bahamas.
   One key approval was granted last week by the Internal Revenue
Service. The Casino Control Commission was scheduled to vote
Tuesday regarding Griffin's eligibility to hold a casino license in
New Jersey.
   The latest deadline for completion of the acquisition was
allowed to expire last Friday without extension. Griffin said that
means that any party to the deal is free to terminate its
obligations at any time.
   In a separate matter, Griffin's organization said it had decided
that if it does complete the acquisition, it will be by means of a
merger rather than a tender offer. The amount paid to shareholders,
$36 a share in cash, is not affected by the decision.
   A merger offer was approved on Aug. 30 by the requisite number
of shareholders, Griffin said.
   The proposal calls for Griffin to pay Trump $135 a share, or $96
million, for Trump's Class B stock. Trump also would receive
another $63 million from Griffin to break Trump's management
agreement with Resorts.
   Griffin's tender offer for holders of Class A stock would cost
him $205.2 million. Griffin would also invest $50 million in
Resorts to help it generate enough cash flow to cover interest
payments on Resorts' debt.
   In turn, Trump would pay Resorts $273 million for the
unfinished, 1,250-room Taj Mahal Casino, which is next door to the
Resorts International Casino Hotel and is owned by Resorts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
