<1ST_LINE>a f BC-XerographyAnniversary Adv15-16   10-10 1059</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Xerography Anniversary, Adv 15-16,1086</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 15</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Oct. 15-16 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Xerography, At 50, Father of Copier Revolution</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Go into any business and look past the
desks, the computers, the file cabinets, the telephones and chances
are you'll find a copier.
   It's a machine that's taken for granted now that copiers have
found their way into schools, shopping centers and even homes.
   But it was just 50 years ago _ on Oct. 22, 1938 _ that Chester
F. Carlson, a patent worker, invented the process that's at the
heart of every copier.
   His discovery of xerography, the dry method for making
duplicates, helped give birth to the billion-dollar Xerox Corp.,
now based in Stamford, Conn., and in the process, changed the way
the world communicates.
   ``In the history of mankind, there were very few revolutions in
communications, and they all led to the democratization of the
media. The last big revolution prior to Carlson was Gutenberg's
invention,'' said Paul A. Strassman, a former Xerox vice president
now working as an author, teacher and consultant in New Canaan.
   George White, vice president for research at the University of
Pittsburgh and another former Xerox vice president, agreed that
Carlson's invention was as important as Johannes Gutenberg's
invention of printing with moveable type in the 15th century. But
he said it also enabled all workers to participate in business
communications and established the office supplies business as a
multibillion-dollar market.
   ``It liberated the personal initiatives of everyone in the paper
stream. You didn't have to write a book to distribute your notes.
You could type them up and distribute them by xerography,'' he said.
   This freedom is something that doesn't exist with other office
equipment, including the personal computer, White said. Using a
copier requires no training, little expense and time, and works in
all languages. This is particularly important in such countries as
Japan, where copiers are immensely important, because of the
complexity of their written language, he said.
   ``It is probably culturally unbiased more than anything else you
can think of,'' White said.
   Dataquest Inc., a market research firm in San Jose Calif.,
estimates that more than 4.8 million copiers were in use in the
United States last year. Combined, the machines produced an
estimated 490 billion copies and generated revenues in excess of
$15 billion, according to Dataquest.
   What makes the numbers truly astounding is that the first
easy-to-use office copier wasn't marketed until 1960, when Xerox
introduced its famous 914 model. The machine's name was derived
from the fact that it produced a copy as large as 9 inches by 14
inches.
   In between 1938 and 1960, millions of dollars and countless
hours were spent by Carlson and hundreds of other scientists to
make his invention accessible to everyone.
   But the story of xerography actually began while Carlson worked
in the patent office of the P.R. Mallory & Co. in New York City.
Because of legal requirements, numerous copies of patents had to be
made, often by hand. Carlson, who suffered from arthritis,
determined there had to be a better way.
   With a physics degree from the California Institute of
Technology, Carlson began researching scientific literature at the
New York Public Library. This led to experiments at a laboratory he
built and financed out of his own pocket.
   The experiments consisted of putting an electrostatic charge
into metal plates, and then exposing the plates to light. In this
manner, he was able to create patterns that could be used in
printing.
   On Oct. 22, 1938, at his laboratory in Astoria, N.Y., he
produced his first successful duplicate using this process. The
first words reproduced through xerography said simply, ``10-22-38
ASTORIA.''
   Carlson knew he had made a discovery of immense importance, but
he couldn't find a company interested in developing his invention.
More than 20 companies, including General Electric and RCA,
rejected his invention as insignificant.
   Six years after his discovery, he mentioned his invention to Dr.
Russell W. Dayton of the Battelle Memorial Institute, then a small
research organization in Columbus, Ohio. Battelle asked to see the
process and then agreed to undertake its development.
   Among those who worked on developing xerography was Paul Andrus,
who joined Battelle in 1947 shortly after graduating from the
University of Wisconsin. Andrus, who still works at Battelle, went
on to earn 15 patents in the xerography field.
   ``I can remember the first day I saw the process, in a fairly
crude form, and I thought this is really an interesting process. A
person can really get his hands on it and understand the physics of
it. I was impressed,'' Andrus said.
   But, Andrus said, no one working on xerography had any
indication that it would become a process of such tremendous
significance. He recalled that his boss speculated Battelle might
someday need one copier to satisfy its needs.
   Over the years, Battelle's share in xerography profits has
provided the organization with about $300 million, said Douglas E.
Olesen, Battelle president and chief executive officer.
   ``It was the major milestone in our history by any measurement,
financial or technical,'' Olesen said. ``It did more than anything
to establish Battelle as an organization that could put technology
to work.''
   But Battelle couldn't develop xerography alone. In 1946,
Battelle realized it needed additional financing to make Carlson's
invention practical. A year later, it signed an agreement with a
small Rochester, N.Y., company known as Haloid Co.
   Battelle and Haloid, working together, unveiled their first
copier in 1948. But it required 14 complex steps to operate, and it
was not enthusiastically received by businesses. Still, the
machine, known as the OxBox, or the Model A, eventually did fill a
need in the offset printing business.
   Encouraged by this limited success, Battelle and Haloid
continued to work on the machine, with Haloid eventually assuming
the bulk of the scientific, as well as manufacturing
responsibilities. The first machine was improved again and again
through subsequent models, until 1960, when the 914 was introduced.
   Following the success of that copier, the Haloid company
formally changed its name to the Xerox Corp. It had spent $60
million and obtained more than 200 patents in advancing xerography
from Carlson's crude invention to a truly automatic machine.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Oct. 15-16</NOTE>
