<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Open Higher, Grains Lower On Harvest Estimate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures opened slightly higher while
grain futures opened mostly lower today on the Chicago Board of
Trade in reaction to new production estimates by a respected
private analyst.
   The Chicago-based analyst, Conrad Leslie, pegged 1988 U.S.
soybean production at 1.48 billion bushels and predicted a corn
harvest of 4.55 billion bushels.
   Leslie released his influential estimates ahead of the
Agriculture Department's production estimates, which will be
released Wednesday afternoon.
   Both of Leslie's numbers were higher than the USDA's September
estimates of 1.47 billion bushels of soybeans and 4.46 billion
bushels of corn. But analysts said Leslie's soybean number was
lower than traders had expected and it prompted some buying of
soybean futures.
   Leslie's corn production number was higher than expected and
sparked some selling of corn futures, analysts said.
   Selling linked to the advancing corn and soybean harvest also
weighed on the market, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.33 a bushel; corn was 1
cent lower to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.93{ a bushel;
oats were 2{ cents to 4} cents higher with December at $2.49 a
bushel; soybeans were 2} cents to 5 cents higher with November at
$7.93 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent lower to .35 cent higher with October
at 72.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .13
cent higher with October at 82.20 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent
lower to .23 cent higher with October at 40.50 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .38 cent to .70 cent higher with February
at 47.90 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Friday.
</TEXT>
