<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TennecoSale     10-10 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tenneco Sale,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tenneco Expects Oil Company Sale Will Gross $7.3 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tenneco Inc. announced today it has entered into
definitive contracts with several buyers for the sale of almost all
of its oil and gas businesses and that it expects the transactions
to gross more than $7.3 billion.
   Tenneco did not name the buyers. However, Mesa Limited
Partnership, controlled by Texas oilman T. Boone Pickens, announced
it has agreed to buy Tenneco's oil and gas production in its
mid-continent division for $715 million in cash.
   In addition, Seagull Energy Corp. announced today it had signed
letters of intent to buy Tenneco's Houston Oil & Minerals Corp. for
$16.4 million.
   It was also announced today that Seagull has agreed to buy the
assets of the Houston Oil Trust for $35.3 million and Houston Oil
Royalty Trust for $4.5 million in separate transactions.
   Negotiations are continuing for certain minor portions of
Tenneco's oil and gas segment, but the company said it expects
total gross proceeds from the sales to exceed the $7.3 billion
mark, according to a statement released today.
   Although the Houston-based company did not disclose any details
about the agreements, it said more information would be released
Tuesday following a board meeting.
   Tenneco, the nation's 10th largest oil company, had previously
said it expects all of the transactions to be closed by the end of
the year.
   The company announced in May it was getting out of the petroleum
exploration and production business, which represents about 20
percent of its assets, and would concentrate on its pipeline and
other industrial businesses7.
   When Tenneco made the announcement, it said proceeds would be
used to help pay its hefty $8.5 billion debt. Analysts have
estimated that the sale could fetch between $5 billion and $7
billion.
</TEXT>
