<DOCNO> AP881010-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Wynn-Claridge     10-10 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Wynn-Claridge,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gaming Analysts Keeping An Eye on Wynn's Move</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gaming analysts are keeping an eye on Golden
Nugget Inc. Chairman Steve Wynn's latest move, the purchase of the
troubled Claridge Hotel and Casino in Atlantic City.
   Wynn announced the purchase last Monday, saying Las Vegas-based
Golden Nugget will buy the property for $110 million if the sale is
approved by the hotel's management groups and New Jersey gaming
regulators.
   The Claridge property lost $78.8 million last year.
   Daniel Lee, a gaming industry analyst for Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., a New York-based investment firm, said Wynn has the potential
to turn the Claridge into one of the more profitable casinos in
Atlantic City.
   ``This is the chance for Steve Wynn to prove himself as a
genius,'' Lee said. ``He has always talked about the Golden
Nugget's marketing. Now, the Claridge gives him the perfect place
to prove himself right.''
   Marvin Roffman, a gaming analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott in
Philadelphia, said Wynn will offer a challenge to Atlantic City's
11 other resorts.
   Because the purchase price is relatively low, Wynn's overhead
will be such that he can offer favorable odds to the gambler,
Roffman said.
   ``Steve Wynn, in my opinion, is the most creative marketing man
I've ever seen in the casino business,'' Roffman said.
   Wynn sold his Golden Nugget Hotel and Casino in Atlantic City to
Bally Manufacturing Co. 20 months ago for $440 million. He retained
25 acres of land in the city for a possible return to gaming in New
Jersey.
   But the purchase of the Claridge came as a surprise.
   The move came two days after Wynn took control of the Nevada
Club casino in Laughlin, Nev. He bought the casino for $40 million
from Del Webb, the same company that owns the Claridge.
   Wynn's 3,200-room, $550 million Golden Nugget on the Las Vegas
Strip is scheduled to open late next year.
   Standard & Poor's issued a news release last week following
Wynn's Claridge announcement, saying Wynn's marketing skills would
be challenged by the loss-riddled Atlantic City property.
</TEXT>
