<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Furr'sSuit     10-10 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Furr's Suit,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cafeteria Chain Sues Grocery Stores over Recipes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Furr's-Bishop's Cafeterias L.P. has filed
a $65 million lawsuit against Furr's Inc., a grocery chain,
claiming it stole top-secret recipes.
   The cafeteria company alleges Furr's Inc. has appropriated and
used Furr's-Bishop's recipes for preparation and sale of its food
items.
   The suit filed Friday in state district court here names Furr's
Inc., members of its management and two former Furr's-Bishop's
employees, Joe Sherwood and Rowena Johnson, who now work for the
grocery store chain.
   Furr's-Bishop's alleges that Sherwood and Johnson obtained major
portions of the company's recipe books and took the recipes with
them when they were hired by Furr's Inc.
   The cafeteria company accuses the two of disclosing the
information when Furr's Inc. opened several cafeterias in San
Angelo and Amarillo.
   In addition to monetary damages, Furr's-Bishop's also seeks a
court ruling prohibiting Furr's Inc. from continuing to use the
recipes, which the cafeteria company claims are valuable trade
secrets.
   Both companies are based in Lubbock.
   Furr's-Bishop's operates 154 restaurants in 17 states and is the
second-largest cafeteria operator in the country.
   Furr's Inc. has 154 stores in New Mexico and Texas and had about
$150 million in sales in 1987.
   The two companies began as part of the same family-owned
enterprise, which was later split into cafeteria and grocery store
companies. Both entities were eventually bought by outsiders, the
grocery stores by a West German investment group and the cafeterias
by K mart Corp.
   Furr's-Bishop's Cafeterias L.P. was formed after investor
Michael Levenson purchased the chain from K mart.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
