<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 1619EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-TWA-Icahn     10-10 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-TWA-Icahn,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holders of TWA Preferred Stock Agree To Give Up Voting Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trans World Airlines Inc. said Monday that most
holders of TWA preferred stock have agreed to give up their voting
rights, clearing another obstacle to Chairman Carl C. Icahn's plan
to take the airline private.
   TWA said it expected the privatization to be completed about
Oct. 24.
   The airline said around 83 percent of the holders of its
remaining class of preferred shares who cast ballots consented to
Icahn's proposal to eliminate their right to vote in elections of
TWA directors. Last month, the other TWA preferred issues were
converted into 12 percent notes due in 2008.
   ``This was the last major procedural block'' related to TWA's
capital structure that remained in the way of the privatization
plan, said Mark Buckstein, senior vice president and general
counsel for the airline.
   Other roadblocks remain, however. The union representing TWA
flight attendants has asked the Department of Transportation to
block the privatization and freeze the airline's assets while it
investigates Icahn's fitness to continue managing TWA.
   The Consumer Federation of America has filed a similar petition.
   And a lawsuit filed by the TWA pilots union alleges that Icahn's
plan to go private is a breach of the agreements the union made
with him during his takeover of the carrier.
   The battle between Icahn and TWA's unions spilled over into
Congress late last month, as lawmakers dueled over whether a House
subcommittee should scrutinize the dispute.
   Icahn, an aggressive bidder for corporations, reportedly has had
recent discussions with Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo
about acquiring ailing Eastern Airlines from Texas Air.
   The TWA chairman, who now owns around 77 percent of TWA's 30.5
million common shares outstanding, won approval from shareholders
in early September for his privatization plan.
   Under the plan, Icahn and the financial entities controlled by
him would own about 90 percent of TWA's stock, while the remaining
shares would be held by an employee stock ownership plan.
   Airline industry analysts estimate the bid puts a value of
around $40 a share, or $304.8 million, on the TWA shares that Icahn
does not already own.
   Shareholders not affiliated with Icahn would receive for each
share of common stock $20 in cash and $30 in face amount of the 12
percent notes due 2008. Holders of the remaining class of preferred
stock would receive 25 cents a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
