<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0021,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares End Dull Session Near Day's Low</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished an uneventful session
slightly lower Monday, as the market awaited a series of economic
reports due later in the week.
   Dealers said some of the market's enthusiasm of past weeks was
sapped by weekend statements by British Chancellor of the Exchequer
Nigel Lawson, who indicated that interest rates would likely remain
high over the near term to wring inflationary pressures from the
British economy.
   Lawson's remarks ``stopped last week's rise dead in its
tracks,'' said one market maker.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished off
0.6 point, or 0.03 percent, at 1,844.1, slightly above its worst
level for the day of 1,844.0. The index hit its session high of
1,852.2 at mid-morning.
   Of the 100-share index's stocks, 44 were lower, 36 were higher
and 20 were unchanged.
   Volume was light, as just 423.6 million shares changed hands,
compared with the 583.7 million shares Friday.
   Activity was subdued ahead of the economic reports due out later
this week, dealers said. Among these will be Thursday's release of
U.S. trade figures for August. In Britain, retail price figures
were due Friday.
</TEXT>
