<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed higher, wheat
finished lower and corn futures closed mixed Monday on the Chicago
Board of Trade, reflecting differing opinions about the size of the
nation's corn and soybean crops.
   The Agriculture Department will release its updated crop
production estimates Wednesday afternoon. Trading activity ahead of
the report typically revolves around speculation about the
government report.
   Traders generally expect the government to increase its
production estimates from last month's predictions of 1.47 billion
bushels of soybeans and 4.46 billion bushels of corn, analysts said.
   Higher numbers are expected because with the harvest about half
finished, farmers are reporting better yields than most experts had
projected, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   On Monday, the respected Chicago-based crop analyst Conrad
Leslie pegged 1988 U.S. soybean production at 1.48 billion bushels
and predicted a corn harvest of 4.55 billion bushels.
   The predictions prompted some buying of soybean futures and
selling of corn futures, Lespinasse said. But in general, he added,
``we're all just marking time, waiting for Wednesday.''
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents to 7\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.27{ a bushel; corn was 2
cents lower to 2\ cents higher with December at $2.92{ a bushel;
oats were 2{ cents to 4{ cents higher with December at $2.47 a
bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 6 cents higher with November at
$7.93 a bushel.
</TEXT>
