<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market showed no clear trend today in
a quiet Columbus Day session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 42.50 on Friday,
rose another 8.36 to 2,158.61 by 3 p.m. on Wall Street.
   But losers slightly outnumbered gainers in nationwide trading of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 650 up, 704 down and
518 unchanged.
   Stocks had trouble extending Friday's strong rally in the
absence of many investors who were taking Columbus Day off.
   The market for government securities, which sets the tone for
interest rates, did not operate today.
   Still, analysts said traders were heartened by the news on
Friday of smaller-than-expected employment growth in September.
   The resulting rally in the bond and stock prices carried
stock-market indicators near or, in some cases, past the levels
they reached in early July, which marked their peaks since the
crash a year ago.
   Best Products led the active list, up 5~ at 26|. The company
agreed to be acquired by a New York investment firm for $27.50 a
share.
   Pinnacle West tumbled 3~ to 19. The company's chairman said
Friday that its 1989 earnings probably won't be enough to keep the
dividend at its present level.
   General Electric, which reported a 17 percent increase in its
third-quarter earnings, rose [ to 44[
   Among other actively traded blue chips, American Telephone &
Telegraph rose { to 27; American Express gained 1\ to 30, and
International Business Machines was up [ at 116[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added
.23 to 157.04. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .28 at 303.54.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 106.72 million shares with two
hours to go.
