<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Consolidated-Minorco     10-10 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Consolidated-Minorco,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minorco Says It Would Sell Target's 49.3 Percent Newmont Mining
Stake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African-controlled Minorco SA, which has
offered $3.5 billion for the 70.6 percent of Consolidated Gold
Fields PLC it does not already own, said Monday it would sell
Consolidated's 49.3 percent stake in Newmont Mining Corp. if its
bid were successful.
   The stake of about 33 million Newmont Mining shares was worth
about $1.25 billion at Monday's late-afternoon price of $37.87{ a
share on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Luxembourg-based Minorco, which already owns 29.4 percent of
Consolidated Gold Fields, is controlled by Anglo American Corp. and
De Beers Consolidated Mines Ltd., the gold and diamond mining
interests of the wealthy Oppenheimer family of South Africa.
   A spokesman for Minorco could not be reached for comment. His
office telephone was answered by an answering machine late Monday.
   Minorco's cash and stock offer currently values the entire
company at $5 billion, or $21.80 a share. Consolidated Gold Fields
shares closed Monday at 12.87 pounds, or about $22 a share, down 16
pence, or 27 cents a share, on London's Stock Exchange.
   Minorco said its decision to sell the stake follows New
York-based Newmont Mining's decision to join Consolidated in asking
President Reagan to block the Minorco bid and Newmont's failure to
take up an offer of direct talks with Minorco. It said it would
sell the stake at the best possible terms.
   Previously, Minorco had said it would negotiate with Newmont
Mining to reduce Consolidated's stake in Newmont Mining.
   Consolidated and Newmont Mining appealed to President Reagan on
Thursday to block the bid, saying it would affect U.S. national
security because of Minorco's South African links.
   Consolidated also has asked the British government to review the
bid because of the South African connection.
   The Pretoria government is also investigating the proposed
acquisition.
   In another development, the government of Papua New Guinea said
Monday it would order Minorco to divest itself of Consolidated Gold
Fields' gold interests there because of its South African
ownership, Consolidated said.
   ``We cannot allow this apartheid regime to benefit from our rich
resources,'' Prime Minister Rabbie Namaliu said in a statement
provided by the London-based gold mining company.
   South Africa's apartheid system has allowed the white minority
to control the government.
   Minorco said when it launched the bid Sept. 21 that it would
sell Consolidated's South African interests to a South African
company.
   Consolidated Chairman Rudolph Agnew said Monday: ``They have
already said they will sell GFSA (the South African interests). Now
they are saying Newmont is available for sale on the best terms
possible. They have been told they will have to divest in Papua New
Guinea. What will be left by the closing date?''
</TEXT>
