<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls In Thin Trading; Gold Prices Climb</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 6th graf, But trading ..., to explain
who was trading in the United States; picks up 7th graf, Monday's
thin ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar tumbled Monday in light trading that
was unusually jumpy because most of the major traders in the United
States and Japan had the day off.
   Gold prices rose, boosted by a jump in oil prices. Republic
National Bank of New York, which traded in spite of a bank holiday,
said gold was bid at $408.75 as of the close of trading at 2:30
p.m. EDT, up from $403.30 an ounce as of Friday at 4 p.m.
   Traders described the dollar's decline as a continuation of the
trend that began Friday, when the Labor Department reported a
smaller-than-expected increase in U.S. non-farm jobs in September.
   Slower economic growth means flat or lower interest rates, which
would make dollar-denominated investments less attractive to
foreign investors.
   Some traders were also concerned that the government's report
due Thursday on the August trade deficit would hurt the dollar.
   But trading was so light Monday that some major traders might
not regard the dollar's drop as a reliable indicator of its
underlying trend, said Jack Adkins, a currency analyst for Refco
Partners Ltd. in Chicago.
   Those trading in the United States were mainly brokerage houses,
other financial firms, and banks that kept their currency-trading
operations open in spite of the holiday.
   Monday's thin trading turned the attention of dealers to the
British pound, which was boosted by a pledge Sunday from Chancellor
of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson to keep interest rates high to curb
inflation.
   In London, the pound rose to $1.7130 from $1.6985 late Friday.
Later in New York, the pound rose to $1.7127 from $1.6980 late
Friday.
   Japan's financial markets were closed for a national holiday. In
London, the dollar was quoted at 132.45 yen. Later in New York, the
dollar fell to 132.18 yen from 133.37 late Friday. In Tokyo on
Friday, the dollar closed at 133.50 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8545 West German marks, down from 1.8629; 1.5745
Swiss francs, down from 1.5812; 1.2070 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2085; and 6.3180 French francs, down from 6.3460.
   No quote was available from Telerate Inc. on the Italian lira,
which closed Friday at 1,388.50 to the dollar.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8550 West German marks, down from 1.8608; 1.5755
Swiss francs, down from 1.5795; 6.3213 French francs, down from
6.3420; 2.0907 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0988; 1,383.26 Italian
lire, down from 1,387.50; and 1.2070 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2116.
   Higher oil prices pushed up gold by raising fears of inflation.
   In Hong Kong, gold bullion rose $3.28 a troy ounce to close at a
bid $409.34 an ounce.
   Gold climbed in London to a late bid price of $407.25 per troy
ounce, compared with late Friday's $403.05. In Zurich, gold rose to
close at a bid $407.00 compared with $404.25 late Friday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $408.60 a troy ounce from $403.20 an ounce Friday.
   Silver bullion prices rose moderately in London where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.37 per troy ounce, up from
Friday's $6.33. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery rose to $6.342 an ounce from $6.325 an ounce Friday.
</TEXT>
