<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 2005EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CocaCola     10-10 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coca Cola,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New President Named For Coca-Cola USA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coca-Cola Co. on Monday named Ira C. Herbert
president of its flagship division, Coca-Cola USA, in a move aimed
at increasing its advertising firepower in the cola wars.
   Herbert, executive vice president of the parent company, will
replace Edwin R. Mellett as president of both Coca-Cola USA and the
company's North America Business Sector.
   Mellett, a senior vice president of The Coca-Cola Co., will take
over the new job of president of international post-mix sales,
where he will be in charge of fountain sales outside the United
States.
   ``We are convinced that the key factor to success in the decade
ahead will be the ability to serve, excite and communicate with the
consumer in cooperation with our bottlers and the retail trade,''
said Donald R. Keough, president of The Coca-Cola Co.
   He called Herbert ``our most experienced and senior marketing
executive.''
   PepsiCo Inc., Coca-Cola's chief rival in the soft drink market,
has staged splashy advertising campaigns this year linked to the
America's Cup race and heavyweight boxing, while Coca-Cola's
advertising has been more conventional.
   Emanuel Goldman, a beverage industry analyst for PaineWebber in
San Francisco, said Coca-Cola has not necessarily been upstaged by
the Pepsi campaigns, but he said Herbert's appointment may indicate
a concern about marketing among the company's top management.
   ``You can't really be sure, but I would say the fact that it's
Ike Herbert and not somebody else says something,'' Goldman said.
   Herbert worked for the McCann-Erickson advertising agency before
joining Coca-Cola in 1965. He later was vice president of marketing
for Coca-Cola USA and president and chief executive officer of
Coca-Cola Foods. He became chief operating officer of the parent
company in 1982.
   ``He has a history of doing things well,'' Goldman said.
   Asked if marketing had become a chink in Coca-Cola's armor,
Goldman said, ``We should have all such chinks in our armor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
