<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ElectricBoat     10-10 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Electric Boat,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Striking Electric Boat Workers to Vote on New Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking shipyard workers at the Electric
Boat Division of General Dynamics Corp. prepared Monday to vote on
a tentative 4-year contract similar to one rejected two months ago
by union negotiators.
   Joseph Messier, president of the striking Metal Trades Council,
said there were a number of recent developments in the 14-week
strike that put pressure on negotiators to get some 10,000 strikers
back to work.
   ``Not only did we have a (National Labor Relations Board)
complaint to deal with, but we got the Boilermakers International
cutting off their strike benefits, and it just caused a big
problem,'' said Messier, whose Metal Trades Council is an umbrella
organization for 10 unions at Electric Boat.
   ``And people started getting worried about the loss of their
jobs and some of them being finally unable to cope anymore. So, we
were under a lot of pressure to get it settled,'' Messier said.
   Electric Boat, which builds submarines, is a division of St.
Louis-based General Dynamics, a major defense contractor.
   Due to the Columbus Day holiday, Electric Boat was closed Monday
and company officials couldn't be reached for comment.
   A ratification vote on the proposed contract was to be conducted
from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m. Tuesday at the Groton City Municipal
Building, and Messier said he expected the contract to be approved.
   The proposed contract, reached Saturday evening after four days
of negotiations in Washington, D.C., and Connecticut, calls for a 3
percent pay increase and bonuses averaging about $2,250, plus
increased costs to workers for health insurance.
   Before walking off the job July 1, workers had rejected the idea
of lump-sum bonuses in lieu of wage increases. They had insisted on
a 3-year contract with a 5 percent raise in the first year, and 4
percent raises in each of the next two years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
