<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-GE     10-10 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-GE,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE Earnings Rise 16 Percent in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. said Monday that
its third-quarter profit rose 16 percent mainly as a result of
improved performances in its plastics, financial services and
medical systems divisions.
   The Fairfield-based company said net income for the quarter
ended Sept. 30 totaled $815 million, or 90 cents per share,
compared with $703 million, or 77 cents a share in the year-ago
period.
   As required, GE's 1987 quarterly earnings were restated to
reflect the adoption of new accounting rules. Third-quarter 1988
earnings are up 23 percent over the restated 1987 earnings of $661
million, or 73 cents a share.
   Sales for the third quarter totaled $9.31 billion, down 1
percent from $9.40 billion a year ago.
   However, GE said, adjusting for all acquisitions and
divestitures in 1987, sales for the current quarter were up 7
percent from last year's comparable period.
   The company noted that plastics led the increase in operating
profits in the materials division. Major appliance revenues were up
reflecting the acquisition of Roper Corp., but operating profits
were down because of higher materials costs and competitive pricing
pressures.
   The parent of National Broadcasting Co., GE noted that
broadcasting revenues were up but operating profit slipped because
of increased costs associated with covering the Olympics and the
two major political conventions.
   Chairman John F. Welch Jr. said that while ``improvements were
led by plastics, financial services and medical systems, ... there
were also widespread margin improvements throughout the rest of the
company.''
   For the first nine months, net income totaled $2.38 billion, or
$2.63 a share, up 16 percent from $2.05 billion, or $2.24 a share
in the year-ago period.
   Nine-month revenue totaled $26.53 billion, down 3 percent from
$27.28 billion a year ago but up 4 percent when adjusted for
acquisitions and divestitures.
   GE is a diversified manufacturing services and technology
company. Its products include plastics, medical diagnostic
equipment, aircraft engine and radar equipment, major appliances
and power generation equipment.
</TEXT>
