<DOCNO> AP881010-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 2315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Obit-Bass     10-10 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Obit-Bass,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Dow Corning Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shailer L. Bass, a former board chairman
and chief executive officer of Dow Corning Corp., has died at age
82.
   Bass, who died Sunday at Provincial House Midland following a
lengthy illness, joined Dow Chemical Co. in 1936 and served as
research director on cellulose ethers and other compounds.
   He is credited with developing the first commercial silicone
product, a substance used to protect aircraft ignition systems.
Bass was active in the founding of Dow Corning and served as its
director of research.
   Bass was elected vice president and assistant general manager of
Dow Corning in 1954 and executive vice president in 1960. Seven
years later he became president, chief executive officer and board
chairman. He retired in April 1971.
   Bass is survived by his wife, Elizabeth, and seven children.
   Funeral services tentatively were set for Saturday in Midland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
