<DOCNO> AP881010-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 2316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f AM-Obit-Craig     10-10 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Craig,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Union Chairman Ben T. Craig</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ben T. Craig, president of First Union
Corp., died Monday of cancer, the banking company announced. He was
55.
   Craig, a Gastonia native and graduate of Davidson College, died
at his Charlotte home, said First Union spokesman Marshall Hester.
   Craig was chairman and chief executive officer of Northwestern
Financial Corp. until 1985, when the Greensboro-based company
merged with First Union. After the merger, Craig became president
of First Union Corp. and chairman and chief executive officer of
First Union National Bank of North Carolina.
   ``Ben Craig's contributions to First Union and the banking
industry were incalculable,'' said Edward E. Crutchfield Jr., First
Union Corp. chairman and chief executive officer. ``He was a valued
colleague and a great friend, and we will all miss him.''
   Craig began his banking career in 1954 as an assistant vice
president for finance for Wachovia Bank & Trust Co. In 1963, he
became executive vice president and director of finance and
administration at The Bank of Lancaster in Lancaster, S.C. Four
years later he became treasurer of Springs Mills, Inc., of Fort
Mill, S.C., and in 1972 was named president of American Bank and
Trust Company of Reading, Pa.
   He became chairman of Northwestern in 1978. Under his leadership
the company doubled its assets in seven years, to $2.9 billion at
the time of its merger with First Union, a $28.4 billion bank
holding company that operates largely in the Southeast.
   Graveside services Craig were scheduled for p.m. Tuesday in
Davidson, and a memorial service was scheduled for Wednesday in
Charlotte.
</TEXT>
