<DOCNO> AP881010-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-10-88 2316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Philips-Kloster     10-10 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Philips-Kloster,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Executive To Become President Of North American Philips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Einar Kloster, chairman of Kloster Cruise Ltd., the
parent company of Norwegian Cruise Lines and Royal Viking Line,
said Monday he will become president of the electronics
conglomerate North American Philips starting Jan. 1.
   Kloster said he intends to remain chairman of Kloster Cruise and
make strategic decisions for the Miami-based company. Trygve
Hegnar, recently appointed as president and chief executive, will
handle day-to-day operations.
   Before taking over the cruise business in 1986, Kloster spent 25
years in executive positons at Philips's Netherlands-based parent,
which employs 340,000 worldwide and recorded $27 billion in sales
last year.
   North American Philips is a wholly owned subsidiary with 55,000
employees and $5.5 billion in annual sales.
   During his two years in charge of the cruise lines, Kloster
consolidated management and cut costs by moving NCL's headquarters
from Oslo to Miami, reflagging the company's ships and hiring crew
members at lower wages from Third World countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
